@{"Quick Start" link QuickStart}
@endnode 
@node Require "Requirements" 
@toc GETTINGSTARTED

@{b}@{u}Requirements@{ub}@{uu}

The minimum requirements are an Amiga with OS 2.04 (37.175) and 1 MB RAM. 
Recommended configuration: Amiga with OS 3.x (39.x or higher), 68020 
Processor, 2 MB RAM and a hard disk. 

    Fiasco uses the gtlayout.library by Olaf Barthel for its GUI. Var 
string fields are implemented using the textfield.gadget  by Mark Thomas. 
The files are included in the archive of Fiasco. 

    Fiasco requires the @{b}ACTION_SET_FILE_SIZE@{ub} packet, which was introduced 
with Amiga OS 2.0. Both the 2.0 ROM filesystem and the 2.0 RAM handler 
support this packet, however, some handlers may not support it. Thus, you 
cannot save Fiasco projects to these handlers. Reading should be always 
possible. 

    Possibly also due to this, Fiasco does not work with Diskexpander and 
XFH. You are able to read databases, but saving does not work. If you use 
Diskexpander, errors will be produced. Take care if you use XFH: Saving a 
database to a XFH handler may crash the system. 

    The memory pool functions of Amiga OS 3.0 and Amiga OS 3.1 do not 
free unused puddles until the pool is deleted. Use SetPatch 40.16 
(already included in WB 40.42) to fix this. If you use Amiga OS 2.0 or 
Amiga OS 2.1 you do not have to worry about that. 


@{b}Features and required OS-Versions:@{ub}


Localization: 	 Amiga OS 2.1 (38.x) 
Screenmode-Requester: 	 Amiga OS 2.1 (38.x) 
Online-Help: 	 Amiga OS 3.0 (39.x) or amigaguide.library v34 
Datatypes-Fields: 	 Amiga OS 3.0 (39.x) 


@endnode 
@node Install "Installation" 
@toc GETTINGSTARTED

@{b}@{u}Installation@{ub}@{uu}

If you have the Installer program simply double-click on the install icon 
of your preferred language in the install drawer. You then will be given 
step-by-step instructions. 

    If you don't own the Installer, you may simply drag the Fiasco drawer 
somewhere you want. You may copy the catalogs to locale:catalogs, but 
they will work at this place, too. You may delete the unused languages in 
"Documentation" and drag the remaining files in the parent drawers. The 
files in "Development" and "Install" are not required for normal 
operation of Fiasco and may be deleted, too. With this configuration, 
Fiasco will run. If you have a 68020 processor or better, you should 
delete the file gtlayout.library in the main directory of Fiasco. Then, 
you should copy the gtlayout.library from the directory @{b}libs/68020@{ub} into 
the main directory. If you want to make the gtlayout.library accessible 
for all programs, you should copy it into the @{b}libs:@{ub} directory. 

@endnode 
@node RunningFiasco "Starting Fiasco" 
@toc GETTINGSTARTED

@{b}@{u}Starting Fiasco@{ub}@{uu}

You can start Fiasco from Workbench or Shell. The simplest way to start 
Fiasco from Workbench is to double click on the Fiasco icon. From shell, 
you have to change the directory to Fiasco's directory and then type 
@{b}Fiasco@{ub}. These startup arguments are supported by Fiasco:  

    
@{b}From:@{ub} The databases to be loaded on startup. You may specify several 
   databases. Only supported from shell. If started from Workbench, there 
   is a different scheme: If Fiasco was started using a project icon of a 
   Fiasco database, Fiasco will load the database of the icon on startup. 
   You may also select multiple project icons and start Fiasco with the 
   program icon. In that case, Fiasco will load all selected projects. 

@{b}Config:@{ub} After this keyword you may specify a Fiasco configuration file to 
   be used by Fiasco. Default: @{b}env:fiasco.prefs@{ub}. Example: 
   @{b}CONFIG=env:fiasco_24bit.prefs@{ub}. Supported both as shell argument and as 
   Workbench tool type. 

@{b}Iconfied:@{ub} If you specify @{b}ICONIFIED@{ub}, Fiasco will not open its GUI but 
   start in iconified state. If the Workbench is running, an Fiasco 
   AppIcon will be displayed on it, with which you may open Fiasco's GUI. 
   You may also start Fiasco again or use the @{"ARexx port" link ARexx} to open the GUI. 
   Supported both as shell argument and as Workbench tool type. New in 
   Fiasco 2.2. 

 Before you start Fiasco, you have to ensure, that Fiasco has enough 
stack. For now, 8192 Bytes is a good value. When you start Fiasco from 
Workbench, you can set the stack size in the information requester for 
Fiasco's program icon or the project icons. In a shell, you have to use 
the @{b}Stack@{ub} command to increase the stack. 

    If you try to start Fiasco, while it is already running, Fiasco will 
recognize itself and not start again. If you have specified databases to 
be opened by Fiasco when you have started it the second time, these will 
be opened by the already running Fiasco process. If you have not 
specified any databases, Fiasco will open a new window. 

@endnode 
@node Quickstart "Quick Start" 
@toc GETTINGSTARTED

@{b}@{u}Quick Start@{ub}@{uu}

These are the most important things, which you have to know while working 
with Fiasco: 

·  The program may be started over the program or project icon 

·  There are two working-modes: In the record mode you may edit records, 
   search for them etc. The mask mode allows you to add or modify fields. 
   You may control the modes using the menuitems @{b}@{"Control/Record Mode" link MnRecordMode}@{ub} and @{b}
   @{"Control/Mask Mode" link MnMaskMode}@{ub} 

·  The @{"service window" link ServiceWin} makes certain operations easier, especially if you 
   are not familiar with menu shortcuts. You may open it over @{b}
   @{"Control/Service Window" link MnServiceWindow}@{ub}. @{i}Attention: @{ui}The functions of the gadgets differ 
   in the different modes. 

·  A @{"list" link List}, which can be opened with @{b}@{"Control/List Window" link MnListWindow}@{ub}, may be changed 
   by clicking in the titles of the list. Clicking one time on a column 
   title activates the respective column. Using the menu @{b}List@{ub} you can now 
   do several things with this column. If you click at the right border 
   of a title, you can change the size of the column. The other space can 
   be used to drag the column to any other place in the list. 

·  Certain project options may be changed with the menuitem @{b}
   @{"Database/Options" link MnOptions}@{ub} 

·  The sort and filter functions use indices. When you sort or filter a 
   database, a new index is created and activated. To activate the old 
   index again, use the menu item @{b}@{"Database/Previous active index" link mnpreviousactiveindex}@{ub}. You 
   have complete control over the indices with the menu item @{b}
   @{"Database/Indices" link mnindices}@{ub}.  

·  @{b}Record/Delete Record@{ub} only removes the record from the index. To get 
   finally rid of it, you have to call @{b}@{"Datenbank/Reorganize" link mnreorganize}.@{ub}  

·  If you have any problems, you may press the help key while browsing 
   through the menu. 



@endnode 
@node DATABASEELEMENTS "Basic elements of a Database" 
@toc main

@{b}@{u}Basic elements of a Database@{ub}@{uu}

Basically, most databases are analogous to a card file. A Fiasco database 
project consists of two components: First, there is the data which is 
divided into records. Second, there is the mask which defines the 
structure of the data. 

    The following pages describe the basics of databases in general and 
the basic Fiasco-specific principles. 

@{"Records" link Records} 
@{"Indices" link Indices} 
@{"Fields" link Fields} 
@{"Mask" link Mask } 
@{"List" link List } 
@endnode 


@node Records "Records" 
@toc DATABASEELEMENTS

@{b}@{u}Records@{ub}@{uu}

Records  are the file cards  of a database. That means a record is a 
collection of several data items for one main item (e.g. for a person 
name, address, etc.). In Fiasco the @{"mask" link Mask} is only able to display one 
record at a time. The @{"list" link List} displays several records as lines. @{"Indices" link Indices} 
give you more control over records. One database may have several 
indices. Each index determines, which record is actually displayed, and 
how the records are ordered. Thus, a database may contain records, which 
are not visible, because they are not in the active index. 

@endnode 
@node Indices "Indices" 
@toc DATABASEELEMENTS

@{b}@{u}Indices@{ub}@{uu}

Indices are new for Fiasco 2.0. Indices are used to control the order of 
the records and whether a record is actually displayed or not. There may 
be several indices per database. 

    If you imagine the records as file cards, indices are additional 
lists which say "File card 16 is at position 1, file card 5 at position 
2", etc. The so-called record numbers used by Fiasco are actually the 
positions of the index entries. Thus, with each additional index, the 
record number of a particular record may change. 

    The new @{"sort" Link RqSort} and @{"filter" Link Filter} functions also use indices. These functions 
simply create a new index which is sorted or filtered as wanted. 
Furthermore, Fiasco allows you to automatically keep an index sorted or 
filtered. 

    Normally, records are only added to the active index. If you want, 
that another index also gets the new record, you will have to activate 
the option @{b}Automatically add new Records@{ub} in the @{"Edit Index requester" Link RqIndex}. 

    More information on indices can be found in the section @{"Using Indices" link UsingIndices}
.   
@endnode 


@node Fields "Fields" 
@toc DATABASEELEMENTS

@{b}@{u}Fields@{ub}@{uu}

Fields define what data may be stored. In Fiasco the fields are defined 
in the mask. Fields are the basic elements of the mask and the list. 
Fiasco supports several types of fields. More information on the field 
types and their features are located in the @{"field types" link Fieldtypes} chapter. 

@endnode 
@node Mask "Mask" 
@toc DATABASEELEMENTS

@{b}@{u}Mask@{ub}@{uu}

The mask is the way to display data, which Fiasco uses most of the time. 
A mask, in contrast to a @{"list" link list}, can display only one record. The advantage 
of the mask is the clarity of the display. In the card file example, the 
mask defines the structure of the file cards.  The mask consists of 
fields of which there are several types and images. 

    If you use normal Amiga programs, you would call these fields 
"gadgets".  

    Internally, Fiasco uses gadgets as fields, which optically conform to 
the GadTools standard. 

    Fiasco masks adjust automatically to any non-proportional font. Topaz 
and courier are examples of non-proportional fonts.  

    To create a mask in Fiasco you have to be in the mask mode. You may 
change the position of existing fields using the mouse or make other 
changes with the @{b}Field@{ub} menu.  More on this topic @{"here" link MaskCreation}. 

    See the @{"mask window section" link MaskWindow} for more information about the user 
interface features of the mask window.  

@endnode 
@node List "List" 
@toc DATABASEELEMENTS

@{b}@{u}List@{ub}@{uu}

Opposed to the mask, a list can display several records at once. In a 
list, the records are represented by lines, while the fields of a record 
are represented by columns. Thus, there is much less space for one record 
in a list and the layout of a list is much more restricted than the 
layout of a mask. On the other hand, the list can be used to get a quick 
overview of all records in the database or the active index, 
respectively.  See the section @{"list window" link ListWindow}   for a detailed explanation 
of the specific features of Fiasco's list window. 

@endnode 
@node EditingModes "Editing Modes in Fiasco" 
@toc DATABASEELEMENTS

@{b}@{u}Editing Modes in Fiasco@{ub}@{uu}

Fiasco divides it's operation into modes. If you want to make changes in 
the mask, you have to be in the mask mode. If you want to make changes in 
the records, you have to be in the record mode. 

@{"Record Mode" link recordmode}
@{"Mask Mode" link maskmode}  

    The section @{"Mask Window" link MaskWindow}   contains descriptions of the features of 
the mask window in both modes. 
@endnode 
@node recordmode "Record Mode" 
@toc EditingModes

@{b}@{u}Record Mode@{ub}@{uu}

You may add, delete or edit records in this mode. It may be activated 
with @{b}@{"Control/Record Mode" link MnRecordMode}@{ub}. When the record mode is active, "tape deck" 
gadgets are shown in the service windowthe status gadget displays 
normally the  number of the active record and the number of all records 
(for instance: @{b}78 / 92@{ub}). 

@endnode 
@node maskmode "Mask Mode" 
@toc EditingModes

@{b}@{u}Mask Mode@{ub}@{uu}

This mode give you the ability to edit the mask, that is, you may create 
new fields, delete some or change their position or attributes. Relations 
may also created and changed here. This mode may be activated with @{b}
@{"Control/Mask Mode" link MnMaskMode}@{ub}. When the mask mode is active a field type cycle gadget 
in shown in the service window  and the status gadget displays normally 
the coordinates of the cursor in the mask (for instance: @{b} X: 10, Y: 5@{ub}). 
@endnode 
@node DATABASECREATION "Simple Usage of Fiasco Databases"  
@toc main

@{b}@{u}Simple Usage of Fiasco Databases@{ub}@{uu}

And now to actual use: If you want to create a database in Fiasco you 
will have to create the mask at first and then the records. Fiasco allows 
you in most aspects to create a database in an intuitive way. 

@{"Working in the Mask" link MaskCreation} 
@{"Working with Records" link RecordCreation} 
@endnode 


@node MaskCreation "Working in the Mask" 
@toc DATABASECREATION

@{b}@{u}Working in the Mask@{ub}@{uu}

You have to activate the mask mode before you can create a mask (@{b}
@{"Control/Mask Mode" link MnMaskMode}@{ub}), whereupon a cursor will appear in the mask. You can 
use the mouse or the cursor keys to choose the location of the next 
operation in the mask. Before creating a new field you have to choose the 
type of the new field. You can use either the @{b}Field/Type@{ub} @{"menu" link AllMenus} or the 
cycle gadget in the service window to choose the field type. 

    You then may use @{b}@{"Field/Add Field" link MnAddField}@{ub} to create a new field. This will 
open the @{"field requester" link RqEditField}. The gadgets in the requester depend on the 
supported attributes of the active field type. They are described in the 
@{"type documentation" link FieldTypes} for each field. It is not sufficient to click on @{b}Ok@{ub} 
without any other action; you must specify certain attributes, such as 
the ID. Fiasco won't close the requester if it contains any invalid 
settings. The field will appear in the mask after you close the 
requester. 

    You may change all attributes later except the fieldtype (Fiasco 
provides another function for that). A field's position may be changed by 
dragging it with the mouse. You may cancel dragging while you are 
dragging still it by pressing the right mouse button. You may also select 
several fields by pressing @{b}Shift@{ub} while selecting the fields. The fields 
will be deselected when you select a field without @{b}Shift@{ub}. 

    The field requester may be opened by double clicking on the field or 
by choosing @{b}@{"Field/Edit active Field" link MnEditField}@{ub} after you have activated the field to 
edit. The menuitem @{b}@{"Field/Edit named Field" link MnEditNamedField}@{ub} displays a list of all fields. 
When you have selected one field, @{b}Edit named Field@{ub} will open the field 
requester for the selected field. This is useful for editing hidden 
fields. You should take care if you want to change the field ID. Other 
Fiasco projects or ARexx scripts which try to access this field won`t 
find it after the change. If you change the value @{b}max chars@{ub} of string, 
extern or datatypes fields, you will be informed that you could loose 
data. 

    @{b}@{"Field/Delete Field" link MnRemoveField}@{ub} allows you to delete Fields. @{i}Attention: @{ui}If 
@{b}Security-Requester@{ub} in the user interface settings is not active, all data 
in this field will be freed immediately. Any existing data on disk will 
be also erased when the project is saved. If the field is used by any 
other Fiasco system, such as indices or formulas, you will be warned 
before deleting that field regardless of the @{b}Security-Requester@{ub} setting. 

    You may specify further parameters for the current project, such as 
@{"mask stretching" link Stretch}, name of the author, etc. in the @{"options requester" link RqOptions}. 

    You may also @{"group" link groups} certain fields. If a grouped field is activated, 
all other fields in the group will be also activated. Furthermore, 
certain field types, such as the bar and the listview types, may share 
their visual display when they are grouped.  

    @{b}@{"Field/Edit Relations" link MnEditRelations}@{ub} works similarly to @{b}@{"Edit Field" link MnEditField}@{ub}. With this 
menuitem you are able to control @{"relations" link relations} of this field.  

    When you have completed the mask you may return to record mode. You 
are now ready to create records. 

@endnode 
@node RecordCreation "Working with Records" 
@toc DATABASECREATION

@{b}@{u}Working with Records@{ub}@{uu}

You may create records for data storage in any mask containing fields. 
The simplest way to create a record is to select @{b}@{"Record/Add Record" link MnAddRecord}@{ub} or its 
equivalent @{b}Add@{ub} in the service window. This creates, as the name implies, 
a record and activates it. The fields in the record will contain the 
values that have been assigned in the mask mode. You may now activate a 
field using the mouse and edit its contents. @{b}@{"Record/Duplicate Record" link MnDupRecord}@{ub} 
provides another way of creating records. This function creates a record, 
which is an exact clone of the record, which was previously active. All 
init cont-attributes will be ignored.  

    You may also cut or copy a record and paste it at another position. 
Please note that cutting and pasting is just like deleting and creating a 
new record, not just moving. Thus, if other @{"indices" Link Indices} use the record, which 
you have cut, the contents of the record will remain constant, even if 
you paste the record somewhere else and edit it. 

    If you no longer need a record you may delete it using @{b}
@{"Record/Delete Record" link MnRemoveRecord}@{ub} or @{b}Delete@{ub} in the service window. If you have 
selected @{b}Security-Requesters@{ub} in the user interface settings, you will be 
asked for confirmation before the record is deleted.  

    Please note that only the entry in the active index is deleted. The 
data of the records will remain in the database. To get rid of it 
permanently, you will have to use @{b}@{"Database/Reorganize" link MnReorgProject}@{ub}. 

    You may use the menu, the service window, the cursor keys or a list 
window to view the records you have created.  I believe that the use of 
GUI is intuitive, therefore, I will only explain the cursor keys. The 
up-key activates the previous record. The down-key activates the next 
record. The order corresponds to the concept of a list window. The cursor 
keys combined with the @{b}Ctrl@{ub} key activate the first or the last record 
respectively. 

@endnode 
@node ADVANCEDUSAGE "Advanced Usage of Fiasco Databases" 
@toc main

@{b}@{u}Advanced Usage of Fiasco Databases@{ub}@{uu}

The information described in this chapter is not necessary to work with 
Fiasco. However, it often may be helpful. 

@{"Converting Fields" link ConvertingFields}
@{"Groups" link Groups}
@{"Using Indices" link UsingIndices}
@{"Using Marks" link UsingMarks}
@{"Relations" link Relations}
@{"Virtual Fields" link VirtFields}  
@endnode 


@node ConvertingFields "Converting Fields" 
@toc ADVANCEDUSAGE

@{b}@{u}Converting Fields@{ub}@{uu}

As your project develops you may decide that you want to change one or 
more of the field types. For instance, the contents of a field may have 
developed in a direction other than the one you originally intended. In 
that case, the convert function will be useful. This function is also 
helpful if you have imported a file. After a file is imported all fields 
are string fields. You must be in mask mode to open the convert 
requester. Activate the field you want to convert and select 
@{b}Field/Convert Field@{ub}. The convert requester displays the ID of the field, 
the current field type and the field types to which this field may be 
converted. If you select @{b}Alternative format@{ub}, the convert function may 
convert the data to another, often more abstract format. Not all field 
types support this option. If you select the the new type and proceed 
with @{b}Ok@{ub}, the field will be converted. Note that Fiasco will not warn 
about the possible loss of data. If the new field type requires 
additional attributes (e.g., the extern fieldtype needs a program), the 
field requester will open. Other attributes will use default values. If 
you convert a field and then convert it back to its original type it 
won't retain the original attributes. 

    If a field is used by relations, formulas or indices (for sorting or 
filtering), these uses will be removed. You will be warned before that is 
done. 

    Information about the results of a field type conversion can be found 
in the @{"field documentation" link Fieldtypes}. Text, button and bar fields cannot be 
converted. In other cases, converting from one field type to another does 
not make much sense (e.g., boolean to datatypes). 

    If you convert a listview field to a non-listview field or 
vice-versa, the character `|' will be used to separate the entries of the 
listview. 

@endnode 
@node Groups "Groups" 
@toc ADVANCEDUSAGE

@{b}@{u}Groups@{ub}@{uu}

Generally, a Fiasco group is a group of fields, which have been selected 
by the user. This only sounds less than useful. The advantages of groups 
are the additional characteristics grouped fields have. First: In mask 
mode grouped fields stick together. That means, if you select one grouped 
field, the whole group will be selected. Thus, if you want to drag a 
grouped field, the whole group will be dragged. All other functions which 
affect all selected fields will also affect the whole group. The second 
advantage of groups is the joined display (and function) of grouped 
fields. Some fieldtypes share their images with other fields next to them 
in the group. This is supported by these fieldtypes: 

    
·  @{"Bar fields" Link ft_Bar} 

·  @{"Listview fields" Link ft_lv} 

How these fields share their images is described in the 
@{"field type documentation" link Fieldtypes}. 

    To create a group, select all fields to be in the group and call @{b}
@{"Field/Create Group" link MnCreateGroup}@{ub}. To resolve a group, select it and call @{b}
@{"Field/Resolve Group" link MnResolveGroup}@{ub}. 

    If you try to group an already existent group with other fields or 
other groups,  you will get a new big group of all selected fields. 
Resolving that group will resolve all groups, which have been grouped in 
the group. Thus, all fields in the group will get free. 

@endnode 
@node UsingIndices "Using Indices" 
@toc ADVANCEDUSAGE

@{b}@{u}Using Indices@{ub}@{uu}

The concept and simple use of indices is described in the sections @{"Indices" link Indices}
 and @{"Filters" link Filter}.   However, the index system is much more powerful. It 
allows you to automatically sort, filter and update indices. The GUI of 
the index system is the @{"index requester" link RqIndex}, which can be opened using @{b}
@{"Project/Indices" link MnIndices}@{ub}. You can activate an index here by selecting it and 
clicking on @{b}Ok@{ub}. You can also create new indices and edit or delete 
existing ones. 

    There may be no indices before the database has been saved or if the 
database is in Fiasco 1.x format. A standard index will be created when 
the database is saved the first time. 


@{b}Creating a new Index@{ub}

When you create a new index using the @{b}New@{ub} button the @{"new index requester" Link RqIndex} 
will open. 

    The topmost gadget takes a name for the index. 

    The checkbox @{b}Automatically add new Records@{ub} controls whether you want 
Fiasco to automatically add new records to the index. If the checkbox is 
not active, records that have been added to the database while another 
index was active will not be added to this index. If the checkbox is 
active, Fiasco will automatically add the records to the index, which 
have been added to the database, while another index was active. If the 
sort option (see below) is active, the new record will be automatically 
sorted in the index. If the filter option (also see below) is active, it 
will be tested using the filter and only added if it matches the filter. 

    Click on the appropriate buttons to edit a filter for the index or 
the sorting. The sorting and filtering functions will be activated only 
if you have selected the checkboxes beneath the buttons. Sorting will be 
always automatically done when you change or add a record. The filter 
will be used only during the initial creation of the index and when a 
record has been added in another index and @{b}Automatically add new Records@{ub} 
is active. The filter will @{i}not@{ui} be used when a record is added while the 
index is active or when a record is changed. 

    The listview gadget allows you to select an existing index as the 
model for the new index. Only records that are in the selected index will 
be examined for the new index. If you do not use sorting, the order of 
the records will be carried over. If you use neither sorting nor 
filtering, a copy of the selected index will be created. By selecting an 
index, which already uses a filter, you can create a filter, which uses 
several conditions logically combined with "and". The special entry @{b}«No 
Index»@{ub} corresponds to all records in the database, even those not used in 
any index. 

    The new index will be created after you have exited both the new 
index requester and the index requester with the @{b}Ok@{ub} gadgets. 


@{b}Editing an Index@{ub}

When you @{b}Edit@{ub} an index, the @{"edit index requester" link RqIndex} will appear. This is the 
new index requester without the index name and listview gadgets. You may 
change filtering, sorting or the @{b}Automatically add new Records@{ub} option. 
The changes will be executed after you have exited both requesters with 
@{b}Ok@{ub}. 


@{b}Deleting an Index@{ub}

The @{b}Delete@{ub} gadget removes the selected index. However, you cannot remove 
the last index; Fiasco requires at least one index. 

@endnode 
@node indexhistory "The Index History" 
@toc UsingIndices

@{b}@{u}The Index History@{ub}@{uu}

The index history is a system that remembers the order in which indices 
are activated by the user. For example, if you create a new index with 
the filter function, this new index will be activated. However, Fiasco 
keeps track of the index that was active before this one. Thus, you can 
simply switch off the filter by going a step back in the index history. 
This can be done with the menuitem @{b}@{"Database/Previous active index" link mnpreviousactindex}@{ub}. To 
activate the filter again, you may use @{b}@{"Database/Next active index" link mnnextactindex}@{ub} to go 
that step forward again. 
@endnode 


@node UsingMarks "Using Marks" 
@toc ADVANCEDUSAGE

@{b}@{u}Using Marks@{ub}@{uu}

Marks can be useful in advanced database use. A mark is simply a record's 
flag that may be toggled on or off, that is, a record is either marked or 
unmarked. Marks could be simulated using boolean or other fields, but the 
marking feature of Fiasco provides some additional advantages over that 
approach. First of all, a marked record can be easily discovered in the 
list because it is displayed in a highlighted state. If a marked record 
is active an "M" will be displayed to the right of the service window's 
status gadget, therefore, marked records can only recognized in a mask if 
the service window is open. Marks can be set using @{b}@{"Record/Mark Record" link mnmarkrecord}@{ub} and 
cleared using @{b}@{"Record/Unmark Record" link mnunmarkrecord}@{ub}. Use @{b}@{"Record/Unmark all Records" link mnunmarkallrecords}@{ub} to 
clear all marks in a project. To set all marks, use @{b}
@{"Record/Mark all Records" link mnmarkallrecords}@{ub}. Use @{b}@{"Record/Toggle all Marks" link mntoggleallmarks}@{ub} to unmark all marked 
records and to mark all unmarked records. 

    @{b}@{"Compare/Mark" link mnmark}@{ub} opens a search requester that can be used to mark all 
records that match a given pattern. 

    Marks are saved with the record data and thus, they are independent 
from indices. 
@endnode 


@node Relations "Relations" 
@toc ADVANCEDUSAGE

@{b}@{u}Relations@{ub}@{uu}

Relations are fields that store their contents in another database rather 
than in the database of the relations. An additional field is required 
that contains a key used to identify the record from which the data 
should be taken.  

    This mechanism prevents the situation, that in many different 
projects the same data are stored; it therefore saves disk space. 
Furthermore, you only have to change the contents of one field in one of 
the databases -- all other corresponding fields will also recognize that 
change. 

    Using Fiasco, you have define relations in the database, which will 
actually read the data from another database. The database, in which you 
have defined the relations will be referenced with the word "local" in 
this document. The database from which the data are read, will be called 
"remote".    

@{"Relation Types" link RelTypes}
@{"Creating Relations" link CreatingRelations}
@{"Relation checklist" link RelChecklist}


@endnode 
@node reltypes "Relation Types" 
@toc Relations

@{b}@{u}Relation Types@{ub}@{uu}

Fiasco supports these relation types: 

@{b}1:N@{ub}



    This is the simplest relation type. A 1:N relation reads the data of 
any fieldtype in the remote database using a key, which has to be of a 
simple type, i.e. it must not be a listview type. In the remote database, 
the key has to be unique. The read data are directly copied into the 
appropriate field in the local database. 


@{b}N:Sum@{ub}

This is not really a relation, because the data cannot be written back. A 
N:Sum relation reads the data of simple fieldtypes and tries to calculate 
the sum of all fields in the records with matching keys. Thus, the key 
needs not to be unique in the remote database. 


@{b}N:L@{ub}

A N:L relation reads the the data of simple fieldtypes in the remote 
database. For each record in the remote database, in which a matching key 
is found, Fiasco will add an entry in the local listview field, and copy 
the data into it. Thus, the key needs not to be unique in the remote 
database. 


@{b}1:L@{ub}

A 1:L relation is the only relation type, which requires the local key in 
a listview field. The remote key has to be in field of simple type, 
though. This type is very similar to the 1:N type, however, you may 
specify several local keys using the capabilities of the 
@{"listview field type" Link FT_LV}. Fiasco will search the real data in the remote 
database for each key in the listview and create entries in the local 
real data listview with the found data. Because there is no thing like a 
listview in a listview, the remote real data has to be simple. 


@{b}Only Read@{ub}

@{b}Only Read@{ub} is a modifier, that can be applied to the relation types @{i}1:N@{ui} 
and @{i}1:L@{ui}. If @{b}Only Read@{ub} is active, the relation system is only used to 
enhance editing possibilities. Thus, you can copy data from a remote 
database using an unique key. However, the data are stored in the file of 
the local database and are not kept any longer up-to-date according to 
the remote database. 

@endnode 
@node creatingrelations "Creating Relations" 
@toc Relations

@{b}@{u}Creating Relations@{ub}@{uu}

This section describes creating of relations in Fiasco databases. It was 
originally written to describe the creation of relations of the type 1:N. 
However, you can also create the other relation types according to these 
instructions when you also keep the conditions for the relation types 
described in the previous section in mind. To use relations in Fiasco you 
have to create a project, which will be the data source for another 
project. You have to create at least two fields in the remote project, 
one for the data and one for the key. The field for the key should be an 
integer field. This is the fastest method. However, it is possible to use 
any other field type as a keys. 

    You may use the special field attribute @{b}Unique Key@{ub}, if you want to 
automatically get an unique key whenever you create a new record. Note 
that the key is only created when you create a new record. If you 
activate this attribute later the already existing entries will keep 
their old value. If you change the contents of such a field the change 
will occur without any checking. 

    It is up to you to choose the type of the second field. If you create 
fields, which store strings of a designated length (string, extern and 
datatypes), you should remember the @{b}Max Chars@{ub} value because you also have 
to use this same value in the second project. 

    If you want to see any consequences of activating the relation, you 
should create a few records with some content at first. 

    Now it is time to save the project and create a new one. 

    The second project also must contain two fields that have to match in 
typeMax CharsThe key field 
should @{i}not@{ui} use @{b}unique key@{ub}, because you should freely decide which key you 
want to use. 

    Before you activate the relation the project should be saved in the 
directory in which the other project has been saved in order to be able 
to use relative rather than absolute paths. 

    Now you can open the @{"relation requester" link RqRel} for the field that is @{i}not @{ui} 
supposed to contain the key, but the real data (@{b}@{"Field/Edit Relations" link MnEditRelations}@{ub}). 
Set the relation type in the topmost cycle gadget. To start, you should 
select the local key in the listview in the upper left edge of the 
window. After that you should select the other project with the file 
requester gadget at the bottom of the requester. Now you can select the 
remote key and real fields. Proceed with @{b}Ok@{ub}. If everything works 
correctly the requester will be closed and the relations will be loaded. 
Otherwise, a requester will inform you of any failure. 

    A @{"relation checklist" link RelChecklist}, which contains the information in a compressed 
form, is also available. 

@endnode 
@node VirtFields "Virtual Fields" 
@toc ADVANCEDUSAGE

@{b}@{u}Virtual Fields@{ub}@{uu}

The data of virtual fields are not saved on disk; their data are 
calculated while loading the project. If you want to make a field virtual 
you should activate the @{b}Virtual@{ub} option in the field requester. Fiasco 
uses the formula of a field for calculating these data. Whenever a record 
is read, the contents of the virtual fields in it are calculated using 
the formula. More about formulas can be found   @{"here" link formulas}.  

    It is also possible to use ARexx scripts for virtual fields. However, 
for speed and for technical reasons, the use of ARexx scripts for this 
purpose is discouraged. Therefore, this use is no longer documented. If 
you want to know more about ARexx and virtual fields, refer to the 
release 2.0x versions of this document. 

@endnode 
@node SEARCH "Searching in a Database" 
@toc main

@{b}@{u}Searching in a Database@{ub}@{uu}

Fiasco's search function allows you to search for specific data in a 
database. There are two ways to search for data: You may specify search 
patterns for one or more fields which must all match the field contents. 
Or you may specify a formula that can do complex investigations on the 
contents of a record. 

@{b}The Search Requester@{ub}

The main interface to the Fiasco search function is the search requester. 
It may be opened with the menu item @{b}@{"Compare/Find" link MnFind}@{ub}. Furthermore, the 
filter, count, replace and mark functions or menu items also use this 
requester. 

    To select, whether you want to search with specifications of field 
contents or with formulas, use the @{b}Mode@{ub} cycle gadget in the upper part of 
the requester. 

    If you use the field mode, the requester displays two listview 
gadgets: @{b}Fields@{ub} displays all the fields in the active database. Clicking 
on one of the fields causes it to be displayed in the listview with the 
title @{b}Search for@{ub}. Below it you can enter the search pattern for that 
field. To remove the field from that list, use the @{b}Delete@{ub} gadget. 

    If you search @{b}by Formula@{ub}, the window displays only one string gadget 
for the formula. The picker gadget of the right side can be used to open 
the @{"formula requester" Link RqEditFormula}. 

    The gadgets at the bottom of the requester start the search. The 
record will be displayed if a matching record is found. You can use the 
menu items @{b}@{"Compare/Find next" link MnFindNext}@{ub} and @{b}@{"Compare/Find previous" link MnFindPrevious}@{ub} to continue your 
search. 

    More about the search requester can be found   @{"here" link RqFind}.  


 @{"Searching by Fields" link SearchByFields}
   @{"Patterns" link SearchPatterns}
   @{"Wildcards" link SearchWildcards}
   @{"Wildcards for Numbers" link SearchNumberWild}
   @{"Blurred Search" link SearchBlurr}
 @{"Searching by Formulas" link SearchByFormula}

 @{"Search Informations" link SearchInfos}

 @{"Searching with ARexx" link ARexxSearch}

 @{"Count function" link Count}
 @{"Replace function" link Replace}
 @{"Filter function" link Filter}


 
@endnode 
@node SearchByFields "Searching by Fields" 
@toc SEARCH

@{b}@{u}Searching by Fields@{ub}@{uu}

If you use the search mode @{b}By Fields@{ub}, you must specify one or more fields 
to be examined. For each specified field, you have to specify a 
@{"search pattern" link searchpatterns}. Fiasco considers a record to be a match only if the field 
contents of all specified fields match the specified patterns. 

@endnode 
@node searchpatterns "Patterns" 
@toc SearchByFields

@{b}@{u}Patterns@{ub}@{uu}

Search patterns are the data that are compared to the field contents. For 
the individual field types there are different rules for pattern 
specification: 

@{b}String, Var String, Extern, Datatypes:@{ub} You have to specify the string 
   itself. Furthermore, you may use @{"wildcards" Link searchwildcards} and @{"blurred search" Link searchblurr}. 

@{b}Integer, Slider, Float:@{ub} You have to specify the number itself. 
   Furthermore, you may use @{"wildcards for numbers" Link searchnumberwild}. 

@{b}Boolean:@{ub} @{b}true@{ub} or @{b}1@{ub} specify a checked field, @{b}false@{ub} or @{b}0@{ub} specify an 
   unchecked field. 

@{b}Cycle:@{ub} You have to specify the label name to search for, or the number of 
   the label (counting from zero). 

@{b}Date, Time:@{ub} You have to specify the date or the time. 

The search requester has an additional feature that makes the 
specification of patterns for fields easier. With the picker gadget at 
the right side of the pattern string gadget, you may open a requester 
that displays a list of possible patterns for the field. If you chose one 
and click on @{b}Ok@{ub} it will be copied to the pattern gadget. The list of the 
possible values again depends on the field type: 

    
@{b}String, Integer, Float, Extern, Datat., Date, Time, Var String:@{ub} The 
   predefined values. 

@{b}Slider:@{ub} The maximum and minimum values for the slider. 

@{b}Boolean:@{ub} @{b}true@{ub} and @{b}false@{ub}. 

@{b}Cycle:@{ub} All labels of the cycle field. 

Please also note that you @{i}cannot@{ui} use the built-in search function to 
search for the contents of files that are specified in datatypes or 
extern fields. You can search for the file name only. 

    The patterns supported by one fieldtype are also documented in the 
@{"fieldtypes documentation" link FieldTypes}. 


 @{"Wildcards" link SearchWildcards}
 @{"Wildcards for Numbers" link SearchNumberWild}
 @{"Blurred Search" link SearchBlurr}



 
@endnode 
@node searchwildcards "Wildcards" 
@toc SearchByFields

@{b}@{u}Wildcards@{ub}@{uu}

In addition to plain patterns you may use wildcards. String, Var String, 
Extern and Datatypes fields support the use of wildcards as used by 
AmigaDOS. These wildcards are supported: 


@{b}?@{ub} 	 A single unknown character. 
@{b}#@{ub} 	 Matches the following expression zero or more times. 
@{b}(ab|cd)@{ub} 	 Matches any one of the items seperated by | .
@{b}~@{ub} 	 Negates the following expression.
@{b}[abc]@{ub} 	 Character class: matches any of the characters in the class.
@{b}[~bc]@{ub} 	 Matches any of the characters not in the class.
@{b}[a-z]@{ub} 	 Character range.
@{b}%@{ub} 	 Matches zero characters.
@{b}*@{ub} 	 Synonym for @{b}#?@{ub}. Must be turned on in the @{"database settings" link rqdatabasesettings}.  

 

    If you want to use the wildcard characters as normal characters in 
the string, you have to type a single quoute (') before the character to 
escape it.  

    If you use @{"blurred search" Link searchblurr}, only the patterns @{b}?@{ub} and @{b}#?@{ub} are available. 


@{b}Examples:@{ub}

@{b}?iasco@{ub} would match @{b}Aiasco@{ub}, @{b}Biasco@{ub}, @{b}Ciasco@{ub}, @{b}1iasco@{ub}, etc. @{b}????@{ub} would match 
entries, which are 4 characters long. @{b}#?@{ub} stands for an unknown number of 
unknown characters. @{b}A#?@{ub},  for example, would match @{b}Amiga@{ub}, @{b}Africa@{ub}, @{b}A@{ub} or 
@{b}ABCD@{ub}. @{b}?#?@{ub} searches for all non-empty entries. 

@endnode 
@node searchnumberwild "Wildcards for numbers" 
@toc SearchByFields

@{b}@{u}Wildcards for numbers@{ub}@{uu}

Integer, slider and float fields support the following wildcards: >, <, 
>=, <=, @{b}!=@{ub}. The argument has to be given after the wildcard. > only 
search for numbers greater than x, >= only for numbers greater or equal 
x, < only for numbers less than x, <= only for numbers less or equal x. 
@{b}!=@{ub} searches only for numbers not equal x. There is not a pattern like @{b}==@{ub} 
(equal), because this is represented by the number itself. 
@endnode 


@node searchblurr "Blurred Search" 
@toc SearchByFields

@{b}@{u}Blurred Search@{ub}@{uu}

"Blurred" search  allows you to search for entries that are similar to a 
pattern. This enables you to search for entries even if you don't know 
the exact spelling. The tolerance of the function may be set by "factor". 
0 matches only entries that are exactly equal. 100 matches nearly all 
entries. This feature can only be used with the field types that contain 
strings, i.e. string, var string, extern and datatypes fields. 

    If you use blurred search, only the patterns @{b}?@{ub} and @{b}#?@{ub} are available. 

    The @{"count function" link count} is very suitable for experiments with "blurred" 
search. 

@endnode 
@node SearchByFormula "Searching by Formulas" 
@toc SEARCH

@{b}@{u}Searching by Formulas@{ub}@{uu}

Even though the GUI for the search mode @{b}By Formula@{ub} looks simpler than the 
GUI of the other mode, this search mode is far more powerful. The formula 
specified in the string gadget will be used to examine each record. A 
record is considered matching whenever the formula results in a true 
value. In Fiasco formulas this is any non-zero value. More on Fiasco 
formulas can be found   in @{"this section" link formulas}.  


@{b}Examples:@{ub}

@{b}size > 5@{ub}
searches for all records in which the field @{b}size@{ub} has a value greater 
than 5. 

@{b}size >= 5 && size <= 10@{ub}
searches for all records in which @{b}size@{ub} has a value ranging from 5 to 10 
inclusive. 

@{b}important && stricmp(name, "Meier") == 0@{ub}
searches for all records in which the boolean field @{b}important@{ub} is checked 
and the field @{b}name@{ub} contains the string @{b}Meier@{ub}. 

@{b}datediff(currentdate(), date) <= 10 && datediff(currentdate(), date) >= 0@{ub}
searches for all records in which the field @{b}date@{ub} contains a date that is 
within the next ten days. 
@endnode 


@node SearchInfos "Search Information" 
@toc SEARCH

@{b}@{u}Search Information@{ub}@{uu}

Search info can be used to temporarily save search criteria. In the 
search requester, the @{b}Name@{ub} gadget can be used to specify a name for the 
search info. The search criteria will be stored when you hit any of the 
positive response buttons at the bottom of the search requester. To get 
the stored search criteria back, you have to click on the picker button 
of the @{b}Name@{ub} gadget and select the desired search info. The criteria will 
be copied to the search requester. When you enter a name into search 
info, any pre-existing name will be overwritten. Search info data will 
remain valid until the database is closed. 
@endnode 
@node ARexxSearch "Searching with ARexx" 
@toc SEARCH

@{b}@{u}Searching with ARexx@{ub}@{uu}

You can also use @{"Fiasco's ARexx port" Link ARexx} to search a database. The ARexx 
commands for searching make use of @{"search info" Link SearchInfos} to keep track of search 
criteria. 

    Thus, you must have a search info before you can start searching. 
This search info may be created with @{b}
@{"NewSearchInfo Name/K,Fields/S,Formula/K,Var/K" link RxNewSearchInfo}@{ub}. If you do not specify a 
@{b}Name@{ub}, Fiasco will chose a name that does not exist yet and will return it 
in @{b}Result@{ub}. This name has to be specified in the arguments of all 
following search commands that refer to this search info. 

    If you want to search by formula, you must specify the formula for 
the search in the arguments for @{b}NewSearchInfo@{ub}. 

    If you want to search by fields you have to use the command @{b}
@{"SetSearchField SearchInfo/K/A,FieldID/K/A,Blur/K/N,Pattern/K/A/F" link RxSetSearchField}@{ub} to 
specify a field to be searched for. You may call that command several 
times to specify several fields. 

    Now you can use the command @{b}
@{"Find SearchInfo/K/A,Record/K/N,Reverse/S,All=Stem/K,Var/K" link RxFind}@{ub} to search for 
matching records. You may use the @{b}Record@{ub} argument to search with each 
call for the next matching record. This argument specifies the record 
after which the search will start. For example, if you specify @{b}Record 0@{ub}, 
the search will start at the first record. If a matching record is found, 
its number will be returned in @{b}Result@{ub}. To continue the search you can 
call @{b}Find@{ub} with the record number of the found record. In contrast to the 
GUI search function, found records are not activated. 

    The other method involves the @{b}All@{ub} argument. Fiasco will search all 
records and store the numbers of the found records in the stem variable 
specified after the @{b}All@{ub} argument. The number of found records will be 
stored in @{i}stem@{ui}@{b}.count@{ub}. Please do not use this method if a very large 
number of matches is possible; it would be too time and memory intensive. 
@endnode 
@node Count "Count" 
@toc SEARCH

@{b}@{u}Count@{ub}@{uu}

@{b}@{"Compare/Count" link MnCount}@{ub} opens a requester similar to the search requester. As in 
the search requester you have to specify pattern, field and tolerance. If 
you select @{b}Ok@{ub} the matches will be counted. This way you can get 
experience with the @{"blurred search" link BlurredSearch} feature.  

@endnode 
@node Replace "Replace" 
@toc SEARCH

@{b}@{u}Replace@{ub}@{uu}

@{b}@{"Compare/Replace" link MnReplace}@{ub} is the function that allows you to replace certain values 
with others. You have to specify as normal the criteria for the search 
here. Additionally, you have to define at least one field in which a new 
value will be inserted whenever a record matching the search criteria is 
found. This replacement may be either a fixed value (select @{b}Replace by 
value@{ub}) or the result of a Fiasco formula (@{b}Replace by formula result@{ub}. 

    By using the second mode, you are able to apply updates or 
corrections to your data. An example for this is a change of a phone area 
code or some general change of an area code system (which happened 
recently in Italy). When the area code 0123 is changed to 0456, you have 
to set the search criteria for the phone number to @{b}0123#?@{ub}. Then set the 
replace formula for phone number to @{b}strcat("0456", strmid(test, 5, -1))@{ub}. 
This formula truncates the first four characters of the phone number and 
replaces them by 0456. As only phone numbers starting with 0123 are 
affected by this operation, the codes will be simply exchanged. 

    If you select the @{b}Confirm@{ub} gadget you will be asked if you really want 
to replace the value for each record. The record will be displayed while 
you are asked.  

    Attention: You can quickly destroy important data with a bad pattern 
(for example: @{b}#?@{ub})!!! 
@endnode 
@node Filter "Filter" 
@toc SEARCH

@{b}@{u}Filter@{ub}@{uu}

Fiasco's filter allows you to display only those records that match a 
pattern. With @{b}@{"Compare/Filter" link MnEditFilter}@{ub} you may open the @{"filter requester" link RqFilter} which has 
the same structure as the search requester. If you select @{b}Ok@{ub} only those 
records that match the specified pattern will be displayed.  

    You may browse through the records with @{b}@{"Record/Next" link MnNext}@{ub} and @{b}
@{"Record/Previous" link MnPrevious}@{ub}. The list also displays only matching records. 

    A filter is simply an index. Therefore, you may specify the name of 
the index in the filter requester. 

    To switch the filter off, you may use the index history. The menu 
item @{b}Database/Previous active index@{ub} will activate the index that was 
active before the filter was active.  

    If you create a new filter while another filter is still active (i. 
e. you did not select the old index in the index requester), only the 
records in the old filter will be examined. Thus, you can create filters 
with two conditions logically combined using "and". 

    If you create new records while a filter is active the records will 
be displayed whether or not they match the filter pattern. If you change 
the contents of an existing record it also will be displayed. If you want 
to update the filter, you have to select the old index and then call the 
filter requester and select @{b}Ok@{ub}. 

    For more advanced use of the filter see the section @{"Using Indices" link UsingIndices}.   
@endnode 


@node PRINT "Printing a Database" 
@toc main

@{b}@{u}Printing a Database@{ub}@{uu}

You can create a print-out of a Fiasco database in several ways. The 
internal print function is the easiest to use. To increase the quality of 
the print-outs, you may combine TeX with the print function. If you want 
to create a print-out that can't be created with the print function, you 
may use an ARexx script. 

 @{"Internal Print Function" link InternalPrint}
 @{"Printing with TeX" link TeXPrint}
 @{"Printing with ARexx" link ARexxPrint}


 
@endnode 
@node InternalPrint "Internal Print Function" 
@toc PRINT

@{b}@{u}Internal Print Function@{ub}@{uu}

The menuitem @{b}Project/Print@{ub} opens the print window of Fiasco. This window 
is similar to a Fiasco project window in mask mode. It contains elements 
which can be arranged with the mouse. In the final print-out all records 
will be laid out that way. When you open the print window Fiasco tries to 
open a file containing the standard print mask for the project. The file 
name for such files is @{i}Project Name@{ui}@{b}.fpr@{ub}. @{i}Project Name@{ui} is the file name of 
the project without @{b}.fdb@{ub}. If the file is not found, Fiasco lays-out the 
print mask according to the real mask. 

    To print the database as a list, you should select the menuitem 
@{b}Project/Get from list@{ub}. This will layout the print mask according to the 
real list. You may use @{b}Project/Get from mask@{ub} to get the mask layout. 

    You simply have to select @{b}Project/Print@{ub} to print the project with 
this layout. 

    
@{"Print Mask files" link printmaskfiles}
@endnode 


@node printmaskedit "The Print Mask" 
@toc InternalPrint

@{b}@{u}The Print Mask@{ub}@{uu}

The print mask has three parts: The head, the body and the foot. The head 
will be printed before any other data. The body will be printed for each 
record. It may contain references to project fields. These references 
will be substituted by the field contents of the records while printing. 
The foot will be printed last. The print window displays only one of 
these parts at a time. To change the displayed part, use the @{b}Control@{ub} 
menu. 

    The print window can be handled much like the project window in mask 
mode. To create an element (comparable to fields in the project mask), 
select a type with @{b}Element/Type@{ub} and select @{b}Element/Add@{ub} or press @{b}Return@{ub}. 
Depending on the type, a requester will appear which gives you some 
options for the fields. Fiasco supports three element types: 

·  Field 

·  Text 

·  Formfeed 

Field elements are usable only in the print body. They can be used 
to display the field contents in the print-out. The requester for field 
elements contains gadgets to select the field, to set the width, to set 
print styles like bold, italic or underlined and to activate clipping. 
Clipping  can be used to control whether or not an entry may get wider 
than the specified width. If clipping is active, every entry which is 
longer than the width will be clipped to fit in that width. If clipping 
is not active, the following entries will be shifted. 

    Text elements are similar to text fields in the mask. They serve to 
put static text in the print mask. They support print styles like bold, 
italic and underlined. Text elements are the most important elements in 
the head and foot parts. 

    Formfeed elements terminate the page. That means that the data after 
a formfeed will be printed on a new page. Formfeed elements have no 
editable options and thus no requester opens after adding such an 
element. @{b}Edit element@{ub} also is not usable for these elements. Because of 
the special meaning, the width of formfeed elements is "infinite". 
Formfeed elements appear as a horizontal line in the mask. 

@endnode 
@node printmaskfiles "Print Mask Files" 
@toc InternalPrint

@{b}@{u}Print Mask Files@{ub}@{uu}

@{b}Project/Save@{ub} and @{b}Project/Save as@{ub} in the print window create files which 
contain the print mask structure. These files can be reopened to restore 
a particular structure. If you have deleted a field in the database or if 
you have changed its ID, the print mask file may contain references to 
"nothing". When you open it Fiasco will try to get these references back. 
Fiasco uses a requester for that purpose which shows the field ID that 
was not found and a list of all fields in the current project. If you 
select one and click on @{b}Ok@{ub} the reference will be changed to the selected 
field. If you @{b}Cancel@{ub} the requester the element will be deleted. You can 
easily adopt print masks to other projects this way. Simply load the 
database, open the print window and load the print mask. Now you can 
change all elements to the matching fields in the new database. 

    Besides the layout print mask, files contain the settings made in the 
@{"print options requester" Link RqPrintOptions}. 
@endnode 


@node TeXPrint "Printing with TeX" 
@toc PRINT

@{b}@{u}Printing with TeX@{ub}@{uu}

You can use TeX to create high-quality print-outs of Fiasco projects. TeX 
is a kind of programming language, originally developed by Donald E. 
Knuth, which can be used to create printed documents. PasTeX is a freely 
distributable TeX implementation for the Amiga that can be found for 
example on the Meeting Pearls III CD-ROM. The print function of Fiasco 
supports TeX using @{"ARexx" Link ARexx}. 

    If you select @{b}Print with ARexx@{ub} in the @{"print options requester" Link RqPrintOptions}, the 
function of the @{b}Print@{ub} menuitem of the print window is changed: After 
creating the print-out, the ARexx script @{b}ARexx/ARexxPrint.rexx@{ub} is called 
with the name of the created file as its argument. This script should 
call TeX to compile and print the file. Because of that you must not 
write the file to @{b}PRT:@{ub}. You should set @{b}Print to@{ub} in the print options 
requester to a temporary file, for example @{b}T:FiascoPrintOut.tex@{ub}. The 
script should look like this:  

/* ARexxPrint.rexx
 * For use with PasTeX
 */

/* Parse arguments 
 */
Parse Arg File 

Address Command

File = strip(File,,'"')

/*  Call virtex
 */
'virtex' '"' || File || '"'

/*  Create name of dvi file
 */
dotpos = lastpos(".", File)

if dotpos ~= 0 then 
    DVIFile = substr(File, 1, dotpos-1) || ".dvi"
else 
    DVIFile = File || ".dvi"

/*  Call dviprint
 */
'dviprint' '"' || DVIFile  || '"'   

/* Delete temporary files
 */
call delete(file)                   
call delete(dvifile)


If you want to print with TeX you have to create the print mask in a TeX 
compatible manner. For instance, you have to include a text element with 
the text @{b}\\documentstyle{article}@{ub} or something similar in the header if 
you work with LaTeX. Furthermore, the file must not contain any control 
charaters. Thus, Style attributes and formfeed elements cannot be used. 
The Fiasco distribution contains several examples for this. 
@endnode 
@node ARexxPrint "Printing with ARexx" 
@toc PRINT

@{b}@{u}Printing with ARexx@{ub}@{uu}

"Printing with ARexx" is a very comprehensive topic. This section should 
give you a rough idea of what can be done and how. 

    One way of printing with @{"ARexx" Link ARexx} has already been explained in the 
section Printing with TeX. You may "misuse" ARexxPrint.rexx for purposes 
other than calling TeX. For example, you may use a script which parses 
the data for your own purposes or loads it into your word processing 
program. 

    If you want to create more complex print-outs, which cannot be 
created with Fiasco's internal print function, you have to create the 
print-out with ARexx alone. Such an ARexx script has to go through the 
whole database and get the data it needs with @{b}@{"GetField" Link rxgetfield}@{ub}. After that it may 
do with the data what it wants. 

@{"GraphPrint.rexx" link graphprintrexx}  

@endnode 
@node graphprintrexx "GraphPrint.rexx" 
@toc ARexxPrint

@{b}@{u}GraphPrint.rexx@{ub}@{uu}

The Fiasco distribution contains a complex example for a script, as it 
was described in the previous section. The script @{b}GraphPrint.rexx@{ub} is 
located in the @{b}ARexx@{ub} directory and can be used with the GraphDemo 
project. However, it can be used with any other project that contains the 
required data. The script reads data from the project and creates an x/y 
diagram of the data. It automatically adapts to different value ranges. 
The script uses LaTeX and the eepic extension for the print-out. That 
means that you have to run a special host program in the background while 
printing. Because the script performs many mathematical operations it 
uses the rexxmathlib.library, which is not included in the distribution. 
To start GraphPrint.rexx, click on the @{b}Graphic@{ub} button in the 
GraphDemo/Fragments project. To use the script with another project, 
simply activate the project in Fiasco and start the script from the 
Workbench or Shell. Several requesters will appear. You have to specify 
what fields you want to use. You may select whether you want to view or 
print the TeX file directly or to write it to a specified location. After 
that the advanced options menu appears. To modify nothing, simply click 
on @{b}Continue@{ub}. @{b}Edit Scale Base@{ub} allows you to specify a value which will be 
used by the script as a base value for the scale of one of the axises. 
For example, if you use 5 (which is the default) you will get a scale of 
5, 10, 15, etc. If you use 2 you will get 2, 4, 6, etc. @{b}Edit Origin@{ub} 
allows you to choose whether the diagram will begin at point (0;0) or at 
a point which is the best for the project. 

@endnode 
@node XPORT "Import and Export" 
@toc main

@{b}@{u}Import and Export@{ub}@{uu}

The Import and Export functions of Fiasco provide the ability to load 
data from other database programs into Fiasco and to write data with 
Fiasco that may be read by other programs.  Such Import/Export-files 
contain ASCII data. The fields or records are marked with special 
characters that may be freely defined in the Import/Export function of 
Fiasco. 

    @{i}Beginners, please note: @{ui} Some basic knowledge is required to be able 
to effectively use Fiasco's Import/Export function. If you are familiar 
with databases you can skip the following information.  The section 
@{"Special characters" link XPSpecChars} describes the special escape sequences used by Fiasco. 
  Although other databases may use a similar scheme you should read this 
section carefully. The whole Import/Export function of Fiasco relies on 
these escape sequences. 

    
@{"How to specify special characters" link XPSpecChars}
@{"Importing of Data" link ImportingData}
@{"Exporting of Data" link ExportingData}  
@endnode 
@node XPStructure "Structure of Import/Export files" 
@toc XPORT

@{b}@{u}Structure of Import/Export files@{ub}@{uu}

The names used here refer to the gadget labels in the Import/Export 
requesters. Note that some marking characters may be empty. To use the 
file with Fiasco you have to define, at minimum, either @{b}Field Start@{ub}/@{b}Field 
End@{ub} or @{b}Field Separator@{ub} and either @{b}Record Start@{ub}/@{b}Record End@{ub} or @{b}Record 
Separator@{ub}.   However, the import functions of other programs may get 
upset, although this structure is correct. When you export data, Fiasco 
will filter the characters used as control characters from the exported 
data. I.e., if one fields contains @{b}1,2@{ub} and the , is used as control 
character, Fiasco will export @{b}12@{ub}. 


@{b}Record Start@{ub} 	 
@{b}Field Start@{ub} 	 
@{i}Field Data@{ui} 	 Contents of the field in ASCII format.
@{b}Field End@{ub} 	 
@{b}Field Separator@{ub} 	 Separates two fields, @{i}not @{ui}used after the last field of a record. 
...	 
@{b}Field Start@{ub} 	 
@{i}Field Data@{ui} 	 
@{b}Field End@{ub} 	 
@{b}Record End@{ub} 	 
@{b}Record Separator@{ub} 	 Separates two records, @{i} not@{ui}used after the last record of a file. 
...	 
@{b}Record Start@{ub} 	 
...	 (see above) 
@{b}Record End@{ub} 	 
@{i}End of File@{ui} 	 

 


    If you activate @{b}First Record contains IDs@{ub}, the field IDs will be 
stored in the first record as if they were fields. 

    When you export listview fields, Fiasco will separate the entries 
with the characters specified in @{b}Listview/Separator@{ub}. 


@{b}An Example of an Import/Export file@{ub}

@{b}Record start@{ub} and @{b}record end@{ub} are empty. @{b}Record separator@{ub} is a newline 
character. @{b}Field start@{ub} and @{b}field end@{ub} are double quotes. @{b}Field separator@{ub} 
is a comma. The first record contains the IDs of the fields. Note the 
empty field in the last record. 
"Name","FirstName","Rank","Ship"
"Picard","Jean-Luc","Captain","U.S.S. Enterprise"
"Riker","William Thomas","Commander","U.S.S. Enterprise"
"Data","","Lieutenant Cmdr.","U.S.S. Enterprise"


 
@endnode 
@node XPSpecChars "How to Specify Special Characters" 
@toc XPORT

@{b}@{u}How to Specify Special Characters@{ub}@{uu}

You often cannot simply type the characters for marking fields and 
records as plain text. For example, if you want to use the newline 
character as a record separator, you cannot simply hit the Return key. 
Instead, you have to type it in as an escape sequence. Fiasco supports 
escape sequences similar to the escape sequences of the "C" programming 
language. The escape sequences are introduced by a \\. These are 
supported: 


@{b} \\n@{ub}	 Newline-character, ASCII 10 
@{b}\\f@{ub}	 Formfeed-character, ASCII 12 
@{b}\\r@{ub}	 Return-character, ASCII 13 
@{b}\\t@{ub}	 Horizontal tabulator, ASCII 9 
@{b}\\v@{ub}	 Vertical tabulator, ASCII 11 
@{b}\\@{ub}@{i}Number@{ui}	 Character with specified ASCII code
@{b} \\@{ub}@{i}Char@{ui}	 Character directly copied





    The last option (\\ + @{i}Character @{ui}) makes it possible to use a 
character, which is reserved for escape-sequences. 

    In Import, you may also specify character-classes.  Character-classes 
are introduced in Fiasco with an #. These are supported: 


@{b}#p@{ub}	 Printable character. 
@{b}#a@{ub}	 Printable ASCII-character. Without international chars
@{b}#c@{ub}	 Control-character. Not printable 




    Export supports to insert some additional information in the 
export-file. These commands are introduced with an %. These are 
supported: 


@{b}%f@{ub}	 ID of field 
@{b}%r@{ub}	 Number of record 



@endnode 
@node ImportingData "Importing of Data" 
@toc XPORT

@{b}@{u}Importing of Data@{ub}@{uu}

The import requester is the GUI interface for Fiasco's import function. 
You can open it using @{b}Project/Import@{ub}. The file you want to import must be 
specified in @{b}File@{ub}. After having done this you have to specify the 
structure of the file in the requester.If you are importing a file into 
Fiasco immediately after export it from another database and still know 
the structure parameters you can simply copy them into Fiasco's import 
requester. Otherwise you can display the contents of the file using the 
@{b}View@{ub} button at the right side of the filename. Fiasco will start either 
"More" or "MultiView" to display the file. If the file has a standard 
structure it should not be too difficult to recognize the parameters. 
Usually, @{b}Record Start@{ub} and @{b}Record End@{ub} are empty and @{b}Record Separator@{ub} is 
\\n. @{b}Field Start@{ub} and @{b}Field End@{ub} are often empty or double quotes ("). Usual 
values for @{b}Field Separator@{ub} are a comma (,) or a tabulator (\\t). 

    @{b}Skip Lines@{ub} defines the characters that introduce a comment @{i}at the 
beginning of a line@{ui}. If present, specify the comment introducer here. 
This may also be used to skip any formatting information present in the 
file. Fiasco's import function does not use such information. You can use 
@{b}Start Skip@{ub} to skip any initial comment or similar items in the file. @{b}Max. 
Fields@{ub} can be used to specify a record end mark if neither @{b}Record 
Separator@{ub} nor @{b}Record End@{ub} can be used. 

    Activate @{b}First Record contains IDs@{ub} if the first record of the input 
file consists of Field IDs rather than real data. If you activate this 
the IDs will be used by Fiasco either to create fields with these IDs or 
to use already existent fields. 

    The options @{b}Append new fields@{ub} and @{b}Overwrite old project@{ub} control, 
whether you want to update a project or you want to create a new one. If 
you want to create a new project, you should activate both options. 

    If you want to continue using your current settings you may save them 
with the @{b}Save@{ub} button. Settings may be reloaded with @{b}Load@{ub}. Fiasco already 
comes with several settings to import data from various sources. 

    To start the import process, you just have to click on @{b}Ok@{ub}.
@{i}Attention: @{ui}If the input file is too big, or even if the structure 
parameters are defective, the system may run out of memory! Fiasco has no 
big problems, if it runs out of memory, but other programs may have 
problems.  For this reason, you should be careful with unsaved data! 

    If everything went well, the import requester will close and the new 
project will be activated. You will first want to improve the formatting 
of the project using the mask mode. If you did not activate @{b}First Record 
contains IDs@{ub}, you should change the field IDs according to the contents 
of the fields. In addition, you should create text fields to label the 
existing fields. At this point you have a nicely formatted project. 
However, all fields are string fields. You should determine whether some 
fields may be integer, cycle or other field types. You may change the 
type of these fields with the Fiasco's @{"convert" Link Convertingfields} function. In the example 
used  in @{"Structure of Import/Export files" link XPStructure},   the rank field may be 
converted to a cycle field. 

    If you have followed these steps the project should be saved under a 
appropriate name. 

@endnode 
@node ExportingData "Exporting of Data" 
@toc XPORT

@{b}@{u}Exporting of Data@{ub}@{uu}

From Fiasco's viewpoint, exporting data is much less complicated than 
importing. Normally, you can use Fiasco's default parameters (No @{b}Record 
Start@{ub} and @{b}Record End@{ub}, a newline character for @{b}Record Separator@{ub}, double 
quotes for @{b}Field Start@{ub} and @{b}Field End@{ub} and a comma for @{b}Field Separator@{ub}). If 
you use these parameters, you must take care, that you data do not 
contain any double quotation marks. In addition, you have to be certain 
that the program you want to import the data supports these parameters. 
If you select @{b}First Record contains IDs@{ub}, Fiasco will create an additional 
record at the top of the file which contains the field IDs. The file will 
contain no other formatting information. 

    If you select @{b}Marked Records only@{ub}, only the marked records will be 
written. 

    Click on @{b}Ok@{ub} to start exporting. 

@endnode 
@node UpdatingDBXport "Updating databases with Im/Export" 
@toc XPORT

@{b}@{u}Updating databases with Im/Export@{ub}@{uu}

Fiasco's import and export function can be also used to automatically 
insert data created in other databases in an already existing database. 
To do that, you have to have a database in any export format that Fiasco 
is able to read. Its first record has to contain field IDs for the data 
following it. These IDs must match the IDs of the already existing Fiasco 
database, into which you want to import the data. I.e. if you have a 
field with the ID @{b}Name@{ub} in the existing Fiasco database, the field ID for 
the respective field specified in the exported file must be also @{b}Name@{ub}. If 
it is not, you can easyly change the ID with a text editor. The already 
existing database may contain fields that are not in the file to be 
imported. If the file contains fields that are not in the Fiasco 
database, Fiasco's import function will create a new field for these 
data. To initiate importing, you have to make the apopriate settings for 
the structure of the file to be imported. Furthermore, you must activate 
@{b}First Record contains IDs@{ub} (as Fiasco could otherwise not associate the 
data to the correct fields). @{b}Append new fields@{ub} and @{b}Overwrite old project@{ub} 
must be switched off. 

    This method works both with data exported by Fiasco and with data 
exported or created by any other program, as long it is in a format that 
can be read by Fiasco. 

@endnode 
@node FIELDTYPES "Fieldtypes" 
@toc main

@{b}@{u}Fieldtypes@{ub}@{uu}

Data are stored in fields. There are only two basic types: "string" and 
"number". All other types are modifications, more or less, of these types 
which make working with the database easier. Some fieldtypes may be used 
in @{"listview fields" Link FT_LV}. These are fields, which may contain several entries. 
Entries can be added or deleted. Each entry can be used like any other 
normal field of that type. 

    Fiasco supports the following types: 

@{" String " link FT_Str } 
@{" Integer " link FT_Int } 
@{" Float " link FT_Float } 
@{" Boolean " link FT_Bool } 
@{" Cycle " link FT_Cyc } 
@{" Slider " link FT_Sld } 
@{" Date " link FT_Date } 
@{" Time " link FT_Time } 
@{" Extern " link FT_Ext } 
@{" Datatypes " link FT_DT } 
@{" Var String " link FT_VarString } 
@{" Text " link FT_Txt } 
@{" Button " link FT_But } 
@{" Bar " link FT_Bar } 

@{" Listview " link FT_LV }   

    The descriptions for the field types are based on the  
@{"Standard Attributes" link StdAttrs}.   Each field type may add new attributes, change an 
attribute or it also might not support a particular attribute. 
@endnode 
@node StdAttrs "Standard Attributes" 
@toc FIELDTYPES

@{b}@{u}Standard Attributes@{ub}@{uu}

These attributes are normally supported by a field type: 

    
@{b}Structure/ID:@{ub} This string identifies a field. It is displayed in mask 
   mode in the fields, in the list header, in the search and related 
   requesters and in the relation requester. This string must be unique 
   in the current project. To access the field by its ID from formulas or 
   ARexx scripts, further limitations on the format of the ID apply: It 
   may not contain spaces and it may not begin with a number.  

@{b}Structure/Virtual:@{ub} The value of the field is not saved on disk, but is 
   recalculated every time when the record is required. This is done 
   using the init cont attributes and the formula or the ARexx script 
   attribute. Please note that these fields occupy the same amount of RAM 
   as other fields.   

@{b}Structure/Listview:@{ub} The field will be a @{"listview" Link FT_LV} field. This modifier can 
   only be changed when the field is created. To change the listview 
   modifier later, you will have to use the @{"convert function" Link ConvertingFields}. Listview 
   fields cannot be displayed in the list window, thus the @{b}List Window@{ub} 
   attributes are not available, when this modifier is active.  

@{b}Mask Window/Width:@{ub} defines the width of the field in the mask in 
   characters.   

@{b}Mask Window/Height:@{ub} defines the height of the field in the mask in 
   characters.   

@{b}Mask Window/Keyboard Shortcut:@{ub} You may enter a single character here. 
   When you press this character on the keyboard in record mode the field 
   will be activated or somehow changed. The shortcut paired with @{b}Shift@{ub} 
   may change the field in the other direction.  

@{b}Mask Window/Justification:@{ub} Controls whether the contents in the field 
   will be displayed left or right justified or centered.  

@{b}Mask Window/Read Only:@{ub} The field content will be displayed in a recessed 
   box which cannot be activated or edited.  

@{b}Mask Window/Hidden:@{ub} If this option is active the field will be not 
   visible in the mask. To open the fieldrequester for it you will have 
   to use the menuitem @{b}@{"Field/Edit named Field" link MnEditNamedField}@{ub}.  

@{b}List Window/Width:@{ub} Specifies the width of the field in the list window. 
   It is measured in characters. You may also change this value directly 
   in the @{"list window" Link List}.  

@{b}List Window/Justification:@{ub} Controls whether the contents of the field is 
   displayed in the list window left or right justified or centered.  

@{b}List Window/Hidden:@{ub} The field column will be not displayed in the list 
   when this option is active. You may also change this option directly 
   in the @{"list window" Link List}.  

@{b}Initial Content/Use own value:@{ub} you may specify a value here which will be 
   used while creating a new record.  

@{b}Initial Content/Use old value:@{ub} If you create a new record the value which 
   has been used in the old record will be used in the new record.  

@{b}Predefined Values:@{ub}  This feature allows you to add a picker button at the 
   right side of a field which can be used to open a list of values the 
   field can be set to. Clicking on the @{b}Predefined Values@{ub} button in the 
   field requester will open a new requester that can be used to edit the 
   settings for this attribute. You may either specify a list of possible 
   values for the field or you may specify an ARexx script that will be 
   executed when the picker button is selected. This ARexx script may for 
   instance open a file requester and use @{b}SetField@{ub} to set the desired 
   field to the selected file. The list of predefined values may be also 
   used from the search requester with the picker button at the right 
   side of the pattern gadget. 

@{b}Programming/Formula:@{ub} You may specify a formula here that will be used to 
   calculate the content of the field. The formula may reference other 
   fields to make the calculation. Whenever one of the other fields is 
   changed or a completely new record is added, the formula will be 
   calculated again. This attribute can be combined nicely with the 
   @{b}Virtual@{ub} attribute. More about formulas   @{"here" link formulas}.   

@{b}Programming/ARexx Script:@{ub}  You may specify an ARexx script here which 
   will be called when a new record is created, or the content of a field 
   is changed. It is possible that the @{b}initial content@{ub} attributes will 
   not have the effect specified in the requester, if the script changes 
   the contents of the field. If the operation is also possible with 
   formulas, it is recommended to use formulas instead.  



    By using @{"mask stretching" Link Stretch} it is possible that the attributes, which 
specify the dimensions of the field, will be slightly influenced. 

@endnode 
@node Ft_str "String Fieldtype" 
@toc FIELDTYPES

@{b}@{u}String Fieldtype@{ub}@{uu}

A string field takes strings with a designated length.   
@{"Standard Attributes" link StdAttrs}  


@{b}New Attributes:@{ub}


@{b}Structure/Max Chars:@{ub} determines, how many chars may be typed in this 
   field. This attribute has direct effect on the size of the project 
   file. 



@{b}Changed Attributes:@{ub}


@{b}Mask Window/Height:@{ub} This attribute is only active when the 
   @{"listview modifier" link FT_LV} is active. 



@{b}Search equivalent:@{ub}

correspondents to the content. 


@{b}Supported search patterns:@{ub}


@{b} ?@{ub} 	 - 	 One unknown character. 
@{b}#?@{ub} 	 - 	 No or more unknown characters. 




@{b}Conversion into a string field:@{ub}

Any field can be converted without loss of data into a string field. 
Alternative formats, if supported are specified in parentheses.
Additional notes:


Boolean 	- 	"Checked" is @{b}TRUE@{ub} (1), otherwise @{b}FALSE@{ub} (0) 
Cycle 	- 	Label (label number) converted
Slider 	- 	Level converted 
Date 	- 	Date in current locale format converted
Time 	- 	Time in current locale format converted



@endnode 


@node Ft_int "Integer Fieldtype" 
@toc FIELDTYPES

@{b}@{u}Integer Fieldtype@{ub}@{uu}

You may enter integer numbers in the range from -2,147,483,348 to 
2,147,483,347 in an integer field.   @{"Standard Attributes" link StdAttrs}  


@{b}New Attributes:@{ub}


@{b}Structure/Max Chars:@{ub} determines the maximum length of a number in chars. 

@{b}Initial Content/Use unique Key:@{ub} puts a number unique to this database in 
   this field whenever a new record is created. This Attribute is 
   mutually exclusive to @{b}use own value@{ub} and @{b}use old value@{ub}. 



@{b}Changed Attributes:@{ub}


@{b}Mask Window/Height:@{ub} This attribute is only active when the 
   @{"listview modifier" link FT_LV} is active. 



@{b}Search equivalent:@{ub}

is equal with the field content. 


@{b}Supported search patterns:@{ub}


> 	 - 	 greater than 
< 	 - 	 less than 
>= 	 - 	 greater or equal 
<= 	 - 	 less or equal 
!= 	 - 	 not equal 




@{b}Conversion into an integer field:@{ub}

Integer fields only accept the numeric part of the source data. If the 
source data begin with a non-numeric character the field will contain 0.
Additional notes:


Float 	- 	Integer part converted
Boolean 	- 	"Checked" gets 1, "Unchecked" gets 0
Cycle 	- 	Label number converted
Slider 	- 	Level converted



@endnode 
@node Ft_float "Float Fieldtype" 
@toc FIELDTYPES

@{b}@{u}Float Fieldtype@{ub}@{uu}

You may enter a real number in a float field.  

@{"Standard Attributes" link StdAttrs}  


@{b}New Attributes:@{ub}


@{b}Mask Window/Precision Type:@{ub} If @{b}Number of all digits@{ub} is active, the value 
   specified in @{b}Precision@{ub} (see below) is the maximum number of all digits 
   displayed in the field.  Otherwise, if @{b}Number of digits after point@{ub} is 
   active, the @{b}Precision@{ub} value is the maximum number of all digits 
   displayed right of the decimal point in the field.  

@{b}Mask Window/Precision:@{ub} Either the number of all digits or the number of 
   digits after the decimal point. Controlled by @{b}Precision Type@{ub}.  




@{b}Changed Attributes:@{ub}


@{b}Mask Window/Height:@{ub} This attribute is only active when the 
   @{"listview modifier" link FT_LV} is active. 



@{b}Search equivalent:@{ub}

is equal to the field content 


@{b}Conversion into a float field:@{ub}

Float fields only accept the numeric part of the source data. If the 
source data begin with a non-numeric character, the field will contain 0.
Additional notes:


Boolean 	- 	"Checked" gets 1.0, "Unchecked" gets 0.0 
Cycle 	- 	Label number converted





@{b}Notes:@{ub}

Since Fiasco 2.1, float fields are used in 64 bit representation 
internally. This feature now allows a reasonable high precision for float 
fields. Databases in a pre 2.1 format are automatically converted during 
the next saving. 

@endnode 
@node Ft_bool "Boolean Fieldtype" 
@toc FIELDTYPES

@{b}@{u}Boolean Fieldtype@{ub}@{uu}

A Boolean field can contain only one of two values: "True" or "False". It 
appears in the mask as a "checkbox gadget".   @{"Standard Attributes" link StdAttrs}  


@{b}Changed Attributes:@{ub}


@{b}Structure/Listview:@{ub} not applicable. 

@{b}Mask Window/Justification:@{ub} not applicable. 

@{b}Mask Window/Width:@{ub} always 3. 

@{b}Mask Window/Height:@{ub} always 1. 

@{b}Predefined Values:@{ub} not applicable. 



@{b}Search equivalent:@{ub}

@{b}TRUE@{ub} or 1 - checked field 
@{b}FALSE@{ub} or 0 - unchecked field 



@{b}Conversion into a boolean field:@{ub}

Boolean fields convert all non-0 numbers and @{b}TRUE@{ub} into the checked state. 
All other values will be converted to the unchecked state. 


@{b}Notes:@{ub}

Under Amiga OS 2.x this field can look a bit strange because the images 
are not scalable. Starting with OS 3.0, the size of the field is adjusted 
to the font size. 

@endnode 
@node Ft_cyc "Cycle Fieldtype" 
@toc FIELDTYPES

@{b}@{u}Cycle Fieldtype@{ub}@{uu}

Cycle fields have several choices from a freely definable list, this 
helps to save memory. There is a maximum of 65536 choices. (I hope that's 
enough ;-) A cycle field appears in the mask as a "Cycle gadget" (as the 
name implies).   @{"Standard Attributes" link StdAttrs}  


@{b}New Attributes:@{ub}


@{b}Labels:@{ub} A list of all choices. There must be at least one entry, two 
   entries make it a cycle field. 



@{b}Changed Attributes:@{ub}


@{b}Structure/Listview:@{ub} not applicable. 

@{b}Mask Window/Justification:@{ub} always centered. 

@{b}Mask Window/Height:@{ub} always 1. 

@{b}Predefined Values:@{ub} not applicable. 



@{b}Search equivalent:@{ub}

the number of the label, counting from zero or the entry itself (enter 
correctly!) 


@{b}Conversion into a cycle field:@{ub}

The values will be converted into labels. If there are equal values they 
will get the same label. Data are not lost.
Additional notes:


Boolean 	 - 	 "Checked" becomes @{b}TRUE@{ub} (1), otherwise @{b}FALSE@{ub} (0) 


@endnode 
@node Ft_sld "Slider Fieldtype" 
@toc FIELDTYPES

@{b}@{u}Slider Fieldtype@{ub}@{uu}

A slider is related to a integer field. It can be used to display integer 
numbers graphically. The numbers may range from -32,768 to 32,767 and may 
be influenced by several attributes.  

@{"Standard Attributes" link StdAttrs}  


@{b}New Attributes:@{ub}


@{b}Structure/Min. Value:@{ub} defines the smallest value. It corresponds to the 
   position of the "knob" at the left or at the upper end of the field. 

@{b}Structure/Max. Value:@{ub} defines the highest value. It corresponds to the 
   position of the "knob" at the right or at the lower end of the field. 

@{b}Mask Window/Format:@{ub} is a format string in style of the "C" programming 
   language. The result will be displayed at the right hand of the 
   slider. The syntax:  %[-][0][Field][.Maximum][l]Format  

·  -: The number is left aligned, the default is right aligned 

·  0: The field is padded with zeroes. e.g.: 1 -> 001 

·  Field: The minimal field width 

·  Maximum: only for strings, no meaning here. 

·  l: Says that the number is 32 bit wide. This is here always the case. 

·  Format: 
   @{b}c@{ub} - Char, the ASCII character for the number is displayed. 
   @{b}d@{ub} - The number is displayed. 
   @{b}u@{ub} - The unsigned number is displayed. 
   @{b}x@{ub} - The number is displayed in hexadecimal format. 
   There are also the @{b}b@{ub} and @{b}s@{ub} control characters. These take addresses as 
   arguments and produce only garbage in this case. 
    



    The formatting is done with the exec-function @{b}RawDoFmt()@{ub}.  

    
@{b}Mask Window/Format Length@{ub} :the maximum length of the format. This 
region is in the width region. That means that a higher @{b}Format Length@{ub} 
makes the field itself smaller. 




@{b}Changed Attributes:@{ub}


@{b}Structure/Listview:@{ub} not applicable. 

@{b}Mask Window/Justification:@{ub} not applicable. 

@{b}Mask Window/Height:@{ub} always 1. 

@{b}Predefined Values:@{ub} not applicable. 



@{b}Search equivalent:@{ub}

The number itself. 


@{b}Supported search patterns:@{ub}


> 	 - 	 greater than 
< 	 - 	 less than 
>= 	 - 	 greater or equal 
<= 	 - 	 less or equal 
!= 	 - 	 not equal 




@{b}Conversion into a slider field:@{ub}

Slider fields only accept the numeric part of the source data. If the 
source data begin with a non-numeric character the field will contain 0. 
You should check the range attributes after converting -- they could 
influence the data.


@endnode 
@node Ft_date "Date Fieldtype" 
@toc FIELDTYPES

@{b}@{u}Date Fieldtype@{ub}@{uu}

You may enter a date in a date field. The date will be formatted 
according to the specifications in the active locale settings. If 
@{b}locale.library@{ub} is not available, the format DD.MM.YYYY will be used.   
@{"Standard Attributes" link StdAttrs}  


@{b}New Attributes:@{ub}


@{b}Initial Content/use current Date:@{ub} When a new record is created the 
   current date is copied in this field. 



@{b}Changed Attributes:@{ub}


@{b}Mask Window/Height:@{ub} This attribute is only active when the 
   @{"listview modifier" link FT_LV} is active. 



@{b}Search equivalent:@{ub}

is equal to the content. 


@{b}Conversion into a date field:@{ub}

Date fields require the data in the current locale format. The single 
parts must be numbers. If values are non numeric, the part will get "??".



@{b}Note:@{ub}

Even though it is with most formats possible to enter a two-digit year, 
it is recommended to use a four-digit year to avoid any of the problems 
the DOS world currently has. 

@endnode 
@node Ft_time "Time Fieldtype" 
@toc FIELDTYPES

@{b}@{u}Time Fieldtype@{ub}@{uu}

You may enter a time in a time field. The time will be formatted 
according to the specifications in the active locale settings. If 
@{b}locale.library@{ub} is not available, the format HH:MM:SS will be used.   
@{"Standard Attributes" link StdAttrs}  


@{b}New Attributes:@{ub}


@{b}Structure/Duration Format:@{ub} Normally, the @{b}locale.library@{ub} format will be 
   used to format the time. However, in some countries (most notably the 
   USA) this is not suitable to display time durations. If this attribute 
   is active, always the format HH:MM:SS will be used. Furthermore, the 
   range checking for the hour will be turned off. Thus, you will be able 
   to enter a duration longer than 24 hours.  

@{b}Initial Content/use current Time:@{ub} the current time will be copied in this 
   field when you create a new record. 




@{b}Changed Attributes:@{ub}


@{b}Mask Window/Height:@{ub} This attribute is only active when the 
   @{"listview modifier" link FT_LV} is active. 



@{b}Search equivalent:@{ub}

is equal to the content. 


@{b}Conversion into a time field:@{ub}

Time fields require the data in the format HH:MM:SS. Every element must 
be a number. If an element is non numeric, it will be 0.


@endnode 
@node Ft_ext "Extern Fieldtype" 
@toc FIELDTYPES

@{b}@{u}Extern Fieldtype@{ub}@{uu}

A extern field takes a string (most often a filename) that will be used 
on request as argument for a user defined program. This makes it possible 
to define additional data for a record.   @{"Standard Attributes" link StdAttrs}  


@{b}New Attributes:@{ub}


@{b}Structure/Max Chars:@{ub} defines the maximum length of a filename in chars. 
   This attribute has direct effect on the size of the project file. 

@{b}Command/Command:@{ub} is the name of a program, which is capable of using 
   these data. The characters @{b}%s@{ub} are replaced with the content of the 
   field. If you don`t use @{b}%s@{ub}, no arguments will be submitted. (For 
   example type: @{b}C:ED %s@{ub}) 

@{b}Command/Stack:@{ub} defines the stack size for a command. 

@{b}Mask Window/FileReq Gadget:@{ub} select this attribute to have an gadget at 
   the left side of the field that opens a file requester to edit the 
   content. Of course, this only makes sense if the contents are 
   filenames. 



@{b}Changed Attributes:@{ub}


@{b}Structure/Listview:@{ub} not applicable. 

@{b}Mask Window/Justification:@{ub} not applicable. 

@{b}Mask Window/Height:@{ub} always 1. 

@{b}Predefined Values:@{ub} not applicable. 



@{b}Search equivalent:@{ub}

is equal to the content. 


@{b}Conversion into a extern field:@{ub}

All fields can be converted without loss of data into an extern field. 
However, you have to specify a program that can use these data.
Additional notes:


Boolean 	-	 "Checked" becomes@{b}TRUE@{ub} (1), otherwise @{b}FALSE@{ub} (0) 
Cycle 	-	 Label (Label number) converted





@{b}Notes:@{ub}

The programs will be called using the AmigaDOS function @{b}System()@{ub}. A 
console window will be opened for I/O operations. 
@endnode 
@node Ft_dt "Datatypes Fieldtype" 
@toc FIELDTYPES

@{b}@{u}Datatypes Fieldtype@{ub}@{uu}

A datatypes field is similar to an extern field. The difference is the 
use of the datatypes.library. This is the reason you can use these fields 
only with Amiga OS 3.0 or greater. The major advantage is that the data 
will be displayed directly in the mask. A datatypes field is universally 
usable and freely extensible. A "popup"-gadget at the lower right side of 
the field makes it possible to edit the contents using a file requester. 
If something goes wrong, the error will be displayed in the field.  

@{"Standard Attributes" link StdAttrs}  


@{b}New Attributes:@{ub}


@{b}Structure/Max Chars:@{ub} defines the maximal length of the filename. This 
   attribute has a direct effect on the size of the project file. 

@{b}Mask Window/Options/Display filename:@{ub} When this option is active the 
   filename is displayed at the bottom of the field in a string gadget. 
   If you deactivate this option you cannot edit the value of the field. 
   Using the ARexx script @{b}requestdt.frx@{ub} with a button, editing the value 
   is indirectly possible. 

@{b}Mask Window/Options/Scrollbars:@{ub} Determines if scrollbars will be created 
   at the bottom and at the right border of the field. Without a 
   scrollbar you can only view the upper left of a file. (That is not 
   completely true. Some datatypes scroll their display if you click in 
   their area and drag the mouse in the direction of the hidden part. The 
   picture datatype is one example.)  

@{b}Mask Window/Options/Save gadget:@{ub} If you activate this option you will get 
   a second button under the datatypes field. The button will be marked 
   with an S. If you select the button a file requester will appear which 
   lets you choose a file to which the data, which are currently 
   displayed in the field, will be saved. The data will be written in IFF 
   format. 

@{b}Mask Window/Options/Border:@{ub} If this option is active Fiasco will render a 
   border around the field. Do not deactivate this option too often 
   because there are no other visual elements which mark the beginning 
   and the end of the field. 

@{b}Mask Window/Options/Defer loading:@{ub} If you activate this option, the file 
   of the field will not be immediately loaded when the record is 
   activated. Instead, the message @{b}"Deferred"@{ub} will be displayed in the 
   field. The data will be loaded and displayed only if you activate the 
   string gadget and hit return. 

@{b}Mask Window/Options/Pictures/Scaling:@{ub} Allows you to control the scaling 
   of pictures in the field. If the content of the field is not a 
   picture, this attribute has no effect. This options determines whether 
   there will be no scaling at all, only if the picture is bigger than 
   the field or if there will always be scaling. 

@{b}Mask Window/Options/Pictures/Scale size:@{ub} Allows the selection of the 
   scaling mode. @{b}Full Size@{ub} will make the picture exactly fit into the 
   field and may thus change the proportions of the picture. @{b}Proportional 
   Small@{ub} uses a size that fills the field in one direction and which 
   completely fits into the field. Furthermore, it keeps the proportions 
   of the picture. @{b}Proportional Big@{ub} uses the minimal size, which entirely 
   fills the field. The proportions will be kept here, too. 

@{b}Mask Window/Options/Texts/Word Wrap:@{ub} Select this option to activate word 
   wrapping for texts.  

@{b}Mask Window/Options/Miscellaneous/Play immediately:@{ub} Select this option to 
   start playing the data immediately after activating the record. If you 
   activate this option, @{b}Defer loading@{ub} must not be active. Of course, 
   this option is only effective if the datatype supports playing. The 
   animation and the sound datatypes are such datatypes.   

@{b}Mask Window/Options/Miscellaneous/Center:@{ub} Centers the datatypes object 
   within the field. 




@{b}Changed Attributes:@{ub}


@{b}Structure/Listview:@{ub} not applicable. 

@{b}Mask Window/Justification:@{ub} not applicable. 

@{b}Predefined Values:@{ub} not applicable. 



@{b}Searchequivalent:@{ub}

Is equal to the filename; You cannot search the content. 


@{b}Conversion into a datatypes field:@{ub}

All fields can be converted without loss of data into a datatypes field. 
However, the datatypes system requires valid filenames.
Additional notes:


Boolean 	-	 "Checked" becomes@{b}TRUE@{ub} (1), otherwise @{b}FALSE@{ub} (0) 
Cycle 	-	 Label (Label number) converted





@{b}Notes:@{ub}

The AmigaGuide and the animation datatype seem to have some problems with 
relatively small fields. 

    AmigaGuide datatype sometimes leaves graphical trash after scrolling 
the contents. 

    HAM and EHB pictures cannot be displayed in datatypes fields. 

    The changing of records gets slower because the data have to be 
loaded each time. To avoid that use @{b}Defer loading@{ub}.  
@endnode 
@node Ft_varstring "Var String Fieldtype" 
@toc FIELDTYPES

@{b}@{u}Var String Fieldtype@{ub}@{uu}

Var string fields take strings with variable length opposed to string 
fields, which use a designated maximum length. Var string fields may 
contain several lines.  @{"Standard Attributes" link StdAttrs}  


@{b}New Attributes:@{ub}


@{b}Mask Window/Scrollbars:@{ub} Adds a scrollbar at the right side of the field. 
   You can use it to scroll the contents of the field. 



@{b}Changed Attributes:@{ub}


@{b}Structure/Listview:@{ub} not applicable. 

@{b}Mask Window/Justification:@{ub} not supported. 

@{b}Predefined Values:@{ub} not applicable. 



@{b}Search equivalent:@{ub}

corresponds to the content. 


@{b}Supported search patterns:@{ub}

@{b}?@{ub} = One unknown character. 
@{b}#?@{ub} = No or more unknown characters. 



@{b}Conversion into a var string field:@{ub}

Any field can be converted without loss of data into a var string field. 
Alternative formats, if supported, are specified in parentheses.
Additional notes:


Boolean 	- 	"Checked" is @{b}TRUE@{ub} (1), otherwise @{b}FALSE@{ub} (0) 
Cycle 	- 	Label (label number) converted
Slider 	- 	Level converted 




@{b}Notes:@{ub}

Var string fields are implemented using the textfield.gadget by Mark 
Thomas. There is cut and paste support in var string fields: you may mark 
text parts using the mouse. This text is cut with @{i}A@{ui} @{b}X@{ub} and copied with @{i}A@{ui} 
@{b}C@{ub}. Text from the clipboard can be pasted at the current cursor position 
with @{i}A@{ui} @{b}V@{ub}. These shortcuts are only active if the field is active, i.e. 
the cursor is visible or some text is marked (this also works with 
read-only fields). Otherwise, these shortcuts will invoke other Fiasco 
functions. 

    Relatively big var string fields may slow down record changing. 

    Starting with Fiasco 2.1, the contents of var string fields may be 
displayed as a single line in the list window. Lines breaks in the field 
are converted to spaces for the list window. Note, however, that var 
string fields with a relatively long content may slow down rendering the 
list substantially. You should hide those fields in the list. 

    Since the introduction of var string fields in Fiasco 2.00 till 
Fiasco 2.02 (including) var string fields could not be displayed in the 
list window. If you load databases created with these versions with 
Fiasco 2.1 or higher, the var string fields are marked as hidden in the 
list. To display them, simply deselect the appropriate attribute. 
@endnode 
@node Ft_txt "Text Fieldtype" 
@toc FIELDTYPES

@{b}@{u}Text Fieldtype@{ub}@{uu}

Text fields are not real fields; these fields only serve to put text in 
the mask.  

    This fieldtype supports no standard attributes. 


@{b}Supported Attributes:@{ub}


@{b}Text:@{ub} Will be written in the mask. An underscore ("_") placed before any 
   character will cause the character to be printed underlined. Thus, you 
   may mark the keyboard shortcut of a field. 

@{b}Pen:@{ub} The color used to write the text. The Normal default is black and 
   the Highlight default is white. The colors can be manipulated with the 
   palette prefs editor. 

@{b}Bold:@{ub} Makes the text bold. 

@{b}Italics:@{ub} Makes the text italic. 

@{b}Underlined:@{ub} Underlines the text. 



@{b}Search equivalent:@{ub}

You cannot search for a text field 


@{b}Conversion into a text field:@{ub}

You cannot convert any other fieldtype into a text field. 

@endnode 
@node Ft_but "Button Fieldtype" 
@toc FIELDTYPES

@{b}@{u}Button Fieldtype@{ub}@{uu}

Button fields only serve to put a button in the mask for a user-definable 
action and are not real fields.  This fieldtype only supports the width 
and the shortcut @{"standard attribute" link stdattrs}. 


@{b}Supported Attributes:@{ub}


@{b}Text:@{ub} will be displayed in the button. 

@{b}Type:@{ub} Use @{b}Type@{ub} to choose whether the button will execute a CLI or an 
   ARexx program. CLI programs may be normal programs, commands or 
   scripts (with the "s" attribute). ARexx programs must be ARexx 
   scripts. 

@{b}Command:@{ub} Use @{b}Command@{ub} to select the program that will be executed when the 
   button is activated. 

@{b}Stack:@{ub} You may specify the stack size for the program here. The default 
   is 4096. The program to be activated will crash if the stack size you 
   specify is too small. 

@{b}Console Window:@{ub} lets you specify the I/O stream for the program. It may 
   be a console-window (CON:), the printer (PRT:), a simple file, or, if 
   you don`t want any output NIL:. Since Fiasco 2.1, this is also 
   implemented for ARexx scripts. 



@{b}Search equivalent:@{ub}

You cannot search for a button field 


@{b}Conversion into a button field:@{ub}

You cannot convert another fieldtype into a button field. 

@endnode 
@node Ft_bar "Bar Fieldtype" 
@toc FIELDTYPES

@{b}@{u}Bar Fieldtype@{ub}@{uu}

Bar fields only serve to put a visible separation in the mask and are not 
real fields.  The bar fieldtype supports no standard attributes. 


@{b}Supported Attributes:@{ub}


@{b}Width/Height:@{ub} The width or the height of the bar, depending on @{b}Freedom@{ub}. 

@{b}Freedom:@{ub} determines whether the bar is drawn in the mask horizontally or 
   vertically. 



@{b}Search equivalent:@{ub}

You cannot search for a bar field 


@{b}Conversion into a bar field:@{ub}

You cannot convert another fieldtype into a bar field. 


@{b}Special behaviour in groups:@{ub}

Bar fields are sociable fields, thus several bars in a @{"group" Link Groups}, which touch 
each other (only for technical reasons), will optically join. This 
feature allows you to create boxes with four bars in a square. 

@endnode 
@node Ft_lv "Listview Fieldtype" 
@toc FIELDTYPES

@{b}@{u}Listview Fieldtype@{ub}@{uu}

The listview fieldtype is not a real fieldtype, but a fieldtype modifier. 
 It is currently supported by five fieldtypes: 

·  String 

·  Integer 

·  Float 

·  Date 

·  Time 

To make a field a listview field, you have to activate the @{b}Listview@{ub} 
option in the new field requester. The edit field requester, which may 
have been opened using @{b}Field/Edit Field@{ub} does @{i}not@{ui} allow changing of this 
option, because changing this modifier requires a conversion of the 
field. The @{b}Convert Field@{ub} function does that job. 

    Listview fields may take any number of entries. These entries 
correspond to simple fields. An entry may be activated by clicking on it 
in the list part of the field. The active entry may be edited in the 
gadget below the list part. To add an entry, you have to click on the `+' 
gadget of the field. The `--' gadget removes the active entry. 


@{b}Changed Attributes:@{ub}


@{b}Mask Window/Height:@{ub} The height attribute becomes available when you 
   activate the listview modifier. 

@{b}List Window:@{ub} An active listview modifier makes all list window attributes 
   unavailable, because listviews cannot be displayed in the list window. 

@{b}Initial Content:@{ub} This is the value, which will be inserted into the new 
   added entries. Listviews in new records are always empty. 

@{b}Predefined Values:@{ub} Not applicable. 



@{b}Search Equivalent:@{ub}

You cannot search for a listview field 


@{b}Conversion into a listview field:@{ub}

When you convert a listview field into a listview field of another type, 
each entry of the listview will be converted as described in the 
documentation for the new fieldtype. 

    If you convert a non-listview field into a listview field or 
vice-versa, the `|' character will be used to separate the entries from 
each other. Because this character is not available in numeric fields, 
such conversions do not make much sense (the first number is converted 
though). 


@{b}Special behaviour in groups:@{ub}

Listviews, which have been @{"grouped" Link Groups}, will always activate the entries with 
the same number. Thus, if you activate the second entry in one grouped 
listview, all other listviews in the group will also activate the second 
entry. Furthermore, the add and delete functions of listviews are applied 
to all listviews in a group. 

    If you place grouped listviews directly beneath each other in the 
mask and if the listviews have the same height and the same status of the 
@{b}Read Only@{ub} attribute, these listviews will share their visual appearance. 


@{b}Notes:@{ub}

If you make a listview field too narrow, Fiasco will remove the +/-- 
gadgets to get more space. To get the functionality of these gadgets, you 
may either group the field with another listview field or use the ARexx 
commands @{b}AddLVFieldEntry@{ub} and @{b}DeleteLVFieldEntry@{ub}. 
@endnode 


@node GUI "Fiasco's Graphic User Interface" 
@toc main

@{b}@{u}Fiasco's Graphic User Interface@{ub}@{uu}

Fiasco initially opens with an empty window. You can use the pull down 
menus to work in it. The people who don't like pull down menus may open 
an additional window using @{b}@{"Control/Service Window" link MnServiceWindow}@{ub}. This window makes the 
most important operations accessible via a mouse click. Keyboard 
shortcuts are the third way to execute operations.  
 @{"The Mask Window" link MaskWindow}
 @{"The List Window" link ListWindow}
 @{"The Service Window" link ServiceWin}
 @{"Menus and shortcuts" link AllMenus }
 @{"Requesters" link Requester}


 Fiasco supports menu help. If you press the help key while you browse 
through the menus, a short description will be displayed in an AmigaGuide 
window (This feature requires amigaguide.library, which is part of the OS 
since release 3.0. If you use 2.0 or 2.1, you may get it from the PD). 

    The requesters used by Fiasco have a standard structure. The gadgets 
at the bottom are for responding. Normally, the left one is a positive 
response, while the right one is negative. The close gadget of the window 
is equivalent to a negative response. Nearly all gadgets in the 
requesters may be accessed using the keyboard. Use the @{b}Return@{ub} key for a 
positive response and the @{b}Esc@{ub} key for a negative response. 

@endnode 
@node MaskWindow "The Mask Window" 
@toc GUI

@{b}@{u}The Mask Window@{ub}@{uu}

The operation in the mask window differs in Fiasco's two editing modes. 

@{b}Mask Mode@{ub}

The main control in the mask mode is the cursor. The cursor may be moved 
with the cursor keys. Without any qualifier, pressing a cursor key moves 
the cursor one unit in the direction of the cursor key. If you press a 
cursor key paired with @{b}Shift@{ub}, the cursor will be moved to the appropriate 
end of the window, i.e. if you press @{b}Shift@{ub} and @{b}Cursor right@{ub}, the cursor 
will move to the right border of the window. If you pair a cursor key 
with @{b}Ctrl@{ub}, the cursor will be moved to the extreme position of the mask. 
The cursor right and down keys will move the cursor to the position of 
the last field in that direction, the cursor left and up keys will move 
the cursor to the X position 0 or Y position 0, respectively. 

    If you reach a field with the cursor, it will be activated. 

    If you click any place in the mask with the mouse, the cursor will be 
set to that position. If you click on a field, it will be activated. You 
may select several fields by holding @{b}Shift@{ub} pressed while selecting the 
fields. 

    The selected fields may be dragged using the mouse. Hold the left 
mouse button pressed while moving the mouse. When you release the left 
mouse button the fields will be placed at the point where you have 
dragged them. If you press the right mouse button while dragging the 
fields, the dragging operation will be cancelled, all fields will return 
to their original positions. 

    If you double click on a field the @{"field requester" link RqEditField} for that field 
will be opened. 


@{b}Record Mode@{ub}

In the record mode, all fields in the mask behave much like normal 
gadgets in normal applications. Fields may have a keyboard shortcut. See 
the @{"field documentation" link Fieldtypes} for more information. 

    Furthermore, pressing the tab key in a String, Integer, Float, Date, 
Time, Extern, Datatypes or Var String field will cause the next field to 
be activated. Shift and Tab will activate the previous field. If you 
press Tab when no field is active the first field in the mask will be 
activated. 

    If you prefer using the @{b}Enter@{ub} key to cycle through fields as in 
Fiasco 1.x, you will have to edit the @{"user interface settings" Link RqUserInterface}. 

@{"Mask Stretching" link Stretch}  
@endnode 


@node stretch "Mask Stretching" 
@toc MaskWindow

@{b}@{u}Mask Stretching@{ub}@{uu}

Normally, the Fields in a Fiasco mask are placed very close together. 
This is not very nice and all other "normal" GUIs leave a few pixels 
between the gadgets. It is possible to place one empty line between the 
fields, but this wastes quickly a lot of place. For this reason Fiasco 
makes it possible to leave a few pixels between the gadgets. These values 
may be specified in the @{"options requester" link RqOptions} under Sretch X and Stretch Y. 
The owl stretching (ehhhmm -- mask stretching %-) makes fields bigger 
than specified in the field requesters. This is evident in the lines, 
because most Fiasco fields only expand to this direction. String fields 
may be bigger than the number of chars they can hold. The biggest problem 
are text fields, because their width is normally the minimum required. 
Stretching makes them wider and the text has to be centered. You should 
specify zero as X value to avoid these problems and use one column as a 
separator. In Y direction, 4 is the best value. 
@endnode 
@node ListWindow "The List Window" 
@toc GUI

@{b}@{u}The List Window@{ub}@{uu}

The list window may be opened using @{b}@{"Control/List Window" link MnListWindow}@{ub}. The upper part 
of the list window is the head of the list. It displays the IDs of the 
fields, which are represented by the columns. The lines of the list 
represent the records; the active record is marked with a strong 
backfill. Marked records are displayed with a thin backfill. Fiasco's 
list window displays only those records, which are in the active index. 
The successor of a record is displayed under the record. If you click on 
one record-line, the record will be activated.  However, you must use the 
mask to edit a record. 

    The scroll bars of the window can be used to scroll through the 
contents of it. The vertical scroll bar scrolls through all records, the 
horizontal scrolls trough the fields in the list. 

    The layout of a list, which means position and width of the columns, 
is done automatically. However, you can also control it directly in the 
list window and in the field-requesters in the mask mode. 

    To change the position of a column, you have to click in the middle 
of the column's head. Do not release the mouse button. Two lines will 
appear at the current position of the column. Now you may drag it over 
some other column. If you release the mouse button, Fiasco sets the 
column as near as possible at the new place. Columns, which are 
overlapped by the column, are shifted to the right. The old place of the 
column will be filled by shifting columns right of it to the left. 

    The width of a column may be also changed with the mouse. When you 
click at the right corner of the head of a column and do not release the 
mouse button, a line will appear. You may now drag the line with the 
mouse. The place, where you release the mouse button, will become the new 
right border of the column. The fields right of it will be shifted 
accordingly. You may also use the @{"field requester" link RqEditField} of the field to change 
the width of its column. The attribute @{b}@{"List Window/Width" Link StdAttrs}@{ub} serves for this 
purpose. 

    You may also control, whether a field appears as column in the list, 
or not. Normally, when a field is created, it is automatically added to 
the list. To hide a column, activate the header of a column by clicking 
on it and select the menuitem @{b}@{"List/Hide column" link MnHideColumn}@{ub}. You may also hide it by 
activating the @{b}@{"List Window/Hidden" Link StdAttrs}@{ub} attribute in the field requester. To 
reveal it, use the menuitem @{b}@{"List/Show column" Link MnShowColumn}@{ub} or deactivate the @{b}List 
Window/Hidden@{ub} attribute. 

    The menuitem @{b}@{"List/Show all columns" link mnshowallcols}@{ub} makes all hidden columns visible. 

    @{b}@{"List/Recalc list" link MnRecalcList}@{ub} calculates the positions and dimensions of all 
columns again. You can compare it with @{b}Clean up@{ub} of the Workbench. 
Columns, which have been hidden, are kept hidden. 
@endnode 
@node ServiceWin "The Service Window" 
@toc GUI

@{b}@{u}The Service Window@{ub}@{uu}

The service window may be opened or closed with @{b}@{"Control/ServiceWindow" link MnServiceWindow}@{ub}. If 
you want Fiasco to open the service window on every program startup, 
select the option @{b}Service Window/Open on Startup@{ub} in the 
@{"user interface settings" Link RqUserInterface}. If @{b}Service Window/Fixed Position@{ub} in the same 
requester is inactive, Fiasco will search for a free place on the screen 
when Fiasco opens the window. Otherwise, the position of the service 
window at the time of saving the settings is used. 

    The service window contains these gadgets: 

    @{" Add " link SAdd} @{" Del " link SDel } 


    @{"|<" link SFirst } @{" <" link SPrev} @{"> " link SNext} @{">|" link SLast} 


    @{" <Filename> " link SProj} 


    @{"  <Status>  " link SStat} 


    @{"<Fieldtype> " link SFieldType} 


@endnode 
@node sadd "Add" 
@toc ServiceWin

@{b}@{u}Add@{ub}@{uu}

If the current project is in record mode a new record will be created. If 
mask mode is active a new field will be created.  Equivalent to:
@{b}@{"Record/Add" link MnAddRecord }@{ub} in record mode
resp.
@{b}@{"Field/Add field" link MnAddField }@{ub} in mask mode. 
@endnode 
@node sdel "Delete" 
@toc ServiceWin

@{b}@{u}Delete@{ub}@{uu}

If the current project is in record mode, the current record will be 
removed. If mask mode is active, the current field will be removed. 
@{i}Attention:@{ui} This will normally happen without any security request!  

    Equivalent to:
@{b}@{"Record/Remove" link MnRemoveRecord }@{ub} in record move
resp.
@{b}@{"Fields/Remove Field" link MnRemoveField }@{ub} in mask mode. 
@endnode 
@node sfirst "First" 
@toc ServiceWin

@{b}@{u}First@{ub}@{uu}

If the current project is in record mode, the first record will be 
activated. 

    Equivalent to:
@{b}@{"Record/First" link MnFirstRecord }@{ub} 
@endnode 
@node sprev "Previous" 
@toc ServiceWin

@{b}@{u}Previous@{ub}@{uu}

If the current project is in record mode the previous record will be 
activated. 

    Equivalent to:
@{b}@{"Records/Previous" link MnPrevious }@{ub} 
@endnode 
@node snext "Next" 
@toc ServiceWin

@{b}@{u}Next@{ub}@{uu}

If the current project is in record mode the next record will be 
activated. 

    Equivalent to:
@{b}@{"Records/Next" link MnNext }@{ub} 
@endnode 
@node slast "Last" 
@toc ServiceWin

@{b}@{u}Last@{ub}@{uu}

If the current project is in record mode the last record will be 
activated. 

    Equivalent to:
@{b}@{"Records/Last" link MnLastRecord}@{ub} 
@endnode 
@node sproj "Active project" 
@toc ServiceWin

@{b}@{u}Active project@{ub}@{uu}

The name of the current project is displayed here. If two projects only 
differ in the path and not in the name, the same name will be displayed. 

    You may activate another project by activating the window of a 
project. 

@endnode 
@node sstat "Status" 
@toc ServiceWin

@{b}@{u}Status@{ub}@{uu}

Status information is displayed here. In the record mode:
@{i}number of active record/number of records@{ui}
A @{"Filter" link Filter} may change these numbers. 

    In the mask mode:
@{b}X: @{ub}@{i}X position of cursor@{ui}@{b}, Y: @{i}Y position of cursor@{ui} 

@endnode 
@node sfieldtype "Fieldtype" 
@toc ServiceWin

@{b}@{u}Fieldtype@{ub}@{uu}

If you are in record mode you can select the fieldtype which will be used 
for subsequent calls of @{b}Add Field@{ub}. Equivalent to:
@{b}Fields/Field Type@{ub}. 
@endnode 
@node AllMenus "Menus" 
@toc GUI

@{b}@{u}Menus@{ub}@{uu}

Fiasco has these pull down menus: 
(from left to the right; menus, which are marked with a '/', may be 
activated or deactivated) 

@{b}
  Name                                  Keyboardshortcut
@{ub}
  Project
  @{"New                " link MnNew} @{i}@{b}A @{ui}@{ub}N
  @{"Erase              " link MnErase} @{i}@{b}A @{ui}@{ub}Z
  @{"Open...            " link MnOpen} @{i}@{b}A @{ui}@{ub}O
  @{"Open new...        " link MnOpenNew} @{i}@{b}A @{ui}@{ub} L
  @{"Save               " link MnSave} @{i}@{b}A @{ui}@{ub}S
  @{"Save as...         " link MnSaveAs} @{i}@{b}A @{ui}@{ub}A
  @{"Import...          " link MnInport} @{i}@{b}A @{ui}@{ub}I
  @{"Export...          " link MnExport} @{i}@{b}A @{ui}@{ub}E
  @{"Print...           " link MnPrint} @{i}@{b}A @{ui}@{ub}P
  @{"Hide               " link MnHide} @{i}@{b}A @{ui}@{ub}H
