@node mnnew "Project/New" 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Project/New@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{b}@{I}A @{UB}@{UI} N

Creates a new database project with a mask window. It contains neither 
records, nor fields. You may create a new database or @{b}@{"Open" link MnOpen}@{ub} a saved 
database. 

See also: @{b}@{"Open" link MnOpen}@{ub}, @{b}@{"Open new" link MnOpenNew}@{ub} 
@endnode 
@node mnerase "Project/Erase" 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Project/Erase@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{ui} Z

Erases all data in the current project. The project will be in a status 
like immediately after calling @{b}@{"Project/New" link MnNew}@{ub}. If data have been changed 
since last saving, you will be asked before the data is erased. 

@endnode 
@node mnopen "Project/Open..." 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Project/Open...@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{ui} O

Opens a file requester and loads the selected Fiasco project into the 
current project window. If there are any unsaved data you will be asked 
whether you want to save them first. 
@endnode 
@node mnopennew "Project/Open new..." 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Project/Open new...@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{ui} L

Opens a file requester and loads the selected Fiasco project into an 
automatically created project window. 
@endnode 
@node mnsave "Project/Save" 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Project/Save@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{ui} S

@{b}Save@{ub} writes the data of the current project under the same name to disk. 
If you want to save the project under a different name you have to use @{b}
@{"Save as" Link MnSaveAs}@{ub}. 
@endnode 


@node mnsaveas "Project/Save As..." 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Project/Save As...@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{ui} A

You may save the current project under a new name here. The name will be 
requested using a file requester and will be kept after saving. 
@endnode 


@node mnimport "Project/Import..." 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Project/Import...@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{UI} I

Opens the @{"import requester" Link RqImport}, the GUI interface for the import function of 
Fiasco. You can use import to load data from foreign databases into 
Fiasco. 

@endnode 
@node mnexport "Project/Export..." 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Project/Export...@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{UI} E

Opens the @{"export requester" Link RqExport}, the GUI interface for the export function of 
Fiasco. You can use export to save data in a format which can be read by 
other databases. 
@endnode 
@node mnprint "Project/Print..." 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Project/Print...@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{b}@{i}A @{ub}@{ui} P

Opens the print window, the main interface to Fiasco's @{"print function" Link Print}. 
You may create a layout for printing here and print it. 
@endnode 
@node mnhide "Project/Hide" 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Project/Hide@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{b}@{i}A @{ub}@{ui} H

Closes all windows of the active project. However, the project data will 
not be freed. If the project window was the last open project window, 
Fiasco will close its custom screen or unlock its public screen. An icon 
will be set up on the Workbench. 

    To reopen a project use @{b}@{"Project/Reveal" link mnreveal}@{ub} if another project window is 
still open or double click on the Fiasco icon on the Workbench. Both 
actions will open the @{"reveal project requester" link rqrevealproject} which allows you to choose 
one of the hidden projects to open. 

    Another way to get access to Fiasco is to start Fiasco again. This is 
useful, for instance, when Workbench is not running. Fiasco will open an 
empty project window from which you have access to the @{b}@{"Project/Reveal" link mnreveal}@{ub} 
menuitem. 
@endnode 
@node mnreveal "Project/Reveal..." 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Project/Reveal...@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{b}@{i}A @{ub}@{ui} 

Opens the @{"reveal project requester" Link rqrevealproject} which allows you to choose a project 
hidden with @{b}@{"Project/Hide" link mnhide}@{ub} to be opened again. If you have closed all 
Fiasco windows, you have no access to this menuitem. Therefore, Fiasco 
creates an icon on the Workbench. Doubleclicking on it will result in the 
same function. 

    See also: @{b}@{"Project/Hide" link mnhide}@{ub} 

@endnode 
@node mnabout "Project/About..." 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Project/About...@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{ui} ?

This item shows a requester that displays informations about version, 
copyright and some system internal data. 

@endnode 
@node mnquit "Project/Quit" 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Project/Quit@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{ui} Q

This item closes the current project. If it has been changed and has not 
been saved yet, you will be asked if you want to do this. If this is the 
last open Fiasco project, Fiasco will exit. 

@endnode 
@node mnoptions "Database/Options..." 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Database/Options...@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{ui}  
This menuitem opens the @{"options requester" link RqOptions}, which can be used for editing 
project specific options. That are: 

·  @{"Mask stretching" Link stretch} 

·  Name of author and annotations 

·  project windows 

·  disk access time for reading records 

·  RAM usage of records 

Before Fiasco 2.1, this menu item was in the @{b}Project@{ub} menu. 

@endnode 
@node mnstatistic "Database/Statistic..." 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Database/Statistic...@{ub}@{uu}

no Shortcut

Shows some information about memory usage, etc. for the current project 
in the @{"statistic requester" Link RqStatistic}. 

    Before Fiasco 2.1, this menu item was in the @{b}Project@{ub} menu. 
@endnode 
@node mnindices "Database/Indices..." 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Database/Indices...@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{b}@{i}A @{ub}@{ui} *

Opens the @{"indices requester" Link RqSelectIndex}, which can be used to select, create or 
delete an @{"index" Link Indices}. 

    Before Fiasco 2.1, this menu item was in the @{b}Project@{ub} menu. 
@endnode 
@node mnpreviousactiveindex "Database/Previous active Index" 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Database/Previous active Index@{ub}@{uu}

No Shortcut 

Goes one step back in the @{"index history" Link indexhistory}. That means, that this item 
activates the index that was active before the currently active index was 
activated. To activate this index again, you have to go the step forward 
again with the menu item @{b}@{"Next active Index" link mnnextactiveindex}@{ub}. 
@endnode 
@node mnnextactiveindex "Database/Next active Index" 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Database/Next active Index@{ub}@{uu}

No Shortcut 

Goes one step in the @{"index history" Link indexhistory} forward after is has been gone with @{b}
@{"Previous active Index" link mnpreviousactiveindex}@{ub} backwards. 
@endnode 
@node mnreorganize "Database/Reorganize..." 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Database/Reorganize...@{ub}@{uu}

No Shortcut

This menuitem is similar to @{b}@{"Project/Save" link mnsave}@{ub}. The difference is, that 
@{b}Reorganize@{ub} rewrites the whole database file and deletes all records 
definitely, which are not used in any index of the database. Records, 
which are deleted using the delete functions of Fiasco, are only removed 
from the index, the data will remain until the next reorganization. 
Before Fiasco starts the reorganization, you will be warned with a 
requester, which displays the number of records to be deleted. 

    If there are relations which search for a key defined in these 
records, they will not find it after a reorganization. 

    Before Fiasco 2.1, this menu item was in the @{b}Project@{ub} menu. 

@endnode 
@node mnreloadrels "Database/Reload Relations" 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Database/Reload Relations@{ub}@{uu}

No Shortcut

This item reloads all relations in the current project, just as they were 
loaded while opening the project. This is particularly useful if you have 
deactivated @{b}Update Relations@{ub} in the database settings, changed some keys 
and want to see the result.  Before Fiasco 2.1, this menu item was in the 
@{b}Project@{ub} menu. 

@endnode 
@node mnfunctions "Database/Functions..." 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Database/Functions...@{ub}@{uu}

No Shortcut

Opens the @{"functions requester" Link rqfunctions} that can be used to edit the 
@{"user-defined functions" Link formulafunctions} of the active database. 
@endnode 
@node mnconstants "Database/Constants..." 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Database/Constants...@{ub}@{uu}

No Shortcut

Opens the @{"constants requester" Link rqconstants} that can be used to edit the 
@{"user-defined constants" Link formulaconstants} of the active database. 
@endnode 
@node mnaddrecord "Record/Add Record" 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Record/Add Record@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: +

Adds a new record to the record list of the current project. Each Field 
contains then its @{b}initial content@{ub}, which is normally nothing. If the list 
is open a new line will be inserted. 

    If a @{"Filter" link Filter} is active the new record automatically will be declared 
valid. If you want that new records are filtered correctly you will have 
to rebuild the index. 

    This menuitem may only be selected in @{"record mode" link RecordMode}. 

See also: @{"Record/Remove Record" link MnRemoveRecord} 

@endnode 
@node mnduplicaterecord "Record/Duplicate Record" 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Record/Duplicate Record@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{b}@{i}A @{ub}@{ui} 2

Creates an exact copy of the current record. All @{b}initial content@{ub} 
attributes will be ignored. Even a field with the @{b}Unique Key@{ub} attribute 
will contain the old value. That means that two records with the same 
"unique" key will exist. 

@endnode 
@node mnremoverecord "Record/Delete Record" 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Record/Delete Record@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: -

Removes the active record from the active index. The data of it will 
remain in the database file. To finally delete the record data, no other 
indices may use it. If this is the case, @{b}@{"Project/Reorganize" Link mnreorganize}@{ub} will remove 
the unused record data. 

    To recover the record, you have to create a new index, which uses the 
special entry @{b}«No Index»@{ub} as index source. This index will contain all 
records of the database file. This will not work, if you have used @{b}
@{"Project/Reorganize" link mnreorganize}@{ub}, though. 

    This menuitem may be selected only in @{"record mode" link RecordMode}. 

    If you have selected @{b}Security requesters@{ub} in the user interface 
settings, you will be queried before proceeding. 

See also: @{b}@{"Record/Add Record" link MnAddRecord}@{ub}, @{b}@{"Record/Delete all Records" link mndeleteallrecords}@{ub}, @{b}@{"Project/Reorganize" link mnreorganize}
@{ub} 
@endnode 
@node mndeleteallrecords "Record/Delete all Records" 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Record/Delete all Records@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{UI} \@

Removes all records in the current project. The mask will not be deleted 
by this function. 

    @{b}Record/Delete all Records@{ub} may be only called in record mode. 

    @{i}Note: @{ui}Unlike the functions @{b}Delete Record@{ub} and @{b}Remove Field@{ub}, this 
menuitem does not put up a security requester, if @{b}Security-Requesters@{ub} is 
activated. However, if the project has been changed, Fiasco will put up a 
standard Ok-Save-Cancel-Requester. 

See also: @{"Record/Delete Record" link mnremoverecord} 
@endnode 


@node mncutrecord "Record/Cut Record" 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Record/Cut Record@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{UI} X

Copies the current record to the clipboard and removes it from the active 
index. After that, you may use @{"Record/Paste Record" Link MnPasteRecord} to insert it in the 
project, again. 

    This function may be called only in record mode. 

See also: @{b}@{"Record/Delete Record" link mndeleterecord}@{ub}, @{b}@{"Record/Copy Record" link mncopyrecord}@{ub}, @{b}@{"Record/Paste Record" link mnpasterecord}@{ub}, 
Section Clipboard support of Fiasco 
@endnode 


@node mncopyrecord "Record/Copy Record" 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Record/Copy Record@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{UI} C

Copies the current record to the clipboard. You may use 
@{"Record/Paste Record" link MnPasteRecord} to insert it in the project again. 

    This function may be called only in record mode. 

See also: @{b}@{"Record/Cut Record" link mncutrecord}@{ub}, @{b}@{"Record/Paste Record" link mnpasterecord}@{ub}, Section Clipboard 
support of Fiasco 
@endnode 


@node mnpasterecord "Record/Paste Record" 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Record/Paste Record@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{UI} P

Creates a new record and pastes the contents of the clipboard into that 
record. Normally, you should call @{b}@{"Record/Cut Record" Link MnCutRecord}@{ub} or @{b}@{"Record/Copy Record" Link MnCopyRecord}@{ub} 
before calling this function. 

    This function may only be called in record mode. 

See also: @{b}@{"Record/Cut Record" link mncutrecord}@{ub}, @{b}@{"Record/Copy Record" link mncopyrecord}@{ub}, Section Clipboard 
support of Fiasco 
@endnode 


@node mnprevious "Record/Previous" 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Record/Previous@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{b}Cursor up@{ub}

Activates the record predeceding the current record. If the current 
record is the first one, the display will be "beeped". 

    The order of records is determined by the active @{"index" Link Indices}. 

    The keyboard shortcut correspondents to the structure of the list 
which displays the previous record over the current record. 

    This menuitem may be only selected if @{"record mode" link RecordMode} is active. 

See also: @{b}@{"Next" link MnNext}@{ub}, @{b}@{"First" link MnFirstRecord}@{ub}, @{b}@{"Last" link MnLastRecord}@{ub}, @{b}@{"Goto" link MnGoto}@{ub}, @{b}@{"Find previous" link MnFindPrevious}@{ub} 

@endnode 
@node mnnext "Record/Next" 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Record/Next@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{b}Cursor down@{ub}

Activates the record after the current record. If the current record is 
the last in the list, the display will be "beeped". 

    The order of records is determined by the active @{"index" link Indices}. 

    The keyboard shortcut correspondents to the structure of the list, 
which displays the next record under the current record. 

    This menuitem may be only selected if @{"record mode" link RecordMode} is active. 

See also: @{b}@{"Previous" link MnPrevious}@{ub}, @{b}@{"First" link MnFirstRecord}@{ub}, @{b}@{"Last" link MnLastRecord}@{ub}, @{b}@{"Goto" link MnGoto}@{ub}, @{b}@{"Find next" link MnFindNext}@{ub} 

@endnode 
@node mnfirstrecord "Record/First Record" 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Record/First Record@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{b}Ctrl Cursor up@{ub}

Activates the first record of the current project. 

    The order of records is determined by the active @{"index" link Indices}. 

    This item may be only selected in @{"record mode" link RecordMode}. 

See also: @{b}@{"Next" link MnNext}@{ub}, @{b}@{"Previous" link MnPrevious}@{ub}, @{b}@{"Last" link MnLastRecord}@{ub}, @{b}@{"Goto" link MnGoto}@{ub} 
@endnode 
@node mnlastrecord "Record/Last Record" 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Record/Last Record@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{b}Ctrl Cursor down@{ub}

Activates the last record of the current project. 

    The order of records is determined by the active @{"index" link Indices}. 

    This item may be only selected in @{"record mode" link RecordMode}. 

See also: @{b}@{"Next" link MnNext}@{ub}, @{b}@{"Previous" link MnPrevious}@{ub}, @{b}@{"First" link MnFIrstRecord}@{ub}, @{b}@{"Goto" link MnGoto}@{ub} 
@endnode 
@node mngoto "Record/Goto..." 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Record/Goto...@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{ui} G

Opens the @{"goto requester" link RqGoto} which can be used to activate a record using its 
number. Please note that the record number may be changed by adding or 
deleting records or by using several @{"indices" link indices}. 

    This item can only be selected in @{"record mode" link RecordMode}. 

See also: @{b}@{"Next" link MnNext}@{ub}, @{b}@{"Previous" link MnPrevious}@{ub}, @{b}@{"First" link MnFirstRecord}@{ub}, @{b}@{"Last" link MnLastRecord}@{ub} 

@endnode 
@node mnmarkrecord "Record/Mark Record" 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Record/Mark Record@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{UI} .

Marks the current record. If a record is marked, it will displayed 
highlighted in the list and the character "M" will be displayed in the 
service window. 

    This item can only be selected in @{"record mode" link RecordMode}. 

See also: @{b}@{"Unmark Record" link MnUnmarkRecord}@{ub}, @{b}@{"Mark all Records" link MnMarkAllRecords}@{ub}, @{b}@{"Unmark all Records" link MnUnmarkAllRecords}@{ub} 
@endnode 
@node mnunmarkrecord "Record/Unmark Record" 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Record/Unmark Record@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{UI} :

Deletes the mark of the current record. It won`t be displayed highlighted 
anymore. 

    This item can only be selected in @{"record mode" link RecordMode}. 

See also: @{b}@{"Mark Record" link MnMarkRecord}@{ub}, @{b}@{"Mark all Records" link MnMarkAllRecords}@{ub}, @{b}@{"Unmark all Records" link MnUnmarkAllRecords}@{ub} 
@endnode 


@node mnmarkallrecords "Record/Mark all Records" 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Record/Mark all Records@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{UI} ,

Marks all records in the current project. Note that the previous marking 
of all records will be overwritten. 

    This item can only be selected in @{"record mode" link RecordMode}. 

See also: @{b}@{"Mark Record" link MnmarkRecord}@{ub}, @{b}@{"Unmark Record" link MnUnmarkRecord}@{ub}, @{b}@{"Unmark all Records" link MnUnMarkAllRecords}@{ub}, @{b}@{"Toggle all Marks" link MnToggleAllMarks}
@{ub} 
@endnode 


@node mnunmarkallrecords "Record/Unmark all Records" 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Record/Unmark all Records@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{UI} ;

Clears the marks of all records in the current project. Note that the 
previous marking of all records will be overwritten. 

    This item can only be selected in @{"record mode" link RecordMode}. 

See also: @{b}@{"Mark Record" link MnmarkRecord}@{ub}, @{b}@{"Unmark Record" link MnUnmarkRecord}@{ub}, @{b}@{"Mark all Records" link MnMarkAllRecords}@{ub}, @{b}@{"Toggle all Marks" link MnToggleAllMarks}@{ub} 
@endnode 
@node mntoggleallmarks "Record/Toggle all Marks" 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Record/Toggle all Marks@{ub}@{uu}

No Shortcut

Toggles the marks of all records in the current project. A marked record 
will be unmarked and an unmarked will be marked. You can restore the 
previous marking of the records by calling this menuitem once again. 

    This item can only be selected in @{"record mode" link RecordMode}. 

See also: @{b}@{"Mark Record" link MnmarkRecord}@{ub}, @{b}@{"Unmark Record" link MnUnmarkRecord}@{ub}, @{b}@{"Mark all Records" link MnMarkAllRecords}@{ub}, @{b}@{"Unmark all Records" link MnUnmarkAllRecords}
@{ub} 
@endnode 


@node mnfieldtype "Field/Fieldtype" 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Field/Fieldtype@{ub}@{uu}

Select the current fieldtype in this submenu. It will be used if you 
create fields. The cycle gadget in the @{"service window" Link ServiceWin} has the same 
function.  These fieldtypes are available: 


@{"String    " link FT_Str    } 	 @{b}Ctrl S@{ub} 
@{"Integer   " link FT_Int    } 	 @{b}Ctrl I@{ub} 
@{"Float     " link FT_Float  } 	 @{b}Ctrl F@{ub} 
@{"Boolean   " link FT_Bool   } 	 @{b}Ctrl B@{ub} 
@{"Cycle     " link FT_Cyc    } 	 @{b}Ctrl C@{ub} 
@{"Slider    " link FT_Sld    } 	 @{b}Ctrl S@{ub} 
@{"Date      " link FT_Date   } 	 @{b}Ctrl A@{ub} 
@{"Time      " link FT_Time   } 	 @{b}Ctrl M@{ub} 
@{"Extern    " link FT_Ext    } 	 @{b}Ctrl E@{ub} 
@{"Datatypes " link FT_DT     } 	 @{b}Ctrl D@{ub} 
@{"Var String" link FT_VarString} 	 @{b}Ctrl V@{ub} 
@{"Text      " link FT_Txt    } 	 @{b}Ctrl T@{ub} 
@{"Button    " link FT_Button } 	 @{b}Ctrl U@{ub} 
@{"Bar       " link FT_Bar    } 	 @{b}Ctrl R@{ub} 


@endnode 
@node mnaddfield "Field/Add Field..." 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Field/Add Field...@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{b}Enter@{ub}

Opens the @{"field requester" Link RqEditField} for the current field type and inserts the 
created field at the current cursor position. 

    This item can only be selected in @{"mask mode" link MaskMode}. 

    If there is already a field at the current cursor position nothing 
will be done. 

    Please note that @{b}Enter@{ub} is also shortcut for @{b}@{"Edit active Field" link MnEditField}@{ub}. @{b}Enter@{ub} 
creates a new field, if no field is currently active, otherwise, it opens 
the requester for editing the active field. 

See also: @{b}@{"Edit active Field" link MnEditField}@{ub}, @{b}@{"Edit named Field" link MnEditNamedField}@{ub}, @{b}@{"Edit Relations" link MnEditRelations}@{ub}, @{b}
@{"Remove Field" link MnRemoveField}@{ub} 
@endnode 


@node mneditfield "Field/Edit active Field..." 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Field/Edit active Field...@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{b}Enter@{ub}

Opens the @{"field requester" Link RqEditField} for the selected field. The field requester can 
be used to change several attributes of the field. If certain changes 
would cause the lose of data (e.g. changing @{b}max chars@{ub} of a string field 
to a lower number), you will be informed about the problem and given the 
opportunity to cancel the change. Field types may not be changed this 
way. You have to use @{b}@{"Convert Field" Link MnConvertField}@{ub}. 

    Because this function edits the selected field, you cannot edit 
hidden fields. @{b}@{"Edit named Field" Link MnEditNamedField}@{ub} serves for that purpose. 

    Please note that @{b}Enter@{ub} is also a shortcut for @{b}@{"Add Field" link MnAddField}@{ub}. @{b}Enter@{ub} calls 
@{b}Add Field@{ub} if no field is active and otherwise calls @{b}Edit active Field@{ub}. 

    This item can only be selected in @{"mask mode" link MaskMode}. 

See also: @{b}@{"Edit named Field" link MnEditNamedField}@{ub}, @{b}@{"Add Field" link MnAddField}@{ub}, @{b}@{"Edit Relation" link MnEditRelations}@{ub} 
@endnode 
@node mneditnamedfield "Field/Edit named Field..." 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Field/Edit named Field...@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{b}Shift Enter@{ub}

Opens a requester with a list of all fields. When you have picked one, 
the @{"field requester" Link RqEditField} for the selected field will be opened. The field 
requester can be used to change several attributes of the field. If 
certain changes would cause the lose of data (e.g. changing @{b}max chars@{ub} of 
a string field to a lower number), you will be informed about the problem 
and given the opportunity to cancel the change. Field types may not be 
changed this way. You have to use @{b}@{"Convert Field" Link MnConvertField}@{ub}. 

    This item can only be selected in @{"mask mode" link MaskMode}. 

See also: @{b}@{"Edit active Field" link MnEditField}@{ub}, @{b}@{"Add Field" link MnAddField}@{ub}, @{b}@{"Edit Relation" link MnEditRelations}@{ub} 
@endnode 


@node mnduplicatefield "Field/Duplicate Field" 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Field/Duplicate Field@{ub}@{uu}

No shortcut
Makes an exact copy of the active fields. The fields will be 
placed as near as possible to the original fields. The ID will be @{b}copy_of_@{ub}
@{i}FieldID@{ui}. 
@endnode 
@node mnremovefield "Field/Remove Field" 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Field/Remove Field@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: Del

Removes the selected fields. All data in these fields will be lost. 
Relations or ARexx scripts which refer to these fields will be not 
functional. @{i}Attention: @{ui}The relations or ARexx scripts will not complain 
immediately after removing the fields, but at the first activation. 

    This item can only be selected in the @{"mask mode" link MaskMode}. 

See also: @{b}@{"Edit Field" link MnEditField}@{ub}, @{b}@{"Edit Relations" link MnEditRelations}@{ub}, @{b}@{"Add Field" link MnAddField}@{ub} 
@endnode 


@node mneditrelations "Field/Edit Relation..." 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Field/Edit Relation...@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{ui} &

This item opens the @{"relation requester" Link RqRel}, which adds a @{"relation" Link Relations} to the 
current field. 

    This item can only be selected in @{"mask mode" link MaskMode}. 

See also: @{b}@{"Field/Remove Relation" link mnremoverelation}@{ub} 
@endnode 
@node mnremoverelation "Field/Remove Relation" 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Field/Remove Relation@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{UI} 0

This item deletes all relation information for the active field. The data 
in this field will be written into the normal file. 

    This item can only be selected in @{"mask mode" link MaskMode}. 

@endnode  
@node mncreategroup "Field/Create Group" 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Field/Create Group@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{UI} J

Creates a @{"group" Link Groups} of the active fields. If you have selected a group and 
other fields or groups, these will be joined in one big group. 

    Use @{b}@{"Field/Resolve Group" link mnresolvegroup}@{ub} to make the fields independent again. 

See also: @{b}@{"Resolve Group" link mnresolvegroup}@{ub}, Groups Section 

@endnode 
@node mnresolvegroup "Field/Resolve Group" 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Field/Resolve Group@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{UI} / 

Resolves the active @{"group" link Groups}. All fields of the group will get independent. 
Groups that have been grouped in this group will also be resolved. 

See also: @{b}@{"Create Group" link mncreategroup}@{ub}, Groups Section 
@endnode 


@node mnconvertfield "Field/Convert Field..." 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Field/Convert Field...@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{UI} "

Opens the @{"convert requester" Link RqConvertfield} for the selected field. Using convert you may 
change the type of a field. 

    This item can only be selected in @{"mask mode" link MaskMode}. 

See also: @{b}@{"Add Field" link MnAddField}@{ub}, @{b}@{"Edit Field" link MnEditField}@{ub} 
@endnode 


@node mnhidecolumn "List/Hide column" 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}List/Hide column@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{ui} [

Hides an activated column of the @{"list" link List}. You activate a column by clicking 
in the topmost line of the list which contains the field IDs. After 
hiding a column, the columns at the right side of it will be shifted to 
the left. The column may be made visible again by using @{b}@{"Show column" Link MnShowColumn}.@{ub} 

    This item may only be selected if the list window is open. 

@endnode 
@node mnshowcolumn "List/Show column..." 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}List/Show column...@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{ui} ]

This item opens a requester which may be used to reveal the columns 
hidden with @{b}@{"Hide column" Link MnHideColumn}@{ub}. Fiasco tries to place the columns as near as 
possible at their old positions. 

    This item may only be selected if the list window is open. 

@endnode 
@node mnshowallcols "List/Show all columns" 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}List/Show all columns@{ub}@{uu}

no shortcut

Makes all columns visible, which have been hidden using @{b}@{"Hide column" Link MnHideColumn}@{ub}. 

    This item may only be selected if the list window is open. 

@endnode 
@node mnrecalclist "List/Recalc List" 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}List/Recalc List@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{ui} %

This menuitem calculates all positions and dimensions of the columns in 
the @{"list" link list}. Hidden columns are not revealed. 

    This item can be compared with @{b}Clean up@{ub} of the Workbench. 

    This item may only be selected if the list window is open. 
@endnode 
@node mnfind "Compare/Find..." 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Compare/Find...@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{ui} F

Opens the @{"search requester" Link RqFind} which can be used to define search criterions. 

    This item is only selectable, if the @{"record mode" link RecordMode} is active and if the 
current project contains at least one record. 

See also: @{"search requester" link RqFind}, @{b}@{"Find next" link MnFindNext}@{ub}, @{b}@{"Find previous" link MnFindPrevious}@{ub} 
@endnode 


@node mnfindnext "Compare/Find next" 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Compare/Find next@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{ui} > 

Activates the @{i}next @{ui}record, which matches with the search criterions, 
specified using the @{"search requester" Link RqFind}. You will be informed if no matching 
record is found. 

    This item is only selectable if @{"record mode" link RecordMode} is active and if the 
current project contains at least one record. 

See also: @{"Search requester" link RqFind}, @{b}@{"Find" link MnFind}@{ub}, @{b}@{"Find previous" link MnFindPrevious}@{ub} 
@endnode 


@node mnfindprevious "Compare/Find previous" 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Compare/Find previous@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{ui} < 

Activates the @{i}previous @{ui}record, which matches with the search criteria 
specified with the @{"search requester" Link RqFind}. You will be informed if no matching 
record is found. 

    This item is only selectable if @{"record mode" link RecordMode} is active and if the 
current project contains at least one record. 

See also: @{"Search requester" link RqFind}, @{b}@{"Find..." link MnFind}@{ub}, @{b}@{"Find next" link MnFindNext}@{ub} 
@endnode 
@node mnfilter "Compare/Filter..." 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Compare/Filter...@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{ui} ~ 

Opens the @{"filter requester" Link RqFilter}, which can be used to create @{"filter indices" Link Filter}. 

    This item is only selectable if @{"record mode" link RecordMode} is active and if the 
current project contains at least one record. 
@endnode 


@node mnreplace "Compare/Replace..." 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Compare/Replace...@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{ui} R

Opens the @{"replace requester" Link RqReplace},which can be used for replacing data. 

    This item is only selectable if @{"record mode" link RecordMode} is active and if the 
current project contains at least one record. 

@endnode 
@node mncount "Compare/Count..." 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Compare/Count...@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{ui} #

Opens the @{"count requester" Link RqCount}, which can be used to determine the number of 
the records matching with the specified pattern. 

    This item is only selectable if @{"record mode" link RecordMode} is active and if the 
current project contains at least one record. 

    See also: @{b}@{"Find" link MnFind}@{ub} 
@endnode 
@node mnsort "Compare/Sort..." 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Compare/Sort...@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{ui} =

Opens the @{"sort requester" Link RqSort} which may be used to create a sorted index of 
the active database. 

    This item is only selectable if @{"record mode" link RecordMode} is active and if the 
current project contains at least one record. 
@endnode 


@node mnmark "Compare/Mark..." 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Compare/Mark...@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{B}@{I}A @{UB}@{UI} K

Opens the @{"mark requester" Link RqMark} which can be used to mark specific records that 
match a pattern. 

    Existing marks will be overwritten; marked records will be unmarked, 
if they do not match. 

    This item is only selectable if @{"record mode" link RecordMode} is active and if the 
current project contains at least one record. 

@endnode 
@node mnrecordmode "Control/Record Mode" 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Control/Record Mode@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{b}Ctrl F1@{ub}

This item switches the current project to @{"record mode" Link RecordMode} in which records 
and the contents of records can be changed. If this mode is @{i}active @{ui}, a 
checkmark will be set to the left side of the item. 

See also: @{"record mode" link RecordMode}, @{"mask mode" link MaskMode} 
@endnode 


@node mnmaskmode "Control/Mask Mode" 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Control/Mask Mode@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{b}Ctrl F2@{ub}

This item switches the current project to @{"mask mode" Link MaskMode} in which the @{"mask" link mask} can 
be changed. If this mode is @{i}active @{ui}, a checkmark will be set to the left 
side of the item. 

See also: @{"Mask mode" link MaskMode}, @{"Record mode" link RecordMode} 

@endnode 
@node mnservicewindow "Control/Service Window" 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Control/Service Window@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{b}Ctrl F3@{ub}

This item controls the @{"service window" Link ServiceWin}. If it is checked the service 
window is open. The service window makes the most important record- and 
mask-operations easier and displays some status information. 

    The service window serves globally for all projects. 
@endnode 
@node mnlistwindow "Control/List Window" 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Control/List Window@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{b}Ctrl F4@{ub}

This item controls the @{"list window" link List}, if it is checked, the list is open. 

    Each project may have its own list window. 
@endnode 
@node mnarexxdebug "Control/ARexx-Debug" 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Control/ARexx-Debug@{ub}@{uu}

No Shortcut

This activates a special debug mode of Fiasco for the @{"ARexx interface" link ARexx}. If 
Fiasco commands fail, Fiasco will create a requester that contains more 
detailed information about the error. 

@endnode 
@node mndatabasesettings "Settings/Databases..." 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Settings/Databases...@{ub}@{uu}

No shortcut 

Opens the @{"database settings requester" Link rqdatabasesettings}. You may use this requester to edit 
certain Fiasco database options. 

@endnode 
@node mnuserinterface "Settings/User Interface..." 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Settings/User Interface...@{ub}@{uu}

No shortcut 

Opens the @{"user interface settings requester" Link rquserinterface}, which controls certain 
elements of Fiasco's user interface, such as service window, field 
activation, etc. 
@endnode 
@node mneditum "Settings/User Menu..." 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Settings/User Menu...@{ub}@{uu}

No shortcut 

Opens the @{"user menu requester" Link RqEditUserMenu} which can be used to define user menus. 
@endnode 


@node mndisplay "Settings/Display..." 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Settings/Display...@{ub}@{uu}

no shortcut

Opens the @{"display requester" link rqdisplayopts} which can be used to specify display options 
for Fiasco. You can select whether Fiasco will open its windows on a 
public screen or on its own custom screen. Furthermore, you may select 
fonts for the screen and the mask. 

@endnode 
@node mneditor "Settings/External Programs and Paths..." 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Settings/External Programs and Paths...@{ub}@{uu}

no shortcut

Opens the @{"external programs and paths requester" Link RqEditor} that lets you specify 
programs that may be called by Fiasco and paths for various uses. 
@endnode 
@node mnsavesettings "Settings/Save Settings" 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Settings/Save Settings@{ub}@{uu}

Saves the current program settings in the files "env:fiasco.prefs" and 
"envarc:fiasco.prefs". The settings "survive" rebooting. 
@endnode 
@node mnsavesettingsas "Settings/Save Settings as..." 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Settings/Save Settings as...@{ub}@{uu}

Saves the settings in a file, which has been specified with a file 
requester. If you save the file in "env:", the settings won't survive a 
reboot. If you save them only in "envarc:", they will only become active 
after rebooting because Fiasco searches for its current settings in 
"env:" and nowhere else. 
@endnode 
@node mnloadsettings "Settings/Load Settings..." 
@toc AllMenus

@{b}@{u}Settings/Load Settings...@{ub}@{uu}

Loads and uses a specified settings file. To use them also after reboots 
you should select @{b}@{"Save Settings" link MnSaveSettings}@{ub} to write them to "env:" and "envarc:". 
@endnode 


@node PrintWindow "The Print Window" 
@toc GUI

@{b}@{u}The Print Window@{ub}@{uu}

The print window can be opened with @{b}Project/Print@{ub}. You can control 
Fiasco's print function from there.  More on the print function in the 
@{"print section" link print}.   The print window contains these menus: 

@{b}Menu               Shortcut@{ub}
Project 
@{"Erase           " link PwMnErase }  @{b}@{i}A @{ub}@{ui}Z
@{"Open...         " link PwMnOpen  }  @{b}@{i}A @{ub}@{ui}O
@{"Get from Mask   " link PwMnGetFromMask }  @{b}@{i}A @{ub}@{ui}M
@{"Get from List   " link PwMnGetFromList }  @{b}@{i}A @{ub}@{ui}L
@{"Save            " link PwMnSave }  @{b}@{i}A @{ub}@{ui}S
@{"Save as...      " link PwMnSaveAs }  @{b}@{i}A @{ub}@{ui}A
@{"Print           " link PwMnPrint }  @{b}@{i}A @{ub}@{ui}P
@{"Options...      " link PwMnOptions }  @{b}@{i}A @{ub}@{ui}T
@{"Exit            " link PwMnExit }  @{b}@{i}A @{ub}@{ui}Q

Element
@{"Element Type   »" link PwMnElementType }
        Field      Ctrl F
        Text       Ctrl T
        Formfeed   Ctrl O
@{"Add...          " link PwMnAddElement }  Return
@{"Edit...         " link PwMnEditElement }  Return
@{"Duplicate       " link PwMnDupElement }
@{"Remove          " link PwMnRemElement }  Del

Control
@{"Edit Head       " link PwMnEditHead }  @{b}@{i}A @{ub}@{ui}H
@{"Edit Body       " link PwMnEditBody }  @{b}@{i}A @{ub}@{ui}B
@{"Edit Foot       " link PwMnEditFoot }  @{b}@{i}A @{ub}@{ui}F


 
@endnode 
@node pwmnerase "Project/Erase" 
@toc PrintWindow

@{b}@{u}Project/Erase@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{b}@{i}A @{ub}@{ui}Z 

Removes all elements from the print window. After using this menuitem the 
print window will be empty. 

@endnode 
@node pwmnopen "Project/Open..." 
@toc PrintWindow

@{b}@{u}Project/Open...@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{b}@{i}A @{ub}@{ui}O 

Opens an file requester and reads the print layout from the selected 
file. The old data will be overwritten. 

@endnode 
@node pwmngetfrommask "Project/Get from Mask" 
@toc PrintWindow

@{b}@{u}Project/Get from Mask@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{b}@{i}A @{ub}@{ui}M 

This menuitem tries to fake the project mask's layout in the print 
window. The old print mask will be overwritten. 

@endnode 
@node pwmngetfromlist "Project/Get from List" 
@toc PrintWindow

@{b}@{u}Project/Get from List@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{b}@{i}A @{ub}@{ui}L 

This menuitem tries to fake the list's layout in the print window. The 
old print mask will be overwritten. 

@endnode 
@node pwmnsave "Project/Save" 
@toc PrintWindow

@{b}@{u}Project/Save@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{b}@{i}A @{ub}@{ui}S 

Select @{b}Save@{ub} if you want to write the current print mask to a file on 
disk. This is the file @{i}Project_Name@{ui}@{b}.fpr@{ub}, if you haven't selected another 
using @{b}Open@{ub} or @{b}Save as@{ub}. The file name is displayed in the window title bar 
of the print window. 
@endnode 
@node pwmnsaveas "Project/Save as..." 
@toc PrintWindow

@{b}@{u}Project/Save as...@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{b}@{i}A @{ub}@{ui}A 

Select this menuitem if you want to save the print mask in another file 
as the currently selected. The file name is displayed in the window title 
bar of the print window. 
@endnode 
@node pwmnprint "Project/Print" 
@toc PrintWindow

@{b}@{u}Project/Print@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{b}@{i}A @{ub}@{ui}P 

This menuitem creates the print-out of the project using the active print 
mask. The exact function of this menuitem is dependent on the settings 
made in the @{"print options requester" Link RqPrintOptions}. 

@endnode 
@node pwmnoptions "Project/Options..." 
@toc PrintWindow

@{b}@{u}Project/Options...@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{b}@{i}A @{ub}@{ui}T 

This menuitem opens the @{"print options requester" Link RqPrintOptions}. Some print mask-specific 
options may be edited here. 
@endnode 
@node pwmnexit "Project/Exit" 
@toc PrintWindow

@{b}@{u}Project/Exit@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{b}@{i}A @{ub}@{ui}Q 

This menuitem closes the print window. The active print mask will be 
deleted from memory. 

    You may also use the window's close gadget for this purpose. 
@endnode 
@node pwmnelementtype "Element/Element Type" 
@toc PrintWindow

@{b}@{u}Element/Element Type@{ub}@{uu}

Use this submenu to select the active element type. This type will be 
used by the subsequent @{b}@{"Element/Add" Link pwmnaddelement}@{ub} calls. 

    These element types may be selected:


·  Field @{b}(Ctrl F)@{ub} 

·  Text @{b}(Ctrl T)@{ub} 

·  Formfeed @{b}(Ctrl O)@{ub} 

More information can be found in the @{"print chapter" link print}. 
@endnode 
@node pwmnaddelement "Element/Add..." 
@toc PrintWindow

@{b}@{u}Element/Add...@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{b}Return@{ub}

Creates a new element at the cursor position. The element will be of the 
type set in the @{b}@{"Element/Element Type" Link pwmnelementtype}@{ub} submenu. If the element type 
supports a requester, the @{"element requester" Link RqPrintElement} will appear. 

    More information can be found in the @{"print chapter" link print}. 

    Note that this menuitem has the same shortcut as @{b}@{"Element/Edit" Link pwmneditelement}@{ub}. This 
shortcut will @{b}Add@{ub} if no element is active and @{b}Edit@{ub} if an element is 
active. 
@endnode 
@node pwmneditelement "Element/Edit..." 
@toc PrintWindow

@{b}@{u}Element/Edit...@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{b}Return@{ub}

Opens the @{"element requester" Link RqPrintElement} for the active element. Elements can be made 
active using the mouse or the cursor keys. 

    Note that this menuitem has the same shortcut as @{b}@{"Element/Add" Link pwmnaddelement}@{ub}. This 
shortcut will @{b}Add@{ub} if no element is active and @{b}Edit@{ub} if an element is 
active. 
@endnode 
@node pwmndupelement "Element/Duplicate" 
@toc PrintWindow

@{b}@{u}Element/Duplicate@{ub}@{uu}

No shortcut

Duplicates the active element. 

@endnode 
@node pwmnremoveelement "Element/Remove" 
@toc PrintWindow

@{b}@{u}Element/Remove@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{b}Del@{ub}

Deletes the active element. You may only recover this element using a 
saved version of the print mask. 
@endnode 
@node pwmnedithead "Control/Edit Head" 
@toc PrintWindow

@{b}@{u}Control/Edit Head@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{b}@{i}A @{ub}@{ui}H

Selects the head part of the print mask for editing. The head part will 
be printed before any other data. It may not contain field elements. This 
menuitem, @{b}@{"Edit Body" link mneditbody}@{ub} and @{b}@{"Edit Foot" link mneditfoot}@{ub} are mutually exclusive. 

    See the @{"print chapter" link print} for more information. 

@endnode 
@node pwmneditbody "Control/Edit Body" 
@toc PrintWindow

@{b}@{u}Control/Edit Body@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{b}@{i}A @{ub}@{ui}B

Selects the body part of the print mask for editing. The body part will 
be printed for each record. It may contain references to fields in the 
form of field elements. These references will be substituted while 
printing by the field contents. This menuitem, @{b}@{"Edit Head" link mnedithead}@{ub} and @{b}@{"Edit Foot" link mneditfoot}@{ub} 
are mutually exclusive. 

    See the @{"print chapter" link print} for more information. 

@endnode  
@node pwmneditfoot "Control/Edit Foot" 
@toc PrintWindow

@{b}@{u}Control/Edit Foot@{ub}@{uu}

Shortcut: @{b}@{i}A @{ub}@{ui}F

Selects the foot part of the print mask for editing. The foot part will 
be printed after any other data. It may not contain field elements. This 
menuitem, @{b}@{"Edit Body" link mneditbody}@{ub} and @{b}@{"Edit Head" link mnedithead}@{ub} are mutually exclusive. 

    See the @{"print chapter" link print} for more information. 

@endnode 
@node Requester "All Requesters" 
@toc GUI

@{b}@{u}All Requesters@{ub}@{uu}

Requesters are used by Fiasco to get information required for certain 
operations. Normally, the requesters are created after selecting Fiasco 
menuitem. So called EasyRequesters, which are used by Fiasco to request a 
simple choice are not explained here, because they are generally easy to 
understand and are described in function specific sections. Most 
requesters can be controlled by using the keyboard. The shortcuts, which 
are marked with an underscore, are usually single characters without a 
qualifier. 

    The gadgets at the lower bottom of a requester are usually for 
proceeding. Normally, the left-most is a positive response (Ok), while 
the right-most is a negative response (Cancel). @{b}Enter@{ub} is the shortcut for 
the positive response. The gadget is additionally emphasized. @{b}Esc@{ub} is the 
shortcut for the negative response. 

 @{"Import Requester" link rqimport}
 @{"Export Requester" link rqexport}
 @{"Reveal Project Requester" link rqrevealproject}
 @{"Project Options Requester" link rqoptions}
 @{"Statistic Requester" link rqstatistic}
 @{"Indices Requester" link rqselectindex}
 @{"New/Edit Index Requester" link rqindex}
 @{"Functions Requester" link rqfunctions}
 @{"Constants Requester" link rqconstants}
 @{"Goto Requester" link rqgoto}
 @{"Field Requester" link rqeditfield}
 @{"Popup Gadget Requester" link rqpopupgad}
 @{"Convert Field Requester" link rqconvertfield}
 @{"Relation Requester" link rqrel}
 @{"Formula Requester" link rqeditformula}
 @{"Show Column Requester" link rqshowcolumn}
 @{"Search Requester" link rqfind}
 @{"Filter Requester" link rqfilter}
 @{"Replace Requester" link rqreplace}
 @{"Count Requester" link rqcount}
 @{"Mark Requester" link rqmark}
 @{"Sort Requester" link rqsort}
 @{"Database Settings Requester" link rqdatabasesettings}
 @{"User Interface Settings Requester" link rquserinterface}
 @{"User Menu Requester" link rqeditusermenu}
 @{"Display Settings Requester" link rqdisplayopts}
 @{"External Programs and Paths Settings Requester" link rqeditor}

 @{"Print Options Requester" link RqPrintOptions}
 @{"Print Element Requester" link RqPrintElement}


 
@endnode 
@node rqimport "Import Requester" 
@toc Requester

@{b}@{u}Import Requester@{ub}@{uu}

The import requester is the GUI interface to the @{"import function" Link XPort} of 
Fiasco. Import allows Fiasco to read data from other database programs. 
Usually this cannot be done directly, but the foreign database has to 
"export" the data. You may specify various parameters for importing, so 
you should be able to read nearly all export formats into Fiasco. The 
Fiasco distribution contains several predefined import formats, which can 
be loaded using the @{b}Load@{ub} button at the bottom of the import requester. 

    The values that may be typed in the gadgets of the import requester 
are described in the Import/Export section of this document. 

    
@{b}File:@{ub} Specify here the file that contains the data to import. You may 
   use the picker button at the right side to select it using a file 
   requester.  

@{b}View:@{ub} Click here, if you want to view the contents of the file. Fiasco 
   will start asynchronously More or MultiView, if available.  

@{b}Records/Start:@{ub} Enter the start characters for records here. Default: 
   Empty.  

@{b}Records/End:@{ub} Enter the characters at the end of a record here. Default: 
   Empty.  

@{b}Records/Separator:@{ub} Enter the characters between two records here. 
   Default: @{b}\\n@{ub}.  

@{b}Fields/Start:@{ub} Enter the characters here that fields start with. Default: 
   @{b}"@{ub}.  

@{b}Fields/End:@{ub} Enter the characters here that fields end with. Default: @{b}"@{ub}.  

@{b}Fields/Separator:@{ub} Enter the characters between two fields here. Default: 
   @{b}\\t@{ub}.  

@{b}Misc/Skip Lines:@{ub} Enter introducing characters for remarks here. Default: 
   Empty.  

@{b}Misc/Start skip:@{ub} Enter the number of lines here that will be skipped at 
   the start. Default: @{b}0@{ub}.  

@{b}Misc/Max fields:@{ub} Enter the maximum number of fields in a record here. Can 
   also be used if record separators are missing. Default: @{b}100@{ub}.  

@{b}Options/First record contains IDs:@{ub} Activate this gadget if the first 
   record of the file contains the IDs of the fields in the project. They 
   will be used by Fiasco then instead of generic IDs.  

@{b}Options/Append new fields:@{ub} Activate this, if you want Fiasco to create 
   new fields for your data and not to use existing fields. If you have 
   an entirely empty project you should activate this option. If this 
   option is not active, Fiasco will first try to associate the fields by 
   their IDs. If there are not enough free fields, Fiasco will create new 
   fields nethertheless.  

@{b}Options/Overwrite old project:@{ub} Removes the old data in the current 
   project window. If you do not select this, you data will be appended 
   in some manner to the existing project.  

@{b}Ok:@{ub} Starts the import process. Note that Fiasco may run out of memory due 
   to bad structure parameters and overly large files. Programs that have 
   problems with low memory should not run during this process.  

@{b}Save:@{ub} Saves the current settings in a specified file.  

@{b}Load:@{ub} Reads the settings from a specified file and sets them up in the 
   requester.  

@{b}Cancel:@{ub} Closes the requester without any further action. 


@endnode 


@node rqexport "Export Requester" 
@toc Requester

@{b}@{u}Export Requester@{ub}@{uu}

The export function provides the ability to share data from Fiasco with 
other databases that cannot read the normal format of Fiasco databases. 
See the @{"Import/Export section" link xport} of this document for more information about 
this mechanism. 

@{b}File:@{ub} Specify the name of the file here that the data shall be written 
   to. If a file already exists with this name it will be overwritten.  

@{b}Records/Start:@{ub} Enter the start characters for records here. Default: 
   Empty.  

@{b}Records/End:@{ub} Enter the characters at the end of a record here. Default: 
   Empty.  

@{b}Records/Separator:@{ub} Enter the characters between two records here. 
   Default: @{b}\\n@{ub}.  

@{b}Fields/Start:@{ub} Enter the characters here that fields start with. Default: 
   @{b}"@{ub}.  

@{b}Fields/End:@{ub} Enter the characters here that fields end with. Default: @{b}"@{ub}.  

@{b}Fields/Separator:@{ub} Enter the characters between two fields here. Default: 
   @{b}\\t@{ub}.  

@{b}Options/First record contains IDs:@{ub} Activate this gadget if you want 
   Fiasco to write the field IDs in the first record.  

@{b}Options/Marked records only:@{ub} Activate this gadget if you want Fiasco to 
   write only marked records.  

@{b}Listviews/Entry Separator:@{ub} Enter the characters between two entries of a 
   listview field here. Default: @{b}|@{ub}.  

@{b}Ok:@{ub} Click here to start the export process.  

@{b}Save:@{ub} Saves the structure parameters to a selected file.  

@{b}Load:@{ub} Loads the structure parameters from a selected file.  

@{b}Cancel:@{ub} Closes the requester without any further action. 


@endnode 
@node rqrevealproject "Reveal Project Requester" 
@toc Requester

@{b}@{u}Reveal Project Requester@{ub}@{uu}

This requester is used to reveal a Fiasco project which has been hidden 
using @{b}@{"Project/Hide" Link MnHide}@{ub}. The reveal project requester can be opened using @{b}
@{"Project/Reveal" Link MnReveal}@{ub} or by doubleclicking on the Fiasco Workbench icon. 

@{b}Project:@{ub} This is a list of all hidden Fiasco projects. To reveal a 
   project, select it and click on @{b}Ok@{ub} or doubleclick on it.  

@{b}Ok:@{ub} Closes the requester and opens the selected project.  

@{b}Cancel:@{ub} Closes the requester without any further action. 


@endnode 


@node rqoptions "Project Options Requester" 
@toc Requester

@{b}@{u}Project Options Requester@{ub}@{uu}

The option requester contains project-related settings. It may be opened 
using the menuitem @{b}@{"Database/Options" link MnOptions}@{ub}. 

    
@{b}Author:@{ub} You can use this field to enter your own name! It will be 
   stored at the beginning of the project file.   

@{b}Annotations:@{ub} Yet another gadget for undefined use. You may store any 
   notes here, for example a version string (with $VER: at the 
   beginning). It will be written to the project file just before the 
   author's name.   

@{b}Mask Stretching X / Y:@{ub} These values are added to the width or height of 
   the cursor. The effect of this operation is a stretching of the mask 
   in the X- or Y-direction.  More on stretching @{"here" link stretch}.    

@{b}Windows/Open list on startup:@{ub} Activate this gadget to instruct Fiasco to 
   open the list window when this project is loaded.  

@{b}Windows/List position fixed:@{ub} If this gadget is active, Fiasco remembers 
   the position of the list window when saving the project. The list 
   window will open at this position thereafter.  

@{b}Windows/Mask position fixed:@{ub} If this gadget is active, Fiasco remembers 
   the position of the mask window when saving the project. The mask 
   window will open at this position thereafter.  

@{b}Windows/Close Gadget:@{ub} If this gadget is active, the mask window of this 
   database will have a close gadget, that can be used for closing the 
   database.  

@{b}Windows/Depth Gadget:@{ub} If this gadget is active, the mask window of this 
   database will have a depth gadget, that can be used for 
   depth-arranging the window.  

@{b}Windows/Drag Bar:@{ub} If this gadget is active, the mask window of this 
   database will be draggable on the screen.  

@{b}Windows/Size Gadget:@{ub} If this gadget is active, the mask window of this 
   database will have a size gadget for sizing the window and 
   proportional gadgets for scrolling the contents. Otherwise, the window 
   borders will be thin.  

@{b}Records/Max. time for reading:@{ub} Use this gadget to set the maximum time 
   for disk access when records have to be read from disk. The time is 
   measured in microseconds. 65000 is a good value here. It reads a 
   relatively high number of records and is not disturbing during record 
   changes. Higher values will lead to longer pauses during record 
   changes and more read records. Lower values will make records changes 
   quicker and fewer records will be read. However, Fiasco will always 
   read at least one record (when available).  

@{b}Records/Max. memory:@{ub} Set here the maximum amount of RAM, measured in 
   kilobytes, to be used by this Fiasco database for records. This is 
   only a standard value because Fiasco will not always check the value. 
   Lower values will lead to more disk accesses, because more records 
   will have to be re-read. The default for this is 200. You may control 
   the actual RAM usage in the @{"statistic requester" Link RqStatistic}.  

@{b}ARexx Scripts/Database Startup:@{ub}  An ARexx script specified here will be 
   executed immediately after this database has been opened. Thus, it may 
   serve for initialization purposes, etc. @{i}Note:@{ui} The 
   @{"User Interface Settings" Link rquserinterface} contain a control to disable this setting.  

@{b}ARexx Scripts/Database Shutdown:@{ub}  An ARexx script specified here will be 
   executed before this database will be closed. Thus, it may clean up 
   things, etc. @{i}Note:@{ui} The @{"User Interface Settings" link rquserinterface} contain a control to 
   disable this setting.   

@{b}CD ROM mode:@{ub}  If active, this Fiasco database will be in CD ROM mode. 
   This mode is for better use of Fiasco databases on CD ROMs (or other 
   read only media). It has two effects: All mask fields will be read 
   only and all indices created by the filter and sort functions will be 
   written to @{b}T:@{ub}. The operation of @{b}Save@{ub} and @{b}Save As@{ub} will remain 
   unchanged, in order allow to save a database with @{b}CD ROM mode@{ub} for 
   preparing CD ROM distributions. 


@endnode 
@node rqstatistic "Statistic Requester" 
@toc Requester

@{b}@{u}Statistic Requester@{ub}@{uu}

Apart from getting information, you cannot do much in the statistic 
requester. It only serves to display information about certain 
statistical values of the active Fiasco database. 

@{b}Database:@{ub} The name of the database is displayed here.  

@{b}Index:@{ub} The name of the active index of the database is displayed here. If 
   no index is active, @{b}--@{ub} will be displayed here. This is the case in a 
   newly created database or a database that is still in Fiasco 1.x 
   format.  

@{b}Records on disk:@{ub} This is the number of records in the database file.  

@{b}Records in index:@{ub} This is the number of records in the active index.  

@{b}Added records in RAM:@{ub} This is the number of records that have been added 
   to the database since it was last saved.  

@{b}Disk-loaded records in RAM:@{ub} This is the number of records that Fiasco has 
   read from disk and which are now held in RAM. This value depends on 
   the @{b}Max. memory@{ub} setting in the @{"project options requester" Link RqOptions} and how many 
   records Fiasco has been able to read so far.  

@{b}All records in RAM:@{ub} This is the number of all records in RAM.  

@{b}Changed records in RAM:@{ub} This is the number of records in RAM, which have 
   been changed since the databases was last saved. This includes both 
   disk-loaded records which have been changed and added records (which 
   are always `changed').  

@{b}Deleted records in RAM:@{ub} Even though it sounds paradoxical, this is the 
   number of disk-loaded records which have been deleted since the last 
   saving of the database. Fiasco holds disk-loaded records which have 
   been deleted in RAM in order to be able to modify the index properly 
   during the next saving. Added records, which are deleted later, are 
   not held in RAM by Fiasco.  

@{b}Free RAM:@{ub} This is the total available RAM in bytes.  

@{b}RAM size of one record:@{ub} This is the amount of RAM that is required by one 
   record. This is only an estimated value, because Fiasco uses pools for 
   memory organization.  

@{b}RAM size of all records:@{ub} This is simply the @{b}RAM size of one record@{ub} 
   multiplied with @{b}All records in RAM@{ub}.  

@{b}Flush Records:@{ub} Tries to remove as many records as possible from RAM. 
   Records which are counted under @{b}Added records@{ub}, @{b}Changed records@{ub} or 
   @{b}Deleted records@{ub} cannot be flushed. You will have to save the database 
   before you can flush these.  

@{b}Ok:@{ub} Closes the requester. 



@endnode 
@node rqselectindex "Indices Requester" 
@toc Requester

@{b}@{u}Indices Requester@{ub}@{uu}

The indices requester can be used to select, create new, edit or delete 
@{"indices" Link Indices}. It can be opened with the menuitem @{b}Database/Indices@{ub}. 

@{b}Index Files:@{ub} Select the index here that will be used by the next 
   operation. Initially, the active index will be selected here. This 
   list will be empty if the database has never been saved yet or is 
   still in Fiasco 1.x format. Doubleclicking on one entry will call the 
   @{b}Edit@{ub} function.  

@{b}New:@{ub} Opens the @{"new/edit index requester" Link RqIndex}, which will create a new index 
   when confirmed with @{b}Ok@{ub}.  

@{b}Edit:@{ub} Opens the @{"new/edit index requester" link RqIndex} for the selected index.  

@{b}Delete:@{ub} Deletes the selected index. If the selected index is the last one 
   you will not be able to delete it.  

@{b}Ok:@{ub} Closes the requester and executes mall changes specified in this 
   requester, i.e. new indices will be built, edited indices will be 
   changed and indices, which have been removed from the list will be 
   deleted. The selected index will be made active.  

@{b}Cancel:@{ub} Closes the requester and ignores all changes specified in this 
   requester. The indices will be the same as they were before opening 
   this requester. 



@endnode 
@node rqindex "New/Edit Index Requester" 
@toc Requester

@{b}@{u}New/Edit Index Requester@{ub}@{uu}

This requester is used to specify certain options for @{"indices" Link Indices}. It can be 
opened in two ways: First, by calling @{b}New@{ub} in the @{"indices requester" link RqSelectIndex}. When 
you have opened the index requester this way, it will have additional 
controls for index creation. The second way is to @{b}Edit@{ub} an index in the 
indices requester. 

@{b}Name:@{ub} This gadget is only present in the new index requester. It takes 
   the name of the index to be created.  

@{b}Index Source:@{ub} This gadget is only present in the new index requester. 
   Select an index here to be used as the model for the new index. The 
   new index will contain only the records that the selected index 
   contains. If you don't use @{b}Index Sorting@{ub}, the order of the records 
   will be copied. Thus, if you use neither @{b}Index Sorting@{ub} nor @{b}Index 
   Filter@{ub} a copy of the selected index will be made.  The special entry 
   @{b}«No Index»@{ub} stands for a virtual index which contains all records in a 
   database.  

@{b}Index Filter:@{ub} Clicking on the button will open the @{"filter requester" Link RqFilter} which 
   can be used to specify the criteria which Fiasco will use to decide 
   whether a record should be present in the index or not. This is used 
   when a new index is built and when a new record is added to the 
   database while another index is active and @{b}Automatically add new 
   Records@{ub} is active. In other cases, the filter information is not used, 
   i. e. a record will be always added to the index when it is added 
   while this index is active.  

@{b}Index Sorting:@{ub} Clicking on the button will open the @{"sort requester" Link RqSort}. You 
   may specify by which fields the records of the index will be sorted. 
   Activate the checkbox if you want Fiasco to keep the index sorted. 
   Thus, Fiasco will always take care that after adding or editing 
   records the index is properly sorted.  

@{b}Automatically add new Records:@{ub} Activate this checkbox if you want Fiasco 
   to add all records which are added to the database to this index after 
   applying the @{b}Index Filter@{ub} and @{b}Index Sorting@{ub}. Normally, only records 
   are added to an index if the index was active when the record was 
   added.  

@{b}Ok:@{ub} Accepts the settings made in this requester. However, the settings 
   will first really become active after confirming the @{"indices requester" link RqSelectIndex} 
   with @{b}Ok@{ub}.  

@{b}Cancel:@{ub} closes the requester and ignores the settings. 


@endnode 


@node rqfunctions "Functions Requester" 
@toc Requester

@{b}@{u}Functions Requester@{ub}@{uu}

In the functions requester, you may specify 
@{"user-defined functions for formulas" Link formulafunctions}. The requester may be opened with the 
menu item @{b}Database/Functions@{ub}. 

    @{i}Important Note:@{ui} Recursive programming is not possible with these 
user-defined functions. 

    
@{b}Functions:@{ub} This list shows all functions defined for the active 
   project so far. If you select one, you may edit it with the other 
   gadgets.  

@{b}Name:@{ub} You have to specify the header for a function here. The header is 
   built of the function name and the function arguments enclosed in 
   parenteses. If the function takes no arguments, you have to specify an 
   empty pair of parenteses. Examples: @{b}min(a, b)@{ub} or @{b}recordsum()@{ub}.  

@{b}Definition:@{ub} Takes the definition of the function. This is a normal 
   formula. The arguments specified in the function header may be 
   accessed like normal fields from this formula. Example for function 
   header @{b}min(a, b)@{ub}: @{b}a < b ? a : b@{ub}.  

@{b}New:@{ub} Creates a new function and activates it for editing.  

@{b}Delete:@{ub} Deletes the currently selected function.  

@{b}Ok:@{ub} Checks all function headers and definitions for errors. If no errors 
   were encountered, the new user-defined functions will become active. 
   If there are already formulas defined for the database, you will be 
   asked, whether you want to recompile these formulas.  

@{b}Cancel:@{ub} Closes the requester without any further action. 


@endnode 


@node rqconstants "Constants Requester" 
@toc Requester

@{b}@{u}Constants Requester@{ub}@{uu}

In this requester you may specify @{"user-defined constants for formulas" Link formulaconstants}. It 
may be opened with the menu item @{b}Database/Constants@{ub}. 

    
@{b}Constants:@{ub} This list shows all constants defined for the active 
   project so far. If you select one, you may edit it with the other 
   gadgets.  

@{b}Name:@{ub} You have to specify the name of a constant here. For constants 
   names the same restrictions as for field IDs in formulas apply.  

@{b}Definition:@{ub} Specify here the value for the constant. It may be a numeric 
   value or a string enclosed in qoutes.  

@{b}New:@{ub} Creates a new constant and activates it for editing.  

@{b}Delete:@{ub} Deletes the currently selected constant.  

@{b}Ok:@{ub} Checks all constant names and definitions for errors. If no errors 
   were encountered, the new user-defined constants will become active. 
   If there are already formulas defined for the database, you will be 
   asked, whether you want to recompile these formulas.  

@{b}Cancel:@{ub} Closes the requester without any further action. 


@endnode 


@node rqgoto "Goto Requester" 
@toc Requester

@{b}@{u}Goto Requester@{ub}@{uu}

The goto requester is one of the simplest of all the Fiasco requesters. 
It may be opened with @{b}@{"Record/Goto" link MnGoto}@{ub} and makes it possible to activate a 
record using its number. Please note that record numbers may vary with 
different @{"indices" Link Indices} or after adding or deleting records. 

    
@{b}Record Number:@{ub} Takes the number of the record.  

@{b}Ok:@{ub} Activates the record with the number.  

@{b}Cancel:@{ub} Oh sorry, I just forgot... %-) 


@endnode 


@node rqeditfield "Field Requester" 
@toc Requester

@{b}@{u}Field Requester@{ub}@{uu}

The field requester can be used to change the attributes of a field. Each 
fieldtype has a different field requester because the gadgets of the 
field requester represent the supported attributes of each fieldtype. The 
supported attributes are listed with the @{"documentation of each field" link FieldTypes}. The 
field requester will be opened if you call @{b}@{"Add Field" Link MnAddField}@{ub}, @{b}@{"Edit active Field" Link MnEditField}@{ub} 
or @{b}@{"Edit named Field" Link MnEditNamedField}@{ub} or double-click on a field. 

    If you proceed with @{b}Ok@{ub}, all values will be checked for validity.  If 
one value cannot be used by Fiasco, a requester will explain the problem. 

    @{b}A small summary of the conditions:@{ub} (presuming that these attributes exist)


·  There must be an ID. 

·  @{b}Max Chars@{ub} must be > 0. 

·  Width or height must be > 2. 

If dimension values cannot be used, because other fields are too 
near the field, another requester appears with @{b}Shift@{ub}, @{b}Squeeze@{ub} and @{b}Cancel@{ub} 
gadgets. Cancel does nothing other than return to the field requester. 
@{b}Squeeze@{ub} makes the field fit the selected space. @{b}Shift@{ub} moves the field to 
the left to make it fit. It is not always possible to @{b}Shift@{ub}.  

    If you change an already existing field that stores its contents in 
strings and supports @{b}MaxChars@{ub} (currently @{"String" link FT_Str}, @{"Extern" link FT_Ext} and @{"Datatypes" link FT_DT}), 
an additional control is implemented. If you change @{b}Max Chars@{ub} to a value 
which does not allow to keep all strings in their original length (that 
means, some strings are longer), you will be asked if you want to 
truncate these strings or keep the old value. 

@endnode 
@node rqpopupgad "Popup Gadget Requester" 
@toc Requester

@{b}@{u}Popup Gadget Requester@{ub}@{uu}

This requester sets the options for the popup gagdet field attribute. It 
may be only opened from the field requester with the button @{b}Predefined 
Values@{ub}. 

@{b}Popup Gadget:@{ub} Here you can activate a popup gadget for the field and 
   select its working mode.  

@{b}Predefined Values/Value:@{ub} This list is only active if you have selected 
   @{b}Select predefined value@{ub} at @{b}Popup Gadget@{ub}. Then you may specify values 
   here that can be later selected with the popup button. These values 
   will be also used in the field requester.  

@{b}Predefined Values/New:@{ub} Creates a new entry in the list above. 

@{b}Predefined Values/Delete:@{ub} Deletes the active entry in the list above.  

@{b}ARexx Script:@{ub} This gadget is only active if you have selected @{b}Execute 
   ARexx Script@{ub}. Then you may specify an ARexx script that will be 
   executed when the popup gadget is selected.  

@{b}Ok:@{ub} Accepts the settings.  

@{b}Cancel:@{ub} Closes the requester without any further actions. 



@endnode 
@node rqconvertfield "Convert Field Requester" 
@toc Requester

@{b}@{u}Convert Field Requester@{ub}@{uu}

The convert field requester can be used to change the type of one field 
without the need of an ARexx script. 

@{b}Field ID:@{ub} This text gadget displays the ID of the field that will be 
   converted. Please check here to see if you have called @{b}Convert Field@{ub} 
   for the correct field.  

@{b}Old Type:@{ub} Displays the current type of the field.  

@{b}New Type:@{ub} Select the new type of the field here. Please note that 
   conversions between certain field types may cause a lose of data. 
   Consult the @{"field documentation" link FieldTypes} for more information on this topic.  

@{b}alternative format:@{ub} Select this checkbox to active an output-format which 
   differs from the normal format. Please see the @{"field docs" link FieldTypes} whether this 
   gadget has any effect and if so, what.  

@{b}Ok:@{ub} Starts the conversion and then closes the requester. If the field 
   should be in use by other Fiasco systems, a requester will show you 
   the respective systems and give you the choice to continue and to 
   remove these uses or the cancel the operation.  

@{b}Cancel:@{ub} Simply closes the requester.  


@endnode 


@node rqrel "Relation Requester" 
@toc Requester

@{b}@{u}Relation Requester@{ub}@{uu}

This is the main interface for @{"relation handling" Link Relations} in Fiasco. It may be 
opened using @{b}@{"Field/Edit Relations" link MnEditRelations}@{ub}. 

@{b}Type:@{ub} Set here the type for the relation.  See the @{"relation types" link RelTypes} section 
   for descriptions of the types.   The available types depend on the 
   type of the selected field. The selected type also influences the 
   availability of the other fields as key and real data fields.  

@{b}Local Key:@{ub} Select the key in the current project.  

@{b}Local Real:@{ub} Displays the ID of the field, whose relations are just now 
   edited.  

@{b}Remote Key:@{ub} Use this listview to select the key-field in the project that 
   has been specified under @{b}Related File@{ub}. This listview displays only 
   fields that can contain the key (with same type).  

@{b}Remote Real:@{ub} Use this listview to select the field of the project that 
   has been specified under @{b}Related File@{ub} and which is supposed to be the 
   counterpart of @{b}Real here@{ub}. This field is used to read the Data, which 
   will be displayed in @{b}Real here@{ub}. This listview only displays also 
   fields that look as if they could contain the data (type and max chars 
   must be equal).  

@{b}Related File:@{ub} Select the project file here relative to the directory of 
   the current project which contains the informations.  

@{b}Ok:@{ub} Loads the relations. If any errors occur while loading, the requester 
   will be activated again, otherwise it will return to the main window.  

@{b}Cancel:@{ub} closes the requester without any further action.  


@endnode 


@node rqeditformula "Formula Requester" 
@toc Requester

@{b}@{u}Formula Requester@{ub}@{uu}

This requester serves as a tool for creating formulas for Fiasco. It may 
be opened from the field requester and from the search requester. After 
you have opened it, you may create a formula. When you exit it with @{b}Ok@{ub}, 
the formula will be copied into the calling requester. 

@{b}Operators:@{ub} This listview displays all operators supported by Fiasco. 
   Clicking on one will insert it at the current cursor position in the 
   formula string gadget below.  

@{b}Functions:@{ub} This listview displays all built-in and user-defined 
   functions. As with all listviews in this window, clicking on one 
   function will insert it at the current cursor position in the formula 
   string gadget.  

@{b}Fields:@{ub} Displays all fields of the respective database. Clicking on one 
   field will insert it into the formula.  

@{b}Constants:@{ub} Displays all constants of the database. Clicking on one 
   constant will insert it at the current cursort position in the formula 
   string gadget.  

@{b}Formula string gadget:@{ub} Displays the formula to be edited. You may edit it 
   manually or with the listviews above. Clicking on one entry in any of 
   the listviews will insert it at the current cursor position.  

@{b}Ok:@{ub} Checks the formula for errors. If no errors are found, the formula 
   will be copied into the calling requester and the requester is closed.  

@{b}Cancel:@{ub} Closes the requester without any further action 



@endnode 
@node rqshowcolumn "Show Column Requester" 
@toc Requester

@{b}@{u}Show Column Requester@{ub}@{uu}

This requester, which may be reached with @{b}@{"List/Show column" link MnShowColumn}@{ub}, displays the 
currently hidden columns in the @{"list" link list}. If you select a column and click on 
@{b}Ok@{ub}, that column will be inserted in the list at its old position. 

@{b}Field:@{ub} All hidden columns are displayed here. Select the column here that 
   you want to be revealed.  

@{b}Ok:@{ub} Inserts the column and re-displays the list.  

@{b}Cancel:@{ub} Closes the requester.  


@endnode 


@node rqfind "Search Requester" 
@toc Requester

@{b}@{u}Search Requester@{ub}@{uu}

The search requester is the main interface to Fiasco's @{"search function" Link search}. 
It may be opened with the menu item @{b}Compare/Search@{ub}. However, there are 
many other functions that use the same or a slightly differnt requester. 

@{b}Mode:@{ub} Select here the mode you want to use for searching. Each mode has 
   its own GUI displayed below in the requester. @{b}By Fields@{ub} is the classic 
   mode in which you may specify for fields patterns. @{b}By Formula@{ub} allows 
   you to use a @{"formula" link formulas} to do a search. 

@{b}Name:@{ub} You may specify here a name under which the current search criteria 
   will be stored. With the select button at the right side of the gadget 
   you can later select these criteria again. 

@{b}Mode By Fields:@{ub} 

@{b}Fields:@{ub} This list displays all fields of the active database. Clicking on 
   a field will cause it to be put in the @{b}Search for@{ub} listview below. 
   There you may specify a pattern for the field. 

@{b}Search for:@{ub} Here all the fields are listed which will be searched. When 
   you activate a field here, you may specify a search pattern and other 
   paramters for that field in the gadget group below. To insert a field 
   in this list, simply click on it in the @{b}Fields@{ub} listview. To remove it 
   again, activate it and click on the @{b}Delete@{ub} buttom. 

@{b}Pattern:@{ub} This string gadget takes the @{"search pattern" Link searchpatterns} for the currently 
   selected field in the @{b}Search for@{ub} listview. Clicking on the picker 
   button at the right side of the gadget will open a list with some 
   values that can be used as a pattern. That may be the predefined 
   values, the labels of a cycle field, etc. 

@{b}Delete:@{ub} Removes the currently selected field in the @{b}Search for@{ub} listview. 

@{b}Blurred Search:@{ub} This gadget allows you to activate the @{"blurred search" Link SearchBlurr} and 
   to control the tolerance. 0 searches only for exactly matching 
   entries, 100 searches for almost all entries. 

@{b}Mode By Formula:@{ub} 

@{b}Formula:@{ub} This gadget takes the formula for searching. A record will be 
   considered matching the formula when the formula returns a @{i}true@{ui} value, 
   i.e. a value not equal 0. The picker button at the right side of the 
   gadget opens the @{"edit formula requester" Link Rqeditformula} that helps with creating a 
   formula. 

@{b}Response gadgets:@{ub} 

@{b}Next:@{ub} Initiates the search for the next matching entry and activates it.  

@{b}First:@{ub} Searches for the first matching entry.  

@{b}Previous:@{ub} Searches backwards for the next matching entry.  

@{b}Cancel:@{ub} Closes the requester without any further action.  


@endnode 
@node rqfilter "Filter Requester" 
@toc Requester

@{b}@{u}Filter Requester@{ub}@{uu}

@{"Filters" Link Filter} offer the possibility of creating an overview of a group of 
records. A filter creates the impression of a database that consists only 
of the matching records. Fiasco uses @{"indices" Link Indices} to create a filter. Like the 
@{"sort requester" link RqSort}, the filter requester is used in two contexts. If you open 
the filter requester using @{b}Compare/Filter@{ub}, the filter function will build 
and activate a filtered index according to the criteria set in the filter 
requester. To turn the filter off, select the menu item @{b}
@{"Database/Previous active index" Link mnpreviousactiveindex}@{ub}. Another way would be to select the old 
index in the @{"indices requester" Link RqSelectIndex}. The created index will be based on the 
active index, thus it will only contain records that the active index 
contained and that match the filter criteria. 

    The second way to open the filter requester is by calling @{b}Index 
Filter@{ub} in the @{"new/edit index requester" Link RqIndex}. The filter criteria set here will 
be used only for building the filter index and when @{b}Automatically add new 
Records@{ub} is active, a record is added and another index is active. 

    Because filters use indices which are created once, records added to 
the database while a filter is active will be displayed regardless of 
their contents. The same rules apply to record changes. 

    As the filter requester is almost identical to the @{"search requester" Link RqFind}, 
only the different or new gadgets are explained here. 

    
@{b}Index:@{ub} This gadget is only present if you have opened the requester 
   using @{b}Compare/Filter@{ub}. Enter the name of the index to be created here. 
   If the index already exists the index will be overwritten after you 
   have acknowledged Fiasco's warning.  

@{b}Response gadgets:@{ub} 

@{b}Ok:@{ub} accepts the settings. If the filter requester has been opened with 
   @{b}Compare/Filter@{ub} the index will be built immediately.  

@{b}Cancel:@{ub} closes the requester without any further action.  


@endnode 
@node rqreplace "Replace Requester" 
@toc Requester

@{b}@{u}Replace Requester@{ub}@{uu}

Most parts of the replace requester are the same as in the 
@{"search requester" Link RqFind}. Only the changed or new gadgets are explained in this 
section. 

    The replace requester may be opened with the menu item @{b}@{"Compare/Replace" link mnreplace}
@{ub}. 

    
@{b}Replace/Fields:@{ub} Clicking on one field in this listview will insert it 
   in the @{b}Replace@{ub} listview. This is very similar to the @{b}Fields@{ub} and @{b}Search 
   for@{ub} listviews above.  

@{b}Replace/Replace:@{ub} This listview contains all fields in which a new content 
   will be copied when a matching record is found. To insert a field in 
   this list, click on it in the @{b}Fields@{ub} listview. To remove it again, 
   select it in the @{b}Replace@{ub} listview and click on @{b}Delete@{ub}. While a field 
   is active in this listview, you may edit the replacement settings 
   below.  

@{b}Replace/Mode:@{ub} Use this cycle gadget to either select @{b}Replace by value@{ub} to 
   insert a fixed value in the selected field above of matching records 
   or @{b}Replace by formula result@{ub} to insert a result of a formula.  

@{b}Replace/Replacement:@{ub} You must either enter here a fixed value as 
   replacement or a formula that calculates the replacement. This depends 
   on the setting of the @{b}Mode@{ub} cycle gadget above.  

@{b}Replace/Delete:@{ub} Removes a selected field from the @{b}Replace@{ub} listview.  

@{b}Replace/Confirm:@{ub} If you want to be asked for every replacing operation, 
   you should select this gadget.  

@{b}Response gadgets:@{ub} 

@{b}All:@{ub} Starts the search and scans all records in the active index. If you 
   have selected @{b}Replace/Confirm@{ub}, you are able to select for each 
   matching individually, whether you want to replace the value or not. 
   You may even break the whole search.  

@{b}Next:@{ub} Only replaces the value in the next matching record and activates 
   it.  

@{b}Cancel:@{ub} Closes the requester without any further action.  


@endnode 
@node rqcount "Count Requester" 
@toc Requester

@{b}@{u}Count Requester@{ub}@{uu}

This requester lets you count records, which match with a patterns.  More 
on counting @{"here" link Count}.   You can open this requester using @{b}@{"Compare/Count" Link MnCount}@{ub}. 

    As the count requester is almost identical to the @{"search requester" Link RqFind}, 
only the different gadgets are explained here. 

    
@{b}Response gadgets:@{ub} 

@{b}Ok:@{ub} proceeds and counts the matching records. The number will be 
   displayed at the end.  

@{b}Cancel:@{ub} closes the requester without any further action.  


@endnode 


@node rqmark "Mark Requester" 
@toc Requester

@{b}@{u}Mark Requester@{ub}@{uu}

Fiasco's mark function makes it possible to distinguish specific records. 
The purpose of the mark requester is to mark all records that match a 
specific pattern. The mark requester may be opened with @{b}@{"Compare/Mark" link MnMark}@{ub}. 

    As the filter requester is almost identical to the @{"search requester" Link RqFind}, 
only the different or new gadgets are explained here. 

    
@{b}Response gadgets:@{ub} 

@{b}Ok:@{ub} marks the matching records. The old record marks will be lost!  

@{b}Cancel:@{ub} closes the requester without any further action.  


@endnode 


@node rqsort "Sort Requester" 
@toc Requester

@{b}@{u}Sort Requester@{ub}@{uu}

The sort requester is used for specifying options for sorting a database 
based on fields. @{"Indices" Link Indices} are used by Fiasco to control the order of 
records. The sort requester can be opened in two ways. First, you may 
call @{b}@{"Compare/Sort" link MnSort}@{ub} which allows you to quickly sort a Fiasco database. 
This function builds a new index and activates it. The name of the index 
may be specified in the @{b}Index@{ub} gadget. This index will be based on the 
active index, that means it will contain only those records which the 
active index contains. 

    The other context in which the sort requester is used is the 
@{"index requester" Link RqIndex}. The sort requester will be opened when you click on the 
@{b}Index Sorting@{ub} gadget in the index requester. You may edit the sort 
options for automatic sorting of a particular index here. 

    
@{b}Index:@{ub} This gadget only exists if the requester has been opened with 
   @{b}Compare/Sort@{ub}. This will be the name for the newly created index. If 
   this name already exists the old index will be overwritten. However, 
   Fiasco will warn you in that case before overwriting the index.  

@{b}Fields:@{ub} A list of all fields of the active project is displayed here. 
   Clicking on a field will put it in the @{b}Sort by@{ub} list.  

@{b}Sort by:@{ub} This list displays the fields by which the project will be 
   sorted. The topmost field has the highest priority while sorting, i.e. 
   most data will be sorted according to this field. If there are entries 
   which contain equal data the following fields will be used. Use @{b}Delete@{ub} 
   to remove a field from this list. The arrows can be used to move the 
   field in the list.  

@{b}Descending:@{ub} Select this gadget to sort the data from high values to low 
   values (i.e. Z, Y, X, ..., C, B, A)  

@{b}Use Locale Settings:@{ub} If you select this gadget, Fiasco will use the 
   current locale settings to sort alphabetical data. This will guarantee 
   the correct sorting of national characters like the German umlauts ä, 
   ö, ü, etc. However, please note, that these sorting rules differ from 
   country to country. Thus, a database sorted with one locale country, 
   may be sorted incorrectly if you change the country.  

@{b}Ok:@{ub} accepts the settings. If the sort requester has been opened with 
   @{b}Compare/Sort@{ub}, the index will be immediately built.  

@{b}Cancel:@{ub} Closes the requester without any further action.  


@endnode 


@node rqdatabasesettings "Database Settings Requester" 
@toc Requester

@{b}@{u}Database Settings Requester@{ub}@{uu}

You may control certain database related functions of Fiasco here. This 
requester may be opened by using @{b}@{"Settings/Databases" link MnDatabaseSettings}@{ub}. It replaces some of 
the @{b}Settings@{ub} menuitems of Fiasco 1.2. 

@{b}Relations/Write Relations:@{ub} If this option is active, Fiasco will also 
   write @{"relations" link Relations} back in their "there" projects. Otherwise, changes 
   made in these fields will be lost. This option should be only active 
   if @{b}Update Relations@{ub} is also active, or when you always call @{b}
   @{"Project/Reload Rels" Link MnReloadRels}@{ub} before saving. Otherwise you risk overwriting data 
   in the "there" project by invalid data in some fields of the "here" 
   project.  

@{b}Relations/Update Relations:@{ub} This checkbox determines whether @{"relations" link Relations} 
   are updated immediately after the input of a new key. This requires 
   disk accesses which may become annoying if Fiasco has to read the data 
   from a floppy disk. If you deactivate this checkbox you should also 
   deactivate @{b}Write relations@{ub}, because there may be invalid data in the 
   project which would be written into the "there" file. If you want to 
   see the changes, you can update the relations using @{b}@{"Project/Reload Rels" Link MnReloadRels}
   @{ub}.  

@{b}Miscellaneous/Use `*' as Synonym for `\#?':@{ub}  Select this option to 
   activate the support of the asterisk as a valid search pattern. The * 
   then has the same meaning as #?.  

@{b}Ok:@{ub} Closes the requester and accepts the changes made in it.  

@{b}Cancel:@{ub} Closes the requester and ignores any changes. 


@endnode 
@node rquserinterface "User Interface Settings Requester" 
@toc Requester

@{b}@{u}User Interface Settings Requester@{ub}@{uu}

This requester allows you to control certain parts of Fiasco's user 
interface. It may be opened using @{b}@{"Settings/User Interface" link mnuserinterface}@{ub}. It replaces 
some of the @{b}Settings@{ub} menuitems of Fiasco 1.x. 

@{b}Service Window/Open on Startup:@{ub}  If this checkbox is checked the 
   @{"service window" Link ServiceWin} will be opened automatically when Fiasco is started.  

@{b}Service Window/Fixed Position:@{ub}  Activate this option to make Fiasco open 
   the service window in a given position. Otherwise, Fiasco will search 
   for a free place on the screen to open the service window.  

@{b}ARexx Scripts/Program Startup:@{ub}  An ARexx script specified here, will be 
   automatically executed after Fiasco has been started.  

@{b}ARexx Scripts/Program Shutdown:@{ub}  An ARexx script specified here, will be 
   automatically executed before Fiasco will be shut down.  

@{b}ARexx Scripts/Database specific startup/shutdown scripts:@{ub}  You may 
   control here, wether startup and shutdown scripts specified in the 
   @{"project options" Link rqoptions} should be executed or not. Such scripts may be 
   specified locally for each database. @{b}Execute automatically@{ub} always 
   executes these scripts, @{b}Ask before executing@{ub} opens a requester before 
   executing, which leaves you the choice, whether you want to execute 
   the script. @{b}Execute never@{ub} does not execute these scripts.  

@{b}Miscellaneous/Create Icons:@{ub} If this option is active, Fiasco will create 
   icons while saving projects.  

@{b}Miscellaneous/Speech:@{ub} Activate this option if you want Fiasco to use the 
   narrator.device to "speak" certain messages.  

@{b}Miscellaneous/Ask for database when started empty:@{ub}  If active, Fiasco 
   will open a file requester whenever it is started and no databases 
   were given to be loaded (either by project icons or by specification 
   on the command line).  

@{b}Miscellaneous/Security Requesters:@{ub}  If this checkbox is active, Fiasco 
   will warn you before deleting any fields or records. This can prevent 
   the erroneous deletion and loss of data.  

@{b}Miscellaneous/Cycle trough fields with Enter:@{ub} Activate this option to 
   instruct Fiasco to activate the next field when one field has been 
   left by pressing @{b}Enter@{ub}. This conforms to the Fiasco 1.x usage. 
   Starting with Fiasco 2.0, you may use the @{b}Tab@{ub} key to cycle through the 
   fields.  

@{b}Miscellaneous/Automatically activate first field:@{ub}  If this option is 
   active, Fiasco will automatically activate the first field when a new 
   record is selected.  

@{b}Ok:@{ub} Closes the requester and accepts the changes made in it.  

@{b}Cancel:@{ub} Closes the requester and ignores the changes. 


@endnode 
@node rqeditusermenu "User Menu Requester" 
@toc Requester

@{b}@{u}User Menu Requester@{ub}@{uu}

Fiasco has the ability to create own menuitems and to put CLI programs or 
ARexx scripts behind them. The defined items also may be selected with 
the F-Keys as well as with the mouse. F1 to F10 correspond to the first 
ten items, Shift and F1 to F10 correspond to the items 11 to 20. If you 
want to define more than 20 items, you will have to select the additional 
items with the mouse. Furthermore, Intuition limits the number of 
definable items to 63. 

    The items defined in this requester may be saved using @{b}
@{"Settings/Save Settings" Link MnSaveSettings}@{ub}. 

    
@{b}Items:@{ub} This is the list of all existing menu items. You can @{b}Add@{ub} one 
   item and @{b}Del@{ub}ete one. < and > serve to change the position of the item 
   in the menu.  

@{b}Type:@{ub} allows you to indicate whether the item will call a program or an 
   ARexx script.  

@{b}Command:@{ub} Specify the program or the ARexx script here that will be 
   executed. 


@endnode 


@node rqdisplayopts "Display Settings Requester" 
@toc Requester

@{b}@{u}Display Settings Requester@{ub}@{uu}

This requester controls the display elements of Fiasco. You can open your 
own screen for Fiasco and choose the fonts for the custom screen and for 
the mask. 

@{b}Screen/Screentype:@{ub} Select here, whether you want to use a public screen 
   or an own custom screen.  

@{b}Screen/PubScreen Name:@{ub} Specify here the name of the public screen, you 
   want Fiasco to open its windows on. This has only effect, if you 
   select @{b}PublicScreen@{ub} for @{b}Screentype@{ub}. If you leave this gadget empty, 
   Fiasco will use the default public screen.  

@{b}Screen/Screen Mode:@{ub} You may select the display mode here for the custom 
   screen. Clicking on the popup gadget will open an ASL screenmode 
   requester. This requires asl.library version 38 or higher.   

@{b}Screen/Screen Font:@{ub} This gadget controls whether you want to use a custom 
   font for the custom screen or the Workbench screen font which is 
   controlled by the Font Preferences.  

@{b}Screen/Custom Font:@{ub} If you want to use a custom font for the custom 
   screen, you may select it here.  

@{b}Mask Font/Mask Font:@{ub} This gadget controls whether you want to use a 
   custom font for the mask or the system default font which is 
   controlled by the Font Preferences.  

@{b}Mask Font/Custom Font:@{ub} You may select a custom font for the mask here. It 
   must be fixed width.  

@{b}Images/New look proportional gadgets:@{ub} Activate this option to get 
   proportional gadets in the mask in "new look".  Proportional gadgets 
   are used for slider fields and for the scrollbars of datatypes, var 
   string and listview fields. Instead of the black bars, new look 
   proportional gadget will be white bars with a black border at the 
   right and at the bottom, which makes them to appear raised.  

@{b}Ok:@{ub} Proceeds with resetting the display of Fiasco. If required, a new 
   screen is opened and so on.  

@{b}Cancel:@{ub} Closes the requester without any further action. 


@endnode 


@node rqeditor "External Programs and Paths Requester" 
@toc Requester

@{b}@{u}External Programs and Paths Requester@{ub}@{uu}

This requester can be used to edit the settings related to external 
programs, that Fiasco may call and the settings related to extenal paths. 

@{b}Programs/Editor Program:@{ub} Specify your favourite editor program here. You 
   may specify a @{b}%s@{ub} here, which will be replaced with the file name to be 
   edited. The program should start synchronously. With programs like 
   GED, that normally start asynchronously, you should specify the 
   respective arguments in order to stop the program to start that way. 
   For GED this would be the argument @{b}sticky@{ub}.  

@{b}Programs/Editor Program/Stack:@{ub} Specify the stack for the editor program 
   here. It should be normally greater than or equal 4000 bytes.  

@{b}Programs/Text Viewer Program:@{ub} Takes your text viewer program. This may be 
   @{b}More@{ub}, @{b}Most@{ub} or @{b}Multiview@{ub}.  

@{b}Programs/Text Viewer Program/Stack:@{ub} Specify the stack for the text viewer 
   program here. It should be normally greater than or equal 4000 bytes.  

@{b}Paths/Fiasco Path for Icons:@{ub} The path specified here will be saved as 
   default tool in Fiasco database icons. Thus, clicking on a Fiasco 
   database icon will start the program specified here. Example: 
   @{b}Work:Fiasco/Fiasco@{ub}  

@{b}Paths/Default Database Directory:@{ub} Specify here the default path for 
   databases. The file requesters will search for databases relative to 
   this directory.  

@{b}Ok:@{ub} Closes the requester and accepts the changes made in it.  

@{b}Cancel:@{ub} Closes the requester and ignores the changes.  



@endnode 
@node rqprintoptions "Print Options Requester" 
@toc Requester

@{b}@{u}Print Options Requester@{ub}@{uu}

The print options requester can be opened using @{b}Project/Options@{ub} in the 
print window. You may control some options for printing here. See the 
Print section for more information on printing. The settings which have 
been made here may be saved using the menuitems @{b}Project/Save@{ub} and 
@{b}Project/Save as@{ub} of the print window. 

    
@{b}Print to:@{ub} Fiasco's print function writes its data to this file. If 
   you want to use conventional printing, you should specify @{b}PRT:@{ub} for the 
   printer here.  

@{b}Print with ARexx:@{ub} Activate this gadget if you want Fiasco to call the 
   ARexx script with the name @{b}ProgDir:ARexx/ARexxPrint.rexx@{ub} after writing 
   the file. Fiasco will call the script with the file name specified in 
   @{b}Print to@{ub} as its argument. In a standard Fiasco installation, this 
   script calls TeX to compile the file into a DVI file and prints this. 
   However, you may change the script to something completely different. 
   If you use @{b}Print with ARexx@{ub}, you must not specify @{b}PRT:@{ub} in @{b}Print to@{ub}. A 
   temporary file, e.g. @{b}T:FiascoPrint@{ub}, would be the best.  

@{b}Only marked records:@{ub} If you activate this gadget the print function will 
   print only records with a mark. 


@endnode 
@node rqprintelement "Print Element Requester" 
@toc Requester

@{b}@{u}Print Element Requester@{ub}@{uu}

You can control several options of a print element in the print window 
with this requester. It appears when you add with @{b}Element/Add@{ub} or edit 
with @{b}Element/Edit@{ub} an element. The layout of a requester depends on the in 
@{b}Element/Type@{ub} selected element type.  See the @{"print" link print} section on more 
information about elements.   


@{b}Field Elements:@{ub}


@{b}Field:@{ub} Select here the field, whose data will be inserted at the position 
   of the print element. 

@{b}Width:@{ub} The width of the print element in the print mask. 

@{b}Height:@{ub} The height of the print element in the print mask. Only available 
   for var string fields or listview fields. 

@{b}Clip:@{ub} If this checkbox is active, the data of the field will be clipped 
   if they would be larger than the size of the print element. If it is 
   not active, the size of the print element will be extended to show all 
   data. If neccessary, other elements will be shifted to the right or -- 
   if the element needs more vertical space -- down. 

@{b}Style/Bold:@{ub} If selected, the field data will be printed in bold face. 

@{b}Style/Italics:@{ub} If selected, the field data will be printed in italics. 

@{b}Style/Underlined:@{ub} If selected, the field data will be printed underlined. 
   Note: The @{b}Bold@{ub}, @{b}Italics@{ub} and @{b}Underlined@{ub} effect is generated by escape 
   sequences. It is not compatible with printing by TeX. 

@{b}Style/Justification:@{ub} You may select here, whether the contents of the 
   element will be justified to the left or right border or will be 
   centered in the element. Default: Left. If @{b}Clip@{ub} is not active, Fiasco 
   may fall back to left justification when the field contents exceed the 
   element borders. 



@{b}Text Elements:@{ub}



    
@{b}Text:@{ub} The text for the element. The width of the element is adjusted 
   to the length of the text. 

@{b}Style/Bold:@{ub} If selected, the text will be printed in bold face. 

@{b}Style/Italics:@{ub} If selected, the text will be printed in italics. 

@{b}Style/Underlined:@{ub} If selected, the text will be printed underlined. Note: 
   The @{b}Bold@{ub}, @{b}Italics@{ub} and @{b}Underlined@{ub} effect is generated by escape 
   sequences. It is not compatible with printing by TeX. 



@{b}Response Gadgets:@{ub}



    
@{b}Ok:@{ub} Acceppts the settings. If certain settings are not possible or 
   need to be adjusted, you will be notified about that. 

@{b}Cancel:@{ub} Ignores all changes. 

There is no requester for formfeed elements. 

@endnode 
@node FORMULAS "Formulas" 
@toc main

@{b}@{u}Formulas@{ub}@{uu}

Starting with release 2.1, Fiasco supports formulas. Formulas can be used 
to calculate the content of fields automatically or to do complex 
searches. Formulas for fields may be specified in the @{"field requester" Link rqeditfield}, 
formulas for searches in the @{"search requester" Link rqfind}. From both requesters you 
have access to the @{"edit formula requester" Link rqeditformula}. This requester can be used as 
tool for creating formulas. A formula may look like this: 

    @{b}floor(price * vat / 100) + price@{ub} 

    The parts a formula is built of are described in the following 
sections. 

 @{"Constant Values" link formulavalues}
 @{"Fields" link formulafields}
 @{"Constants" link formulaconstants}
 @{"Operators" link formulaoperators}
 @{"Functions" link formulafunctions}

 @{"Function Reference" link funcref}


 
@endnode 
@node formulavalues "Constant Values" 
@toc Requester

@{b}@{u}Constant Values@{ub}@{uu}

Constant values are defined directly in the formula. In the formula above 
the @{b}100@{ub} is a definition of a constant numeric value. You can also define 
strings as constant values by specifying the string in double quotes. For 
example: @{b}"Test String"@{ub}.  

    In Fiasco formulas, strings and numbers are exchangable. Whenever a 
number is required and a string is available, the string will be 
converted to a number. The reverse is also true when a string is required 
and only a number is available. 

    Rules for constant values also apply to the following elements of 
formulas that "return" some values. Figuratively speaking, an element of 
a formula that has returned a value during calculation, is replaced by 
the returned value. 

    The final result of a formula is, from that point of view, the value 
that has finally been returned. 


@{b}Boolean Values@{ub}

The boolean values "true" and "false" as used in logical operations are 
represented in Fiasco formulas by numbers. Numbers not equal zero 
represent a true value, zero represents "false". 

@endnode 
@node formulafields "Fields" 
@toc Requester

@{b}@{u}Fields@{ub}@{uu}

Fields in this context are references to fields in the database and are 
replaced during the calculation by the content of the field in the 
current record. If the content of a field in the formula of another field 
is changed, the formula will be recalculated automatically. Fields appear 
in formulas like variables in normal, mathematical formulas. A field in 
the example above is @{b}price@{ub}. The contents of fields of the types 

·  String 

·  Date 

·  Time 

·  Extern 

·  Datatypes 

·  Var String 

are returned as strings, the contents of the remaining field types 
are returned as numbers. Cycle fields return the number of the selected 
label and boolean fields return a 1 for a checked field and a 0 for an 
unchecked field. Fields have to be specified using their IDs in the 
formulas. To be recognized as fields, the field IDs may not begin with 
numbers and may not contain spaces. 

    The elements of listview fields can be addressed with square brackets 
after the field ID containing the number of the element to be used. The 
number of the entry has the base 0, thus the first entry has the index 
number 0, the second 1, etc. @{b}namelist[5]@{ub} for example, represents the 
sixth entry in the listview field with the ID @{b}namelist@{ub}. 

@endnode 
@node formulaconstants "Constants" 
@toc Requester

@{b}@{u}Constants@{ub}@{uu}

Constants have the same appearance as fields in Fiasco formulas. The 
difference is that they are globally defined values that are equal for 
the whole database. The @{"constants requester" Link rqconstants} can be used to define new 
constants. @{b}vat@{ub} could be a constant in the example. 
@endnode 
@node formulaoperators "Operators" 
@toc Requester

@{b}@{u}Operators@{ub}@{uu}

Operators are the symbols that define the most important mathematical or 
logical operations. An operator normally requires two operands that have 
to be placed at both sides of the operator. Some operators require only 
one or three operands. Operators in the example above are @{b}*@{ub}, @{b}/@{ub} and @{b}+@{ub}. 
Furthermore, operators in Fiasco formulas have evaluation priorities. 
Operations with operators of higher priority are calculated before 
operations with operators of lower priority. The order rule stating that 
multiplications or divisions be performed before additions is an example 
of operator priority. 

    See the table for the operators currently supported by Fiasco. 

+-----+----------+--------------------------+----------------------+---------------------+
| Pri | Op.      | Description              | Syntax               | Result              |
+-----+----------+--------------------------+----------------------+---------------------+
|  10 | !        | Logical not              | ! boolvalue          | boolean value       |
|   9 | ^        | Power                    | number ^ exponent    | number              |
|   8 | *        | Multiplication           | 4 * 4                | number              |
|     | /        | Division                 | 10 / 2               | number              |
|   7 | +        | Addition                 | 2 + 3                | number              |
|     | -        | Subtraction              | 5 - 1                | number              |
|   6 | <        | Less than                | value1 < value2      | boolean value       |
|     | >        | Greater than             | value1 > value2      | boolean value       |
|     | <=       | Less than or equal       | value1 <= value2     | boolean value       |
|     | >=       | Greater than or equal    | value1 >= value2     | boolean value       |
|   5 | ==       | Equal                    | value1 == value2     | boolean value       |
|     | !=       | Not equal                | value1 != value2     | boolean value       |
|   4 | &&       | Logical and              | bool && bool         | boolean value       |
|     | ||       | Logical or               | bool || bool         | boolean value       |
|   3 | ? :      | cond. (see below)        | bool ? expr. : expr. | result of one expr. |
|   2 | numentries() number of entries in lv| numentries(fieldid)  | integer number      |
|     | active() | active entry of listv.   | active(fieldid)      | integer number      |
|     | sum()    | sum of listv. (see below)| sum(fieldid[,s][,e]) | number              |
|     | current()| current entry (see below)| current()            | integer number      |
+-----+----------+--------------------------+----------------------+---------------------+


  

@{b}Conditional Operator@{ub}



    The conditional operator is a short version of the @{b}if-else@{ub} construct 
in normal programming languages. If you are familiar with the programming 
language `C' you should already know that operator. 

    The operand before the question mark should result in a boolean 
value. If the value is true (i. e. non-zero) the operator will be 
replaced by the result of the expression after the @{b}?@{ub} and before the @{b}:@{ub}. If 
the boolean value is false (i. e. equal to zero) the expression after the 
: will be used. 

    A formula that returns the larger one of two numbers would look like 
that: 

    @{b}a > b ? a : b@{ub} 

    Of course, you can use several conditional operators in a formula. A 
formula that determines the sign of a number would look like this: 

    @{b}n > 0 ? "Positive" : n < 0 ? "Negative" : "Zero"@{ub} 

    If @{b}n@{ub} is greater than 0, the string @{b}Positive@{ub} will be returned by the 
formula. If this is not true, @{b}n@{ub} will be tested, whether it is less than 
0. If this is true, the string @{b}Negative@{ub} will be returned. If this is not 
true the number must be @{b}Zero@{ub}. 


@{b}Listview Sum Operator@{ub}

The operator @{b}sum()@{ub} can be used to calculate the sum of entries in a 
listview field. Regardless of the type of the field, Fiasco will try to 
sum up the data as numbers. The simple syntax of @{b}sum()@{ub} requires only the 
field ID of the field to be summed, for example @{b}sum(prices)@{ub}. You may, 
however, also specify the entry at which summing should be started in a 
second argument and the entry at which the calculation should be ended in 
a third argument. The numbers of the entries must be specified -- like 
accessing single entries of listviews with square brackets -- on base 
zero, thus the first entry is entry 0, and so on. For example, 
@{b}sum(prices, 2, 4)@{ub} adds the third, fourth and fith entries of the listview 
field with the ID prices. 


@{b}Current Entry Operator@{ub}

The operator @{b}current()@{ub} can be only used within formulas, which are used 
to calculate the values of a listview field. It returns the number of the 
entry, which is currently calculated by this formula. This number is on 
base zero. Thus, if the first entry of a listview is currently 
calculated, @{b}current()@{ub} will return @{b}0@{ub}. 

    This way, you are able to calculate a value across grouped listview 
fields. An example is an invoice in which the single item price and the 
number of items is specified in grouped listview fields and the price of 
the ordered number of items is to be calculated: 

    @{b}singleprice[current()] * itemnumber[current()]@{ub} 

@endnode 
@node formulafunctions "Functions" 
@toc Requester

@{b}@{u}Functions@{ub}@{uu}

Functions are defined by the function name and the arguments of the 
function enclosed in parenteses. If a function has no arguments an empty 
pair of parenteses has to be specified, nethertheless. A function may 
take some arguments, do some calculations on them and return a new value. 
This value will be used for the further calculations. In the example 
above, @{b}floor()@{ub} is a function. It takes only one argument. The argument is 
the result of the calculation @{b}price * vat / 100@{ub}. For a list of all 
built-in functions of Fiasco,   see the @{"function reference" link funcref}.  Beneath the 
built-in functions of Fiasco, the user may also define own functions, 
based on other formulas. Thus, you may define a function with the name  

    @{b}min(a, b)@{ub} 

    that does the following: 

    @{b}a < b ? a : b@{ub} 

    This function determines what number is the smallest and returns it. 
If you have defined this function in the @{"function requester" Link RqFunctions} you can use 
it in all formulas of the particular database. 

    As calls to user-defined functions are internally resolved before 
calls to built-in functions, you may replace a built-in function by a 
user-defined function with the same name. 

    Essentially, you can change the name of a built-in function by simply 
redirecting the call with a user-defined function. If you defined a 
function with the name 

    @{b}length(a)@{ub} 

    to do 

    @{b}strlen(a)@{ub} 

    you can use a function named @{b}length()@{ub} that does the same as the 
function @{b}strlen()@{ub}. 

    Note:
recursive programming. Better not try it! 
@endnode 
