@node AREXX "The ARexx Port" 
@toc main

@{b}@{u}The ARexx Port@{ub}@{uu}

ARexx is a macro programming language capable of connecting different 
programs. ARexx has been developed by William S. Hawes and has been part 
of the system software since OS 2.0.  

    The ARexx port of Fiasco may be accessed externally from a script or 
ARexx scripts can be called by Fiasco. For example: you can specify an 
ARexx script in the command attribute of a button and then click on the 
button -- this script is then executed and may do certain operations. 

    For Fiasco 2.1, Fiasco's ARexx port has been completely revised to be 
more powerful and style guide compliant. ARexx scripts written for Fiasco 
1.x or 2.0x, will continue to work, though. "Old" scripts may be 
recognized with the command @{b}Address FIASCO@{ub} at the beginning of the script 
and the commands with the prefix @{b}F_@{ub} before the Fiasco commands. The old 
commands are no longer documented. See the 2.0x versions of this document 
for documentation of these commands. Please also note, that you cannot 
mix old and new scripts. Fiasco ARexx scripts must use either completly 
the new commands or completely the old commands. 

    Scripts that conform to the new standard do not address the port with 
the name @{b}FIASCO@{ub}. The new ARexx port assigns for each database an own 
ARexx port. The names of the ports are @{b}FIASCO.@{ub}@{i}n@{ui}, where @{i}n@{ui} is a number. If 
the script is directly started by Fiasco (e.g. by clicking on a button) 
the script will be addressed automatically to the ARexx port of the 
corresponding database. Thus, no additional @{b}Address@{ub} command is required. 
More about accessing Fiasco's ARexx port   in the section 
@{"Accessing the Port" link ArexxAccess}.  

    Nearly all operations that can be used with Fiasco's GUI can be used 
with the ARexx commands. Additionally, Fiasco's functions may be extended 
with ARexx. There are many ARexx commands which perform exactly the same 
as their GUI "brothers". In other words, certain commands may open a 
requester under certain conditions. There are also commands which always 
open a requester. 

 @{"Style Conventions" link ARexxStyle}
 @{"Accessing the Port" link ARexxAccess}
 @{"Arguments of Commands" link ARexxArgs }
 @{"Results of Commands" link ARexxResults }
 @{"Debugging ARexx Scripts" link DebuggingARexxScripts}

 ARexx Command Reference
  @{"by alphabet" link ARexxCmds }
  @{"by function" link ARexxFuncInd }


 
@endnode 
@node ARexxStyle "Style Conventions" 
@toc AREXX

@{b}@{u}Style Conventions@{ub}@{uu}

This section documents some stylistic conventions for Fiasco ARexx 
scripts. Many are not required, even though they are recommended. 

    ARexx allows to chose an own suffix for application specific scripts. 
For Fiasco 2.1 ARexx scripts, the suffix @{b}.frx@{ub} should be used instead of 
@{b}.rexx@{ub}. 

    Fiasco ARexx scripts should always lock Fiasco's GUI with the command @{b}
@{"LockGUI" link rxlockgui}@{ub} to avoid any influences by the user. Thus, the ARexx script 
should have extensive error checking to avoid the case that the script 
was stopped because of an error and the user is locked out of Fiasco's 
GUI. The script @{b}dummy.frx@{ub} of the Fiasco distribution contains already all 
neccessary checking and can be used as basis for new ARexx scripts.   

@endnode 
@node ARexxAccess "Accessing the Port" 
@toc AREXX

@{b}@{u}Accessing the Port@{ub}@{uu}

As of Fiasco 2.1, ARexx scripts started by Fiasco are already addressed 
to the ARexx port of the Fiasco database from that the script has been 
started. Thus, you do not need to worry about the name of the ARexx port 
you have to access. If you want to address an ARexx script to the ARexx 
port of another program, and later return to Fiasco's ARexx port, two 
techniques are available: 

    If you address the script to another ARexx port, you may later use 
the command @{b}Address@{ub} without any arguments to return to the previously 
active ARexx port, which was, if the script was started by Fiasco, the 
port of a Fiasco database. For example: 

/* A script that was started by Fiasco */

Address MULTIVIEW.1

/* Do something with MultiView */

Address

/* You are now addressed to Fiasco again */


 Another way is to save the name of the active ARexx port in a variable 
and to later use @{b}Address@{ub} with that variable to return to the original 
port. You have to use @{b}Address Value@{ub} @{i}Variable@{ui} to make ARexx recognize that 
you have specified a variable name and not a literal port name. The 
advantage is that you may address several ports before going back to the 
original port. The other method forgets about the Fiasco port after the 
second @{b}Address@{ub} @{i}Port@{ui} command. For example: 

/* A script that was started by Fiasco */

fiasco_port = address()

Address MULTIVIEW.1

/* Do something with MultiView */

Address Value fiasco_port

/* You are now addressing Fiasco again */


 The script @{b}dummy.frx@{ub} of the Fiasco distribution already initializes a 
variable with the name @{b}fiasco_port@{ub} to the correct ARexx port. 


@{b}Getting the Port of the active Project@{ub}

If you want to start a Fiasco 2.1 ARexx script from outside Fiasco, e.g., 
by double clicking on a project icon with @{b}rx@{ub} as default tool, the script 
has to search for the port of the active Fiasco database. 

    This can be done this way: 

/* Get a list of all available ports */

ports = show("Ports")

/* Search for a port of Fiasco */

do i = 1 to words(ports)

    if abbrev(word(ports, i), "FIASCO.") then
    do
        /* A port of Fiasco has been found.
         * Now query Fiasco to return the port
         * name of the active database.
         */

        Address Value word(ports, i)

        GetAttr Project Name Active ARexx

        Address Value Result

        break
    end
end


 This procedure is already part of the script @{b}dummy.frx@{ub}. 

@endnode 
@node ARexxArgs "Arguments of Commands" 
@toc AREXX

@{b}@{u}Arguments of Commands@{ub}@{uu}

Fiasco interprets the data after the command as arguments or parameters. 
Fiasco uses @{b}ReadArgs()@{ub} of the dos.library to parse the parameters. Thus, 
the same argument conventions used by CLI commands apply to Fiasco. 
Arguments are separated by white spaces. If single arguments are supposed 
to contain spaces, simply enclosing them in quotation marks does not 
work. This is because ARexx swallows all quotation marks. To avoid this 
you should enclose quotation marks within additional, single quotation, 
e.g. @{b}Open ' "Test File" '@{ub}.  You have to use the single quotation marks in 
the outer position because Fiasco (@{b}ReadArgs()@{ub}) can only handle double 
quotation marks. Be sure not to use variables inside of any quotations. 
To use them you have to close the outer quotation, write the variable and 
open the quotation again, if required. These issues do not apply for 
arguments which have the /F modifier.  @{"Results of Commands" link ARexxResults}  

@endnode 
@node ARexxResults "Results of Commands" 
@toc AREXX

@{b}@{u}Results of Commands@{ub}@{uu}

If a command returns a value, this is normally stored in the variable 
@{b}Result@{ub}. To use @{b}Result@{ub}, you have to put the line @{b}Options Results@{ub} at the 
beginning of a script.  The script @{b}dummy.frx@{ub} already does that. A value 
returned in @{b}Result@{ub} may be also redirected to another variable. To do 
that, you have to specify the argument @{b}Var@{ub} followed by the name of the 
variable with the arguments of the command. @{i}Note:@{ui} If you call commands 
with the same @{b}Var@{ub} argument in sequence and you do not specify the 
argument in quotes, ARexx will replace at the second command the variable 
name by the result of the first command. Commands that return more 
complex results return them as stem variables. If you use such commands, 
you have to specify a name for the variable to be set. If the command 
returns a list of a variable number of items, the values of the items 
will be returned in @{i}stem@{ui}@{b}.1@{ub} . . . @{i}stem.n@{ui}. @{i}stem@{ui}.count will contain the 
number of items returned. 

    Fiasco only returns a result in the case of success. Success is 
indicated by the variable @{b}rc@{ub}, which is always set after the execution of 
a command. 0 means success, 5 is -- by definition -- a warning, 10 an 
error and 20 a fatal failure. 

    Starting with Fiasco 2.0, Fiasco supports a special ARexx variable 
named @{b}FIASCO.LASTERROR@{ub}, which will be set on failure of a Fiasco ARexx 
command. 

    The error codes that may be returned by Fiasco are documented in   
the appendix @{"Error Codes" link errorcodes}.  

    The ARexx command @{b}@{"Fault" Link rxfault}@{ub} can be used to convert an error code into 
human-readable text. 

@{"Debugging ARexx Scripts" link DebuggingARexxScripts}  

@endnode 
@node DebuggingARexxScripts "Debugging ARexx Scripts" 
@toc AREXX

@{b}@{u}Debugging ARexx Scripts@{ub}@{uu}

Fiasco has additional features to make debugging of ARexx scripts as easy 
as possible. Whenever a Fiasco command fails to work, Fiasco will return 
in the variable @{b}rc@{ub} a number not equal zero. Furthermore, the special 
variable @{b}Fiasco.LastError@{ub} will be set to a Fiasco error code. If you use 
error signals, the ARexx script may catch the error and display a 
comfortable requester with the error using Fiasco's ARexx port. An 
example for this is the script @{b}dummy.frx@{ub} in the Fiasco distribution. 

    One step further goes the ARexx-Debug function of Fiasco. You can 
activate that function by selecting the menu item @{b}@{"Control/ARexx Debug" link MnARexxDebug}@{ub}. 
Whenever now a Fiasco ARexx command fails, Fiasco will suspend the 
execution of the ARexx script and display a requester that explains the 
error, shows the correct command template and gives you the possibility 
to open the AmigaGuide help for the ARexx command. This is done if you 
click on @{b}Help@{ub}. The other buttons @{b}Continue@{ub} and @{b}Ignore Error@{ub} continue the 
script, while @{b}Continue@{ub} sets @{b}rc@{ub} to the error code and @{b}Ignore Error@{ub} sets @{b}rc@{ub} 
to zero, making the script assume, that the command has worked 
successfully. 

@endnode 
